@wordwrap
@remark (header)
///   jobs                                                //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-JOBS "ASense - General: Available jobs"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT MAIN
@{b}@{u}Currently available jobs@{uu}@{ub} - support the ASense by developing it.

    Skilled, but pennyless people who wish to work for their registration
  are offered to earn their registration by helping to develop the ASense.

  @{u}Currently required are@{uu}:

  - @{b}bugfinders@{ub} - @{i}@{b}one module per bug is offered@{ub}@{ui}; thus to fully register you
    only need to find seven bugs (or less for partial registration). There
    are always some bugs left in every software, please try to find them!

  - @{b}translators@{ub} - only those with rich vocabulary and solid grammar skills
    of their own language would be accepted.

      @{b}Translations of both GUI and documentation would be required@{ub}.

      Whenever an upgrade is released, it would be free of charge to those
    who update the translated docs to their own language.
      @{i}Translators may be offered to maintain the translations in exchange
    for free upgrades@{ui}.Alternatively, someone else may do the updating...

      Please @{"contact" link ASENSE-GENERAL-CONTACT} me before you start.

  - @{b}coders@{ub} - for porting the ASense to other platforms (@{i}MacOS@{ui} in particular).

      You would be given a bunch of specific Amiga functions to replace with
    native ones from the other OS in order for the GUI to be created.Original
    coding is done in C language.

      If you successfuly port the ASense, @{b}a percentage from the sales would
    be offered as a reward@{ub}, depending on the amount of your contribution to
    the project.

      Please @{"contact" link ASENSE-GENERAL-CONTACT} me if you think that you are skilled enough.

  - @{b}webmasters@{ub} - to maintain and develop a web site devoted to ASense.

  - @{b}designers@{ub} - to create different font sizes/types/styles from the available
    ones in order for ASense to maintain it's look on different screen sizes.

    @{i}This job is the simplest one, but it requires some artistic talent@{ui}.

  - @{b}distributors@{ub} - to sell ASense for percentage of profit. @{b}15% is offered@{ub}.
    (If you can't afford to buy the ASense, find several people who can, and
     you'll get your version for free! Find more, and you'll earn some money!)
     Remember, @{i}@{b}every fully registered piece of ASense sold by you, is going
     to get you a module or two@{ub}@{ui}, but @{i}@{b}only if you can sell at least 7 pieces@{ub}@{ui}!

@endnode
///
///   Protection                                          //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-PROTECTION "ASense - General: Protection"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-GENERAL-UNIQUENESS
@{b}@{u}Protection@{uu}@{ub}: Measures to prevent piracy.

    In order to prevent piracy, a very sophisticated approach has been taken.
  There are several @{b}categories of pirates@{ub} with entirely different motivation.
  Each of the categories must be handled separately in order for protection
  to be efficient.Here they are:

  1. @{b}Pennyless paupers@{ub} - People from poor countries with low income can't
  afford to buy commercial software at western prices, but they still need
  the software.Therefore, they have to use pirated software, as it is the
  only option for them.The governments of poor countries are aware of that.
  Hence, the piracy is being tolerated by them.
    @{b}If you are a @{i}pennyless pauper@{ui}, you may purchase the ASense @{i}partially@{ui}@{ub}
  (only selected features).@{b}Alternatively, you may @{"work" link ASENSE-GENERAL-JOBS} for your registration@{ub}.

  2. @{b}Casual users@{ub} - People who wish to use a piece of software seldomly and/or
  for very simple tasks, are usually unwilling to buy the full version of a
  commercial software, even if they have the money.Why to buy a car if one
  lives on an island that can be crossed on foot in about 15 minutes? Just
  to help the car industry? I don't think so.No, they won't.
    @{b}Demo version of the ASense probably offers enough functionality for a
  casual user@{ub}.If so, they don't need to register.However, @{b}if some of the more
  advanced features is required by a casual users, then one should know that
  the ASense may be purchased @{i}partially@{ui}@{ub}@{b}@{ub} (only selected feature(s)), @{b}with
  just a fraction of an already low @{"price" link ASENSE-GENERAL-UPGRADES 21} of the fully registered version@{ub}.

  3. @{b}'@{i}Can't pay@{ui}' people@{ub} - Some people are unable, or unwilling, to make a
  payment through one of the @{"supported methods of payment" link ASENSE-GENERAL-UPGRADES 100}, but they still
  want to use the registered version.
    These people may @{"work" link ASENSE-GENERAL-JOBS} for their registration.This may require some skills,
  though.

  4. @{b}Hackers@{ub} - Some extremely skilled people like to crack the software just
  for the sake of an intelectual exercise and amusement.
    Something like solving a crossword puzzle.
    @{b}To quench their need for intelectual chalenges, there is a special piece
  of code '@{"mystery.c" link ASENSE-PROTECTION-MYSTERY_C}'.It is a legal and harmless strict ANSI C code, although
  it looks like a gargoyle.It compiles without errors and produces a nice
  christmas greeting song when executed.Amazing, indeed@{ub}.
    @{i}The first one who sends an explanation (in great detail) of how does this
  code does what it does, would receive a fully registered version of ASense
  as an honorary reward@{ui}.

  5. @{b}Crackers@{ub} - Plain common thieves with computer skills without scruples.
  They crack the software in order to sell it on low price as it is their own.
    They cater for some of the groups above, which make their market.

  6. '@{b}Spreaders@{ub}' - Those who legaly buy a piece of software and then 'share'
  it with their friends. This is also an act of piracy! Although it may seem
  mild (every spreader makes only 1 or few copies), this activity inflicts a
  heavy reduction on a number of legaly sold pieces of software. One should
  spread only a DEMO version, but not the fully (or partialy) registered one.

  To prevent @{i}crackers@{ui} and @{i}spreaders@{ui} from their activity, a number of measures
  has been taken:
  1. @{b}Every registered piece of ASense is@{ub} @{"guaranteed-to-be-unique" link ASENSE-GENERAL-UNIQUENESS}, which means
     that there is only one such piece in existance, protected by a @{i}keyfile@{ui}
     which only the end user should have.For more details follow the link.
  2. Registered pieces of ASense are delivered to users securely @{"encrypted" link ASENSE-UPGRADES-MESS-FILES}.
  3. @{b}There are rewards for those who find and report a pirated ASense@{ub}.
  4. @{b}There are hidden algorithms which will encourage people to report@{ub}
     (and to register) @{b}a pirated piece of ASense@{ub}.@{i}Numerous, versatile and
     interconnected@{ui}.Remove some, some will remain to activate eventually.
     The last piece of code defence may deliberately sabotage the results.

  NOTE: @{b}Under NO circumstancies, even if under '@{i}piracy alert@{ui}', the ASense
  would NEVER intentionally mess with your computer, not even by grabbing
  the resources!@{ub} It would politely remove itself from memory if required.
@endnode
