///
///   Uniqueness                                          //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-UNIQUENESS "ASense - General: Uniqueness"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GENERAL-PROTECTION
@NEXT MAIN
@{b}@{u}Guarantee of Uniqueness@{uu}@{ub}:

    @{b}Whenever you order a 'copy' of the ASense, it is @{i}guaranteed@{ui} that you
  will receive a completely unique 'copy'@{ub}.The whole content of the ASense
  executable file will be severely different from one 'copy' to another.
  However, @{b}all@{ub} of them would @{b}stem from identical sources, and would behave
  @{i}identically@{ui}@{ub}.

    Moreover, a 'copy' of the ASense which you receive would be protected
  by a 'keyfile', which is actually any file on your computer that you have
  selected during a registration process to become your '@{i}ASense.keyfile@{ui}'.
  The md5 and other checksums of that file will be computed and sent as a
  part of an order.The ASense would @{i}require@{ui} a file with these checksums to
  be present in order to work properly.You are the only one who has this
  file (if you have selected some unique one), and the only one who knows
  which file is the keyfile for the 'copy' of ASense that you have bought.
  This prevents me (the author) of selling multiple copies of ASense and
  then accusing someone for piracy.I can't do that because I don't have
  the keyfiles... (And I can't make them either.)

    Nevertheless, if someone spreads the registered 'copy' of the ASense,
  with a personaö keyfile or cracked to worked without it, sooner or later
  this is going to be discovered (@{b}rumors spread quickly, but pirated files
  are even faster@{ub}).It is always going to be possible to find out whose
  'copy' has been pirated.Every ASense is completely @{i}unique@{ui} and contains
  multiple number of independent hidden registration numbers just for this
  purpose.The trail of piracy would then be easy to trace to its origin.
    The person who did it will then have some explaining to do.@{b}So beware@{ub}!

    @{i}Even if you hack it / crack it / change it, it will still be possible
  to recognize it.There are *many* independent hidden silent registration
  numbers placed throughout the code to ensure its uniqueness, apart from
  the fact that the code is also byte-by-byte severely different from one
  'copy' to another.Nevertheless, if anyone ever alters the ASense beyond
  recognition, it will refuse to work or worse, it will continue to work,
  but will silently sabotage the results by randomly putting small or not
  so small, hardly detectable changes into resulting planetary positions@{ui}.

  NOTE: @{b}Under NO circumstancies, even if under '@{i}piracy alert@{ui}', the ASense
  would NEVER intentionally mess with your computer, not even by grabbing
  the resources!@{ub} It would politely remove itself from memory if required.
@endnode
