///
///     Known bugs                                        //f
@node ASENSE-HISTORY-BUGS "ASense - History: Known bugs"
@TOC ASENSE-GENERAL-HISTORY
@PREV ASENSE-HISTORY-VERSIONS
@NEXT ASENSE-HISTORY-TODO
@{b}@{u}Known bugs@{uu}@{ub}:

  - none.

@{b}@{u}Unimplemented features with buggy appearance@{uu}@{ub}:

  - @{i}@{b}The Chiron has a significantly tailward extended orb, as it is a comet@{ub}@{ui}.
    This is not yet tackled, neither by ASense, nor by anyone else.
    It would be soon...

  - @{b}Influence of distances on orbs@{ub} is unstudied and thus unimplemented.

  - @{b}When a body rises on WEST@{ub} (on extreme north, the Moon may do that rarely),
    @{b}the ASense gets confused@{ub}.Angle crossing times would be messed up in this
    case.Note that handling of this obscure case is more of an '@{i}unimplemented
    feature@{ui}' than a real bug...

@{b}@{u}Features which may look like bugs@{uu}@{ub}:

  - Speeds of objects are from their @{i}@{b}true@{ub}@{ui} positions, not from the @{i}apparent@{ui} ones.
    This makes an error of < 0.3"/day in @{i}speeds@{ui} ONLY, but considerably increases
    the speed of computations, since it removes the neccesity to add another
    layer of planetary computations (30% time saved). Positions are accurate.

  - @{b}If you boot without locale.library present, install the locale.library
    afterwards and then start the ASense @{i}without rebooting first@{ui}, the time
    zone value would be (probably) incorrect@{ub}, because the @{i}locale@{ui} preferences
    were not loaded into system. (The ASense will @{b}NOT@{ub} attempt to load them.)
      The @{i}locale@{ui} preferences are installed during the startup by the @{b}IPrefs@{ub}
    command, called by the startup-sequence if the @{i}locale@{ui}.library is installed.
    After a reboot, everything is going to be fine and will stay as such.
    (@{i}If you don't have the locale.library at all, the ASense will either ask
    for the missing data or use the one supplied by the @{"TIME_ZONE" link ASENSE-GENERAL-TOOLTYPES} tooltype@{ui}.)

  - @{i}@{b}Centers of bodies are always used during the calculation of house posotions,
    and never their limbs@{ub}@{ui}.This is a @{i}feature@{ui}, not a bug!
      (Consequently, if the ASense tells you that the Sun is in the 12th house,
    although it hasn't yet (completely) risen, this is only because you chose
    that the appearance of Sun's lower limb marks the moment of rising.)

  - @{i}@{b}If there isn't any required horizon crossing during the given time interval,
    the ASense displays the current position of the body, in relation to the
    horizon@{ub}@{ui} ('UP', 'ABOVE', 'DOWN', 'BELOW').Note that the body may cross the
    horizon on the other side of the meridian during the given day, and thus
    not necessarily maintain a described position throughout the entire day.

  - @{b}Absence of a precession corrected house positions is a feature@{ub}!

  - @{b}@{"Swap houses" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1 48} calculated for the same time (same ecliptic), but a
    different location, differ if topocentric coordinates are required@{ub}.
    House positions for such houses are incorrect if the zodiacs differ in 2
    charts.The errors depend on the difference between the involved zodiacs.
    To avoid this, do not mix different zodiacs during swap house analysis.

  - @{b}If an object transits over the same angle twice during the same day,
    only one of these transits is found@{ub} (there is no room on display for
    both of them).Change the initial time or the requested time frame to
    find the other crossing time if it is necessary.
      This feature does NOT affect the calculation of house position for
    the Altitude house system, which takes care of the order of appearance
    of meridian transits.

  - As a consequence of merging process, @{b}THE COALESCED NODES ARE NOT OPPOSITE
    TO EACH OTHER@{ub} (i.e. @{i}@{b}they can be anywhere, and even conjunct each other@{ub}@{ui}!).

  - @{b}When the houses get flipped, the placements of Arabic Parts change too@{ub}, if
    they depend upon the positions of the angles or house cusps.This is @{b}because
    a direction of the order of houses gets reversed@{ub}.(In order for it to remain
    consistent with it's own definition).This is @{i}feature@{ui}, not a bug.

@{b}@{u}Bugs in third party software used by ASense@{uu}@{ub}:

  - @{b}There is a bug in amigaguide.library v39.3 (at least), which causes a
    memory leak of 48 bytes every time when the library is opened@{ub}.This is
    a system bug, unrelated to ASense.
      Furthermore, @{b}the asynchronous opening of amigaguide files creates an
    additional memory leak of 216 bytes (another amigaguide.library v39.3 bug)@{ub}
    making a total memory loss of 264 bytes each time the help system is called.
    (The guides were being opened in a @{i}synchronous@{ui} way prior to ASense v4.0.)
      To minimize this, the ASense would only open amigaguide.library (once)
    if the access to the manual(s) is specifically requested by the user.(By
    selecting a '@{i}Project/About@{ui}' menuitem, any item from the '@{i}Help@{ui}' menu, or
    by pressing a 'HELP' key.)

  - There is a buglet in lupe: @{b}when you try to save the content of a lupe
    window as an iff file, the file requester will appear on workbench,
    instead on the ASense screen@{ub}.This is not very convenient, but this
    option would probably not be used frequently by many users and is thus
    left unchanged. The lupe code is available on the aminet, anyway.

  - sysrep's report has some inaccuracies (@{i}screen depth and kickstart version@{ui}),
    These fields aren't relevant for ordering. Only the CPU/FPU is important,
    so that the ASense can be recompiled accordingly.The rest is not important,
    although the resolution is noted, just for the record.
@endnode
///
///     ToDo                                              //f
@node ASENSE-HISTORY-TODO "ASense - History: ToDo"
@TOC ASENSE-GENERAL-HISTORY
@PREV ASENSE-HISTORY-BUGS
@NEXT ASENSE-GENERAL-HISTORY
@{b}@{u}To Do@{uu}@{ub} - what needs to be done and plans for the future.

  This software has many options, but there is still room for improvements.

@{b}@{u}Important things which are still missing@{uu}@{ub}: (a lot, this is only a 1st release)
  0. Ports to other OSs:
   - MorphOS, Linux, MacOS,...
  1. Chiron & asteroids (only Chiron is considered to be important);
   - @{b}Chiron will become available ASAP as an update@{ub}.
   - Asteroids will become available through the Swiss Ephemeris (TM),
     if there is enough interest for this feature to justify the price
     of the license...
  3. Internet support;
  5. Atlas
   - This is a tricky one.There are atlases on the web, however, none
     of them is suitable enough.The atlas should list GPS coordinates
     of HOSPITALS around the world (not of the cities).There is about
     100,000 of those on the globe (rough estimate), and it should be
     feasible to create such an atlas.Probably none exists currently.
  6. More stars (about 100 of them certainly);
  7. More chart types;
  8. Interpreter (this is a long shot, would require construction of an AI).
  9. Cosmetics, better GUI
 10. More features
     ...
@endnode
///
///   Contact                                             //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-CONTACT "ASense - General: Contact"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GENERAL-HISTORY
@NEXT ASENSE-GENERAL-LIMITATIONS
@{b}@{u}Author@{uu}@{ub}: @{b}Jim Sunrise@{ub}, MA degree in robotics engineering and optimisation.

  (To avoid misunderstandings, that is 7 years of high education, 5 in
   robotics engineering (basic studies) and additional 2 years of post
   graduate studies in optimisation and automatization of industrial
   processes.) Studied the field of astrology as a hobby since 1988.

@{b}@{u}Contact@{uu}@{ub}: How to reach the author.

  @{i}e-mail@{ui}: @{b}Jim Sunrise@{ub} <@{"springsoft@tippnet.co.yu" rxs
    "IF ~SHOW('L','openurl.library') THEN CALL ADDLIB('openurl.library',3,-66);
    url='mailto:springsoft@tippnet.co.yu?subject=ASense';OpenURL(url,SHOW,TOFRONT,NEWWIN,LAUNCH);EXIT" }>

  If you like this software, it would be nice if you:

  - send a support e-mail, saying something like
    '@{i}You've made my life better by creating the ASense.Thank you@{ui}.'

  - send me a note about what would you like to find in an upgrade version.
    (Please include your @{"ASense.stats" link ASENSE-PROJECT-STATS} file as well.It might be helpful...)

  - donate some money for the development of new version(s), preferably by
    buying the currently existing one(s).

@{b}@{u}Bug reports@{uu}@{ub}:

  If you have @{"bug reports" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DEBUG}, send them and you may be rewarded with the versino
  of the program without the bug that you have found! @{i}Upgrades are free of
  charge to bug finders@{ui}, but only to those who find previously unknown bug(s).

    Don't expect (quick) answers, I'm only one, and there are many of you...
@endnode
///
///   Upgrades                                            //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-UPGRADES "ASense - General: Upgrades"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-UPGRADES-INSTALL
@{b}@{u}User levels@{uu}@{ub}:

  @{b}Novice@{ub} - downloads a DEMO version and does nothing else about it.
    @{i}Some braves may even try to start the ASense before deleting it@{ui}!
  @{b}Beginner@{ub} - after watching all of the available examples from the help menu,
    one becomes a beginner.@{i}Some braves may even try to read the manual@{ui}!

  @{i}@{b}Average@{ub}@{ui} - an average user would probably buy the @{b}CYCLES@{ub} and @{b}TRANSITS@{ub}.
  @{i}@{b}Competent@{ub}@{ui} - a competent user would also buy @{b}MERGERS@{ub} and @{b}SYNASTRY@{ub} modules.
  @{i}@{b}Advanced@{ub}@{ui} - an advanced user would need @{b}DIRECTIONS@{ub} and @{b}EPHEMERIS@{ub} generator.
  @{i}@{b}Very Advanced@{ub}@{ui} - these users would buy the @{b}STARS@{ub} too, to gaze on heavens.

  @{b}@{FG shine}ELITE@{FG text}@{ub} - An ELITE user would become an @{i}astrologer@{ui} and earn @{i}money@{ui} with ASense.
    ELITE users are strongly advised to purchase the @{b}ADVANCED_DOCS@{ub} module.

  @{u}The advanced docs contain@{uu}: (about 150 kb)
  - Details about the @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} house system
  - Special theory of @{"aspects" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS} (breakthrough discovery)
  - Essay about Sun's evolution
  - Essay about the stellar orbs

  IMPROTANT NOTE: @{b}To order a module you MUST start the ASense and then go
    to the '@{i}Register->Order Modules@{ui}' menu. Enable the @{i}gadget help@{ui} feature
    to receive some further guidance@{ub} (menu '@{i}Pick->Hover Help->Gadgets@{ui}')!
    @{b}Please alos read the part of the ASense.faq file reffering to ordering@{ub}.

@{b}@{u}Prices@{uu}@{ub}: Valid until next version.

  @{b}Module                Price     Referred as     Comment@{ub}
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  @{b}Cyclic Charts@{ub}         14.99 EUR (CYCLES)        A @{i}fabulous@{ui} feature!
  @{b}Directions@{ub}             5.99 EUR (DIRECTIONS)    An @{i}important@{ui} feature!
  @{b}Transits@{ub}              10.49 EUR (TRANSITS)      A @{i}popular@{ui}  feature!
  @{b}All Named Faint Stars@{ub}  3.49 EUR (STARS)         A @{i}relevant@{ui} feature!
  @{b}Synastry@{ub}               8.99 EUR (SYNASTRY)      A @{i}valuable@{ui} feature!
  @{b}Mergers@{ub}                5.99 EUR (MERGERS)       A @{i}recommended@{ui} feature!
  @{b}Ephemeris Generator@{ub}   10.49 EUR (EPHEMERIS)     An @{i}astonishing@{ui} feature!
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  @{b}Advanced Docs@{ub} (~150k)  9.95 EUR (ADVANCED_DOCS) A @{i}@{b}unique@{ub}@{ui} literature!
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  @{b}Everything above@{ub}      @{b}@{u}69.69@{uu}@{ub} EUR (EVERYTHING)    An @{i}@{b}affordable@{ub}@{ui} price!

  @{i}Bugfix-updates@{ui} are @{i}free@{ui} for registered users.
  The most efficient bugfinder is entitled to a free upgrade in exchange for
  a stats file and a bit of a feedback. The winner this time is @{b}Amigamancer@{ub}.

  @{b}VAT@{ub}, @{b}customs@{ub}, @{b}p&p@{ub}, and perhaps some other similar costs vary from case to
  case and @{b}are@{ub} therefore @{b}not listed here, nor included in the above prices@{ub}.

@{b}@{u}Discounts@{uu}@{ub}: Your mileage may vary...

  - upto @{b}15% for distributors@{ub}, depending on the amount of sold 'copies'.
  - upto @{b}10% on occasional '@{i}Special sales@{ui}'@{ub} offers, depending on a season.

@{b}@{u}Modules@{uu}@{ub}: Reasons for chopping the software into smaller pieces.

    @{b}The ASense has been choped into modules in order to cater for the wider
  spread of user-needs@{ub}.Some may require a certain feature, while the others
  don't, so why should everyone pay for everything ? Just because the coder
  wishes to earn more ? I don't think so. (@{i}And I'm the coder, so I decide@{ui}.)
  The modular structure it is, then.
    @{i}Note@{ui}: @{b}Lower the price, wider the market@{ub}!

@{b}@{u}Subscriptions@{uu}@{ub}: @{b}The advanced docs are curently on '@{i}Subcriptions only@{ui}'@{ub}, until
  they officialy get published (or the number of subscribers becomes large).
  You may also subscribe to receive a @{i}regular@{ui} seasonal upgrade immediately.

@{b}@{u}Donations@{uu}@{ub}: If you wish a certain feature to be developed immediately, then
  please make an appropriate donation for the sake of it's development.

@{b}@{u}Payment methods@{uu}@{ub}: How to pay when purchasing ASense.

    If the place where you obtained the demo version of ASense doesn't
  offer a method of payment that is suitable for you, then please @{"contact" link ASENSE-GENERAL-CONTACT}
  the author for an up-to-date list of payment methods.
    It would be nice if you mention in the message what method(s) of payment
  would you prefere.If it isn't already available, an addition to the list
  of available methods will be considered...
@endnode
///
///     Install                                           //f
@node ASENSE-UPGRADES-INSTALL "ASense - Upgrades: Installation"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GENERAL-UPGRADES
@NEXT ASENSE-UPGRADES-MESS-FILES
@{b}@{u}Installation of upgrades@{uu}@{ub} - how to install new modules.

    When you order and pay for an upgrade, you will receive an archive with
  several '@{b}mess@{ub}' files.Once you have extracted them from the obtained archive,
  just select the '@{i}@{b}Upgrades/Install Modules@{ub}@{ui}' menu item.

    File requester will ask you for the order's @{i}keyfile@{ui}.@{b} You MUST select the
  same file which you have selected while you were creating your order@{ub}.This
  may differ from the current keyfile of your (possibly still unregistered)
  piece of ASense. (Checksums of this file are required during decryption.)
  Another requester will then ask for @{i}messed@{ui} files (multiple choice allowed).
    @{b}The ASense will decrypt the given '@{i}mess@{ui}' files if the keyfile matches@{ub}.
  (You may replace your old files with the newly obtained ones afterwards.)

  @{"The mess files" link ASENSE-UPGRADES-MESS-FILES} - Details about them.

@endnode
///
///     Mess files                                        //f
@node ASENSE-UPGRADES-MESS-FILES "ASense - Upgrades: Mess Files"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-UPGRADES-INSTALL
@NEXT MAIN
@{b}@{u}The @{i}mess@{ui} files@{uu}@{ub}: Details, details...

    The '@{i}mess@{ui}' files are special file type, used only by ASense executable
  during it's upgrading.Their aim is to provide sufficiently secure way of
  transporting executable files in an e-mail attachment @{i}without@{ui} using @{b}pgp@{ub},
  @{b}SSL@{ub} or some similar method of conventional encryption, since they aren't
  @{i}always@{ui} readily available. Implemented cryptography is strong enough to
  resist any expected attempt of decryption by a casual pirate.

    @{i}A mess file can only be created by the author of ASense or perhaps
  by a person who has commited an act of piracy by cracking the ASense
  in order to extract and reversely engineer the implemented algorhitm@{ui}.
  (Invention of a separate algorhitm would be easier, though.)
    @{b}The ASense can't create mess files, it can only @{i}decrypt@{ui} them@{ub}.

    To decrypt a @{i}mess@{ui} file, one must have a working @{i}ASense@{ui} executable and
  a matching @{i}keyfile@{ui}, or a file with an identical set of checksums. This
  is almost impossible to occur by chance, unless the selected keyfile is
  some @{i}system@{ui} file (like a shared library), present practically anywhere.
  Even then, the chances of successful decryption by a casual check are slim.
    @{b}It is unwise to apoint a PD, @{i}system@{ui} or other @{i}popular@{ui} file as a keyfile@{ub}!

    @{b}Even if one dissassembles the ASense in order to learn the details of
  a decryption method, one would still need a keyfile to unmess the files@{ub}.
  Alternatively, checksums from an @{i}intercepted order@{ui} may be used, but the
  extracted files definitely won't work without a keyfile or an additional
  cracking. Nevertheless, it is *@{"guaranteed" link ASENSE-GENERAL-UNIQUENESS}* that the ASense files will
  remain @{i}@{b}unique@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}trackable@{ub}@{ui} no matter what. Thus, difficult for pirating.
  @{b}It would be much cheaper and less risky to purchase the ASense legally@{ub}...

@endnode
///
@remark (essays)
///   Limitations of astrology                            //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-LIMITATIONS "ASense - General: Limitations"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GENERAL-CONTACT
@NEXT ASENSE-CHART_STYLE
@{b}@{u}Limitations of astrology@{uu}@{ub}: Place where the borders are.

    The astrological influences have to be considered as @{FG shine}weather@{FG text}.They change
  on they own accord and we have to try to adapt to them the best that we can.
  The difference is that the astrological influences are by far less chaotic,
  and therefore more predictable.For many years in advance.Only the shear
  number of (still insufficiently studied) astrological techniques and methods
  creates a confusion.

    Moreover, one must note that @{i}weather@{ui} is an important factor for every
  living creature, but there are other relatively @{i}independent@{ui} factors too:
  - @{b}genes@{ub} (the personal inhheritance),
  - @{b}environment@{ub} (the material background),
  - @{b}neighbours@{ub} (the social surrounding and family), and
  - @{b}experience@{ub} (comes with age).
    A good way to remember these is to use an analogy of a @{i}farmer@{ui}: to obtain
  the best results, a farmer needs good @{i}@{b}weather@{ub}@{ui}, good @{i}@{b}seeds@{ub}@{ui}, good @{i}@{b}soil@{ub}@{ui} and a
  protection from various @{i}@{b}pests@{ub}@{ui} (like @{i}fungi@{ui}, @{i}herbs@{ui}, @{i}insects@{ui} and other animals).
  The gathered @{i}@{b}experience in farming@{ub}@{ui} will undoubtedtly be helpful for him too.
  All of these are factors which are mostly @{i}independent@{ui} from each other.@{i}Weather@{ui}
  is just one of them.Just like @{i}astrology@{ui}, as mentioned in the first paragraph.

    Let us prove the independence of the mentioned factors:

  @{b}Claim 0@{ub}:@{b}In a case of genes, there is nothing in an astrological chart
  that can tell an astrologer onto what living creature it is attached to@{ub}.
  (Genes are an independent factor.)
  @{b}Proof 0@{ub}: Astrology chart is a simple snapshot of a sky taken from a certain
  place.@{i}On a same place@{ui}/time when someone is being born, millions of bacteria,
  few insects, maybe a plant or a more complex animal begin their life too.
  (Or an event may happen as well.) They all have identical charts, but still
  different patterns of life, which therefore implies the existence of some
  other relatively independent factors.
    Comparing humans to bacteria, one should immediately spot that they are
  different type of organism and that they therefore must have different genes.
    The astrological factors may play some part in selecting which particular
  sperm would become the winner, but the genetic material distributed between
  a number of spermatozoons is not that much different from each other if they
  all come from the same male. (Even when they don't, they are very similar.)
  Genes of a gorila differ from human genes by only 3 percents.Fine details...
    @{i}Conclusion@{ui}: @{b}One can't make a nuclear physicist out of a pig, even if its
  natal chart says so@{ub}.(@{i}The astrologer must be aware that the subject is a pig
  when reading a chart of a pig and adjust the range of possibilities to the
  available set of options@{ui}.)

  @{i}Note@{ui}: @{b}Genes get inherited, but family patterns exist in the astrological
  charts too, if the birth was spontaneous and natural@{ub} (i.e. not induced).
    Somehow, the internal biological clocks work their way to synchronise
  the birth time to be in a moment that follows the family patterns to some
  extent (within the available time window of opportunities, of course).
  @{i}@{b}Adoption agencies should really consult an astrologer when trying to find
  a home for an orphan.If charts of foster parents differ significantly from
  a child's chart, they will have difficulties in understanding each other@{ub}@{ui}.
  These things are easily preventable if one becomes aware of them.

  @{b}Claim 1@{ub}: @{b}Every second 2..3 people are born at average@{ub}.
  @{b}Proof 1@{ub}: There are more than 6 billion humans on Earth, but a vast majority
  of them are younger than 3 billion seconds (~95 years)). 6 / 3 = (do the math).
  (By '@{i}now@{ui}', the first decade of the XXI century is ment, that is.)

  @{b}Claim 2@{ub}: @{b}Claim 1 implies that there are people which have their birth times
  identical upto a nanosecond@{ub}.
  @{b}Proof 2@{ub}: If the birth rate was steady, there would be 3 billion pairs of
  people who share their birth second.There is a good chance that about 3
  pairs would be born during a same ns (nanosecond), which is a bilionth
  part of a second.
    The birth rate is not steady, but it doesn't vary greatly, so perhaps
  there are a number of seconds when only 1 person or none have been born.
  If this is the case, the birth rate during the remaining time would have
  had to be higher to make the average of 1 pair/second.This would increase
  a chance that a pair of people has been born during a same nanosecond.
  (Finding such a pair would be next to impossible, however, since the birth
  records are not (yet) kept in nanoseconds.)
    The point of the Claim 2 is to emphasize the importance of @{"houses" link ASENSE-DECIDE-HS}, as the
  only astrological factor which differs in all these pairs of charts, since
  planetary positions do not.The placement upon the planet Earth, that is.

  @{b}Claim 3@{ub}: @{b}Material inheritance is an independent factor@{ub}.
  @{b}Proof 3@{ub}: Some people are born with a '@{i}silver spoon@{ui}', some in the rich
  countries, but most are not.It is possible that a poor one has a chart
  that implies a large inheritance, but the best possible outcome of it
  may be to inherit the small home that he already dwells in with his
  old parents.This means that what is large for one, is small for other.
  ('@{i}Your mileage may vary@{ui}.')
    @{b}The astrology factors@{ub} indicate ones subjective view of a situation,
  they @{b}don't give the absolute measurements@{ub}.(@{i}@{b}The shape, but not the size@{ub}@{ui}.)

    As for the '@{b}family and social surrounding@{ub}' they are probably the least
  independent factor.The weather causes the appearance of pests as much as
  the chart indicates the quality of the relationships that form between a
  person and the surrounding people.However, as in the previous paragraph,
  it has to be pointed out that a chart doesn't give the absolute measure-
  ments, but only personal subjective views.(@{i}@{b}The shape, but not the size@{ub}@{ui}.)

  - @{b}The moment in history@{ub} (@{i}@{b}higher order cycles@{ub}@{ui}), is an important independent
  factor that seldomly shows, but when it does, it turns everything around.
    For example, people are organized into higher forms of organizations.The
  largest among them are called '@{i}states@{ui}'.They too have their horoscopes.When
  these charts indicate some large event (like war), they take precedence
  over the charts of the individual humans.Most of the people get affected
  to some extent by the events that happen in the charts of organizations
  that they belong too.('@{i}@{b}An individual electron may go with a large speed
  to any direction at any specific time, but when they are looked upon at
  a larger scale, they all go slowly where the current flows@{ub}@{ui}.')
    Thereupon, @{b}if an event strikes an area, the astrologer should look for
  its causes in a chart of that area, rather than in the charts of people
  who have participated@{ub}. (The reason for people's presence may be found
  in their charts, but the reason for the existance of an event should be
  sought in a higher order chart that belongs to the affected area.)
@endnode
///
///   ASense Chart Style                                  //f
@node ASENSE-CHART_STYLE "ASense - General: ASense Chart Style"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GENERAL-LIMITATIONS
@NEXT ASENSE-GENERAL-DATA_GRADING
@{b}@{u}ASense Chart Style@{uu}@{ub} - (c) 2005, 2006 Jim Sunrise, all rights reserved.

    The ASense Chart Style, in further text 'ACStyle', is specifically designed
  to offer as much visual information as possible.It consists of a following:

  I Aspects
     1. When drawn as lines or arcs between points
        - lines and arcs are LARGE, across the whole chart,
        - color of a line indicates the type of aspect,
        - thickness of a line indicates precision (4 grades were defined),
        - type of a line indicates additional properties of the aspect,
          whether it is applying or separating, and
          whether it is ingoing (sinister) or an outgoing (dexter) aspect,
        - depicting by arcs instead of lines is used for parallels and parans.
     2. When depicted as glyphs (9 serie is depicted in this manner)
        - color of a ghostly glyph indicates the the type of aspect,
        - size of a ghostly glyph indicates precision of the aspect,
        - style of a ghostly glyph indicates properties of the aspect.

  II Bodies
     1. Standard objects
        - planets are depicted with their standard glyphs,
        - families of asteroids are depicted as different glyphs,
        - color of glyphs indicates the course of movement of bodies
          (whether they are prograde or retrograde), or some other property
          (i.e. red color of a part of Fortune is chosen to drive attention).
        - optionally, size of a glyph may indicate the distance of object
          (this may be important for inner planets).
        - optionally, style of a glyph may indicate some other property
          (like:bold = strongest almuten, or 'the final dispositor',...).
        - optionally, click on a body reveals further information,
          depending on a type of click (single, double, right button).
        - optionally, 2 coordinates of a body may be depicted on
          the chart, one in a circle, and the other on the radius.
          Both may be selected by the user.
     2. Stars are depicted (optionally)
        - type of a glyph of a star indicates its magnitude,
        - color of a glyph of a star indicates its spectral type,
          but may (optionally) indicate its course of movement,
        - position of a glyph of a star indicates its distance
          (indirectly, this also indicates its luminosity),
          but may (optionally) depict it's second coordinate.

  III Chart
        - additional chart may be presented in a ring,
        - input data are noted in a text around the chart,
        - parameters used during the computation are noted in a
          text around the chart,
        - type of chart(s) is noted in the text around the chart.

  (IV) Copyright notice of the 'ASense Chart Style' (ACStyle)
     (Notes below apply only to charts created with ACStyle.)

     1. Astrologers who draw their charts manually
        - are free to use ACStyle in these charts.

     2. Astrologers who present their ACStyled charts on the web
        - must place this page on the web, unchanged,
        - must include this copyright notice in a text below ACStyled charts:

          "'ASense Chart Style', originally developed by the author of
           the Altitude house system."

        - the words 'ASense Chart Style' must link to this page or to
          some place that sells the ASense astrology software package.

     2. Astrologers who print ACStyled charts in a magazine
        - must include this notice in a text accompanying an ACStyled chart:

          "'ASense Chart Style'"

     3. Programers of astrology software who wish to use ACStyle in their project
        - must include this page in their project's documentation, unchanged,
        - must pay the license fee, the price of which would depend on the
        scope and the size of their project.

@endnode
///
///   Data grading                                        //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-DATA_GRADING "ASense - General: Data grading"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-CHART_STYLE
@NEXT MAIN
@{b}@{u}Data grading@{uu}@{ub}: Data evaluation standards.

    Data grading is an important part of any serious astrological work. In
  astrology the input data consists of only 2 parts: time of event and the
  placement of event. The current (unofficial) standard, the Rodden rating,
  grades only the time part, while the coordinates are not graded at all.
  This document tries to improve this situation by proposing an additional
  system for evaluation of the quality of the placement part of input data.
  It also adds 2 more entries to Rodden rating to allow grading of poorly
  documented, mostly historic events, for the record purposes.

    The reason to include the grading of coordinates is to reduce errors.
  In temperate zones, 1 arc minute of geo. longitude roughly equals 1 km.
  Thereupon, a positional error of 1 km corresponds to an error of 1 arc
  minute of MC placement. This equals 1 week in directions, for example.

    Most people live in large cities which stretch for many kilometers.
  Astrologers who get the coordinates for the chart from an atlas must be
  aware of the magnitude of positional error which comes from the fact
  that a very large area is reduced to a single pair of geo. coordinates.

    These errors increase signifficantly with increase of geo. latitudes.

  ***********************************************************************

  @{b}Rodden Rating (RR)@{ub}: Grading implented in the @{i}Lois Rodden's AstroDatabank@{ui}.

  - @{b}AA@{ub} - Accurate data as recorded by the family or state.
  -  @{b}A@{ub} - Accurate data as quoted by the person, kin, friend, or associate.
  -  @{b}B@{ub} - Biography or autobiography (give complete publication information).
  -  @{b}C@{ub} - Caution: no source of origin.
  - @{b}DD@{ub} - Dirty Data: two or more conflicting quotes that are unqualified.
  -  @{b}X@{ub} - Data with no @{i}time@{ui} of birth.
  - @{b}XX@{ub} - Data without a known or confirmed @{i}date@{ui}.

  -  @{b}-@{ub} - Data without known or confirmed @{i}month@{ui} of birth.
  - @{b}--@{ub} - Data without known or confirmed @{i}year@{ui} of birth. (No data at all.)

  NOTE: @{b}Last 2 entries are a proposed extension to Rodden rating@{ub}, in order
  to cover frequently encountered cases where only month or year is known.
  Such a chart may still hold some information, unlike the one without any
  time data whatsoever.

  IMPORTANT NOTE: If you get data from a Data Service or Data Collection,
  you should cite the @{i}name@{ui} of the service/collection as well.These sources
  MUST provide the source of the original data. If they don't, their data
  should be considered as '@{i}DD@{ui}' (dirty data), even if they claim otherwise
  (they MUST give the original source).

  NOTE: Successfully @{i}@{b}rectified@{ub}@{ui} data may be graded as type @{b}A@{ub} if the details
  about the rectification process are available for verification by others.

  *************************************************************************

  @{b}Grading of coordinates by @{i}Jim Sunrise@{ui}, the author of ASense@{ub}:
  - @{b}VII@{ub} - @{i}@{b}GPS coordinates@{ub}@{ui}, read from the spot of birth (the most accurate)
  -  @{b}VI@{ub} - coordinates from a @{i}@{b}local topographic chart@{ub}@{ui}, the @{i}address@{ui} is known

   @{i}Address unknown, only name of the place is available (descending accuracy)@{ui}:

  -   @{b}V@{ub} - coordinates from atlas, @{i}village/small town@{ui},  < 10,000 people.
  -  @{b}IV@{ub} - coordinates from atlas, @{i}small city@{ui},  10,000 -  50,000 people.
  - @{b}III@{ub} - coordinates from atlas, @{i}medium city@{ui}, 50,000 - 100,000 people.
  -  @{b}II@{ub} - coordinates from atlas, @{i}large city@{ui}, 100,000 - 500,000 people.
  -   @{b}I@{ub} - coordinates from atlas, @{i}very large city@{ui}, 0.5 - 1 million people.
  -   @{b}0@{ub} - coordinates from atlas, @{i}megapolis@{ui}, more than a million people.

  -   @{b}c@{ub} - caution: no source of origin.
  -  @{b}dd@{ub} - dirty data: two or more conflicting quotes that are unqualified.
  -  @{b}xx@{ub} - data without a known or confirmed geographical coordinates.

    (@{i}Similarity with the luminosity grading of stars is deliberate@{ui}. :-))

    @{b}Errors of house cusps in the least accurate class may reach a few degrees
  sometimes!@{ub}.

  NOTE: @{b}To fully grade your data, you should label it with something as
  '@{i}AA VII@{ui}', and then give your sources as well, as completely as possible@{ub}.

  **************************************************************************

  IMPORTANT: Coders of astrology software who wish to implement this grading
  in their own software product are advised
  - @{i}to disallow the casting of a chart until the user grades the input data;
  - to disallow the casting of complex chart types with poorly graded data@{ui}.
@endnode
///
@remark (gadgets)
///   Sides                                               //f
@node ASENSE-GADGETS-SIDES "ASense - Gadgets: Sides"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-GENERAL-TOOLTYPES
@{b}@{u}Sides@{uu}@{ub} - Left or Right.

    The ASense GUI is able to present 2 different charts simultaneously.The
  sizing of those chart is slightly different, so that a user may always know
  (easily) which side is which.

    The focus can be changed from the menu, by menu shortcuts, by pressing
  keys numeric 4 (left) or numeric 6 (right side), or by casting any of the
  charts by pressing a GUI button (buttons on the left side force the focus
  to be changed to left, and vice versa).

    There isn't any special indicator to show the current focus of the ASense
  (i.e. a current side).If in doubt, force your desired side by pressing the
  key 4 or 6 on the numeric keyboard prior of casting the chart from the menu
  (GUI buttons chart casting forces the side by itself, hence side casting by
  the user is not required in this case).
@endnode
///
///   Tooltypes                                           //f
@node ASENSE-GENERAL-TOOLTYPES "ASense - General: Tooltypes"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GADGETS-SIDES
@NEXT ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING
@{b}@{u}Tooltypes@{uu}@{ub}: Control the ASense from its icon.

  @{u}Available tooltypes@{uu}:
  - @{b}EXT_EPHE_DIR@{ub} - path to a @{i}default directory for external ephemeris@{ui}.
    Default path is to use the @{b}ASense:ephe@{ub} directory.
    @{i}Note@{ui}: the ASense does not support any external ephemeris yet (v4.0).
  - @{b}EPHE_DIR@{ub} - path to a @{i}default directory for saving of generated ephemeris@{ui}.
    Default path is to use the @{b}ASense:ephe@{ub} directory.
  - @{b}SAVE_DIR@{ub} - path to a @{i}default directory for chart saving@{ui}.
    Default path is to use the @{b}ASense:map_shots@{ub} directory.
  - @{b}DATA_DIR@{ub} - path to a @{i}default directory for @{"database" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE} and @{"session" link ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY} files@{ui}.
    Default path is to use the @{b}ASense:data@{ub} directory.
  - @{b}REC_DIR@{ub} - path to a @{i}default directory for @{"macros" link ASENSE-PICK-AREXX} and external rexx scripts@{ui}.
    Default path is to use the @{b}ASense:rexx@{ub} directory.

  - @{b}LUPE_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to a 3rd party magnifying utility called '@{i}Lupe@{ui}'.
    Default is '@{b}Lupe@{ub}'.
  - @{b}TAPGIF_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to a 3rd party @{i}iff@{ui} to @{i}gif@{ui} turning utility.
    Default is '@{b}tapgif@{ub}'.
  - @{b}SYSREP_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to a 3rd party @{i}system reporter@{ui}.
    Default is '@{b}sysrep@{ub}'.

  - @{b}CONFIG_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to a config file.
    Default is '@{b}ASense.config@{ub}'.
  - @{b}STATS_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to a stats file.
    Default is '@{b}ASense.stats@{ub}'.
  - @{b}KEY_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to the keyfile.
    Default is '@{b}ASense.keyfile@{ub}'.

  - @{b}GUIDE1_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to the main guide of ASense.
    Default is '@{b}ASense-astrology.guide@{ub}'.
  - @{b}GUIDE2_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to the astronomical guide.
    Default is '@{b}ASense-astronomy.guide@{ub}'.
  - @{b}GUIDE3_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to the guide of stars.
    Default is '@{b}ASense-star-data.guide@{ub}'.

  - @{b}EDITOR_FILE@{ub} - @{i}full@{ui} path to your favourite editor. (Currently unused.)
    Default is '@{b}Ed@{ub}'.

  - @{b}DB_FILE@{ub} - path to a database that is to be loaded during startup.
    Default is @{b}not to load any database initially@{ub}, to speedup the startup.
    The given path may be either @{i}@{b}full@{ub}@{ui} or @{i}@{b}partial@{ub}@{ui}.If it is partial, the search
    will start from the DATA_DIR (as defined above), NOT from a PROGDIR:.
    EXAMPLES: (assuming the default DATA_DIR)
      @{u}Tooltype@{uu}:                         @{u}File to search@{uu}:
      'DB_FILE=@{i}specials/my_friends.db@{ui}'  @{b}ASense:data/@{i}specials/my_friends.db@{ui}@{ub}
      'DB_FILE=@{i}ASense.db@{ui}'               @{b}ASense:data/@{i}ASense.db@{ui}@{ub}    (default)
      'DB_FILE=@{i}/examples.db@{ui}'            @{b}ASense:@{i}examples.db@{ui}@{ub}
    NOTE: Loading (and sorting) of a very large database may take some time.
    Unless you frequently need to work with the same database, it is better
    not to use this tooltype, but to load database(s) only when required
    (by using the @{i}Project/Global Databases/Load Database@{ui}.. menu subitem).

  - @{b}LOCATION@{ub} - @{i}geographical coordinates of the user@{ui}, used for greetings.
      If present, this value is used for a more proper greeting.Enter your geo.
    coordinates as a single word, longitude first.Use '@{b};@{ub}' or '@{b},@{ub}' as a delimiter.
    @{i}Example@{ui}: "120W45;35S35".
  - @{b}TIME_ZONE@{ub} - GMT time offset of the user, in minutes (with summer time).
      @{i}@{b}This value is only needed if you don't have the locale.library installed@{ub}@{ui}.
      For example, if you are currently in -5.00 h time zone with summer time
      in use, than you should set this value to -240.
      (-300 min for zone + 60 min for the summer time).

  - @{b}L_DEF_STR_1 + L_DEF_STR_2@{ub} -  left user default init string.
  - @{b}R_DEF_STR_1 + R_DEF_STR_2@{ub} - right user default init string.
  - @{b}L_DEF_RET_STR_1 + L_DEF_RET_STR_2@{ub} -  left user default return init string.
  - @{b}R_DEF_RET_STR_1 + R_DEF_RET_STR_2@{ub} - right user default return init string.
      @{b}If set, these strings override the built-in defaults@{ub}.
      The strings 1 and 2 are simply merged together.(Both of them must be set.)
    This is a workaround of the fact that the init string required by ASense is
    longer than the maximum allowed length of a tooltype string (127 chars).

  - @{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub} - set a priority of a commodity broker.
      Commodities are (small) utilities, like '@{i}Lupe@{ui}'.Most of them react on the
    input stream or manipulate it.The common feature of commodities is that
    they can be controled by a '@{i}Workbench:Tools/Commodities/Exchange@{ui}' program.
    Default is @{b}0@{ub}.

  - @{b}MAGIC_NR@{ub} - internal use, do not touch!
@endnode
///
///   Input String                                        //f
@node ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING "ASense - Gadgets: Input String"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GENERAL-TOOLTYPES
@NEXT ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW
@{b}@{u}Input String@{uu}@{ub} - How to enter your data.

    The best way to understand this quickly is to study the string labeö text
  carefuly, and to do the same as it has been shown there.However, if anyone
  needs a lengthier explanation, hereby it is provided.

  @{u}Delimitation rules@{uu}:
  0. @{b}Data is entered as a single string@{ub}, which allows easier storing, faster
     typing, better visibility of data and generally less harassment to user.
  1. The required data fields are separated by @{b}spaces@{ub} (' '), @{b}dots@{ub} ('.'), and
     @{b}colons@{ub} (':').ASense chops the string on the occurence of one (or a group)
     of these characters.Any one of them may be used as a delimiter anywhere.
     A @{b}degree sign@{ub} ('°'), and a @{b}minute sign@{ub} (''') are also legal delimiters.
     As of ASense v4.0, the @{b}slash sign@{ub} ('/'), and the @{b}horizontal line@{ub} (ASCII 173,
     '­') may also be used as delimiters, but NOT the @{i}negation sign@{ui} (ASCII 45,
     '-'), as it is required later for data parsing.
  2. Additionally, the last 3 data fields (@{i}name@{ui}, @{i}place@{ui}, and the @{"data grade" link ASENSE-GENERAL-DATA_GRADING})
     *MUST* have a @{i}@{b}semicolon@{ub}@{ui} (';') as a delimiter. A different delimiting
     character was used because these fields are strings, unlike the other
     ones. The chopping of them from a data string is done first, and then
     the rest of the data is parsed.
       The @{b}name@{ub} and @{b}place@{ub} fields are @{i}optional@{ui} (i.e. relevant to the user who
     reads the chart, but not required by the ASense during the process of
     chart casting).
       The @{b}data grading@{ub}, however, will be set to worse possible if omitted,
     which, in turn, may prevent the ASense from casting many complex charts
     due to the poorly graded data...

  @{u}Data fields@{uu}:
  @{b}Date@{ub} - 1 or 2 digits number, 1..31.
  @{b}Month@{ub} - 1 or 2 digits number, 1..12; or a 3 letter acronym.
    If you use 3 letter acronyms for months, the first char MUST be large.
  @{b}Year@{ub} - 1 to 4 digits number, limited by the implemented size of ephemeris.
    Currently, this is several thousands of years in both directions of time.
    If you exceed the ephemeris limit, a warning requester will be issued.
  @{u}The following date formats are allowed@{uu}: (delimiters defined above)
    @{b}DD MM YYYY, DD @{i}Mon@{ui} YYYY, @{i}Mon@{ui} DD YYYY@{ub}.
  Note: The date fields are @{i}ignored@{ui} in the @{"return" link ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW} string.

  @{b}Cycle@{ub} - signed 1..4 digits number, -9999..99999.
    This value is used in casting of @{i}cyclic@{ui} charts, and indicates the required
    age.For example, if you wish to cast a solar return for 35th year of your
    life, you will enter a number 34 here, meaning that you wish a chart to
    refer to your 34th birthday.Then, simply cast a required chart from the
    menu or by buttons.
      @{i}Cycle@{ui} == 0 indicates the @{i}natal@{ui} (or birth) chart (i.e. of zero age).
    IMPORTANT NOTE: @{i}@{b}This field is only required in the@{ub}@{ui} @{"return string" link ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW}.

    @{i}Note@{ui}: When a previously mentioned cyclic chart is cast, it would be the one
    that is valid for a time around your 34th birthday.Cycles that are shorter
    than a year may require the usage of offsets (i.e. casting by GUI buttons)
    to cover the whole year span.The bottom left text around the chart would
    give further explanation about which cycle was actually used.Please try
    to understand it (or read again this manual carefuly) before asking any
    questions.The issue of cycles is quite a complicated one in the ASense.
    With a flick of just a few switches (or buttons), the user is capable to
    cast any of about 5000 different chart types.Therefore, a whole variety
    of results may appear.These issues are further discussed in @{"Decide" link ASENSE-DECIDE-YMD} and
    @{"Choose" link ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE} menu items referring to cycles (@{"returns" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS}, @{"progressions" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS}, @{"directions" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS}).

  @{b}AC/BC@{ub} - switch to indicate the @{i}era@{ui}, AC or BC. (Only first char is parsed.)

    NOTE: @{i}Year 1 BC, refers to year 0 (astronomically), 2 BC == -1 year, etc..
    There is *NO* year 0 BC (or 0 AC) for that matter.After 1 BC comes 1 AC.
    @{b}Astronomically however, a year 0 exists to allow easier manipulation with
    years when presented in a digital form, and corresponds to a year 1 BC@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}Calendar@{ub} - 1 char, indicating a calendar.
    @{b}'J' or 'j'@{ub} - given date is assumed to be expressed in a @{i}Julian@{ui} calendar.
    (anything else) - @{i}Gregorian@{ui} calendar is assumed for the given date.

    @{i}Note@{ui}: All given dates are converted to @{i}Gregorian@{ui} calendar before the
    chart is cast.They are marked as such in a text surounding the chart.

  @{b}Hour@{ub} - time in hours, 1 or 2 digits, 0..23.
  @{b}Minutes@{ub} - time in minutes, 1 or 2 digits, 0..59.
  @{b}Seconds@{ub} - time in seconds, 1 or 2 digits, 0..59.

  @{b}Time-zone, hours@{ub} - signed 1 or 2 digits, ±0..23.
  @{b}Time-zone, minutes@{ub} - 1 or 2 digits, 0..59.
    The @{i}time-zone@{ui} value is an offset from GMT (Greenwich mean time).

  @{b}Geographic longitude, degrees@{ub} - 1 to 3 digits, 0..180.
  @{b}Geographic longitude, minutes@{ub} - 1 or 2 digits, 0..59.
    Seconds are not used, because they are generally not needed.@{i}Nevertheless,
  you may utilize the seconds as well with the help of offsets@{ui} (±.. buttons).

  @{b}E/W hemisphere@{ub}@{b}@{ub} - 1 char, not case sensitive, indicating @{i}east@{ui}@{i}@{ui} or @{i}west@{ui}.

  @{b}Geographic latitude, degrees@{ub} - signed 1 or 2 digits, ±0..90.
  @{b}Geographic latitude, minutes@{ub} - 1 or 2 digits, 0..59.
    Seconds are not used, because they are generally not needed.@{i}Nevertheless,
  you may utilize the seconds as well with the help of offsets@{ui} (±.. buttons).

  @{b}N/S hemisphere@{ub}@{b}@{ub} - 1 char, not case sensitive, indicating @{i}north@{ui} or @{i}south@{ui}.

  @{b}Altitude@{ub} - signed 1 to 6 digits number, -99999..999999 meters.
  '@{b}m@{ub}' - char, indicating the @{i}unit of altitude@{ui} (meters) and a @{i}@{b}type of tim@{ub}@{ui}e.,
    @{u}Here lies a hidden wisdom@{uu}:
    - @{b}If the time is given as @{i}local apparent time@{ui}@{ub} (LAT. @{i}measured on sundials@{ui}),
      which differs from @{i}local mean time@{ui} (LMT, @{i}measured by mechanical clocks@{ui}),
      @{b}the ASense should be noted about it by typing an 'a' (or 'A') character
      here@{ub}.It is usually the case for ancient and medieval historical events.

  @{b}Temperature@{ub} - signed 1 to 4 digits number, -273..9999, in ° of Celsius.
  '@{b}C@{ub}' - char, indicating the unit of temperature, *MUST* be 'C' (Celsius).

  @{i}Note@{ui}: @{i}@{b}Pressure@{ub}@{ui} is estimated from the given value of @{i}altitude@{ui}, and is used
  together with the given temperature to find refraction if that is required.

  IMPORTANT NOTE: @{i}@{b}By casting a chart from the menu, the accumulated offsets
  are set to zero.If the chart is cast by buttons, the offsets are added to
  the values given in a data string@{ub}@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Top Row                                             //f
@node ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW "ASense - Gadgets: Top Row"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING
@NEXT ASENSE-GADGETS-TEXTFIELD
@{b}@{u}Top row of buttons@{uu}@{ub} - Gadgets that manipulate with the input string.

  '@{b}Undo@{ub}' - 1 level simple undo for typing mistakes.
  '@{b}->@{ub}' - Copy @{i}left@{ui} string to the @{i}right@{ui} string.
  '@{b}<-@{ub}' - Copy @{i}right@{ui} string to the @{i}left@{ui} string.
  '@{b}=±@{ub}' - Add the offsets accumulated by the -20..+20 buttons to the string.
         The offsets are set to zero afterwards.

  '@{b}Ow@{ub}' - Enable/disable overwriting during typing into the input string.

  '@{b}DB@{ub}' - Add the content of the input string to currently loaded @{"database" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE}.
         This option allows entering of an optional comment of the entry.
   '@{b}f@{ub}' - Define a @{"filter" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_FILTERS} for the currently loaded database.

  '@{b}r@@{ub}' (@{b}return at@{ub}) - switch between a @{i}natal@{ui} chart's and a @{i}cyclic@{ui} chart's data.

      @{b}When one casts a @{i}cyclic chart@{ui}@{ub} (for example a solar return), @{b}the ASense
    needs 2 sets of coordinates: one that is attached to the natal chart
    (@{i}main@{ui} @{"input string" link ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING}), and the other which describes the changes between
    the natal time and the time of return (@{i}auxiliary@{ui} ('r@') input string)@{ub}.
      Since a time of return depends upon the required cycle type, it is
    computed automatically by ASense.Thereby, the fields in the auxiliary
    string which refer to time are ignored. These include @{i}date@{ui}, @{i}month@{ui}, @{i}year@{ui},
    @{i}era@{ui}, @{i}calendar@{ui}, @{i}hour@{ui}, @{i}minutes@{ui}, @{i}seconds@{ui}, and the @{"grading of time" link ASENSE-GENERAL-DATA_GRADING}.
      The other coordinates, however, are parsed because they may contain
    changes.(Although a '@{i}name@{ui}' may have changed as well, it is not parsed
    to allow easier track keeping of the charts (names are used for chart
    saving).)

    VERY IMPORTANT NOTE: @{b}The cyclic chart is always focused to a temporary
    location.As the owner of the chart moves in space, the cyclic chart(s)
    follow that movement and change as well@{ub}.
      Therefore, a @{i}@{b}user must enter those coordinates which were@{ub}@{ui} (or are
    assumed to become) @{i}@{b}valid during a period@{ub}@{ui} (or part of a period) @{i}@{b}covered
    by the cyclic chart@{ub}@{ui}.It means that @{i}if one travels to a far away place for
    a birthday to achieve a better birthday chart, that chart would change
    again when one returns@{ui}.One must live on a changed location during the
    cycle's length to harvest the effects of a relocation on a cyclic chart.

    @{i}Note@{ui}: Relocation techniques are not yet included in the ASense.However,
    they are the top priority for the next release.
@endnode
///
///   Textfield                                           //f
@node ASENSE-GADGETS-TEXTFIELD "ASense - Gadgets: Textfield (user docs)"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW
@NEXT ASENSE-GADGETS-MIDDLE-ROW
@{b}@{u}textfield.gadget@{uu}@{ub} - (original) docs for users.
  You can mark text for cutting, copying, and erasing by simply clicking and
  dragging.Hitting alphanumeric keys replaces the text that is highlighted.
  Hitting cursor keys moves you to the front or end of the highlighted text.
  If your cursor is already somewhere in the textfield, you can hold the
  SHIFT key and click to mark the text from the curent cursor position
  to the place where you clicked.
  And the last way to mark text is to double-click, which will mark the
  word you clicked on.If you didn't click on a word, but rather you clicked
  on spaces, the whole block of spaces is marked.And if you clicked on word
  delimiters, the whole block of delimiters is marked.
  While you drag to scroll, the farther away from the gadget your mouse
  pointer is, the faster the gadget will scroll.For key sequences, the Amiga
  Style Guide was followed.Anywhere the undo buffer is mentioned, the state-
  ment is only valid if the UndoStream is supplied (see tag section below).
  @{u}Key Sequence - Function@{uu}:
   @{b}TAB@{ub} - Activate next gadget (if @{i}GA_TabCycle@{ui})
   @{b}SHIFT TAB@{ub} - Activate previous gadget (if @{i}GA_TabCycle@{ui})
   @{b}SHIFT CURSOR UP@{ub} - Move to the top line in the current page, or scroll up
     one page if cursor is on top line
   @{b}SHIFT CURSOR DOWN@{ub} - Move to the bottom line in the current page,
     or scroll down one page if cursor is on top line
   @{b}CTRL or SHIFT CURSOR RIGHT@{ub} - Move to the right end of the current line
   @{b}CTRL or SHIFT CURSOR LEFT@{ub} - Move to the left end of the current line
   @{b}SHIFT BACKSPACE@{ub} - Delete all text to the left of cursor on the current line
   @{b}SHIFT DELETE@{ub} - Delete all text to the right of the cursor  on the current
     line (in block cursor mode this also includes the highlighted character)
   @{b}CTRL CURSOR UP@{ub} - Move to the top line of the text
   @{b}CTRL CURSOR DOWN@{ub} - Move to the bottom line of the text
   @{b}ALT CURSOR RIGHT@{ub} - Move to the next word (using the delimiter characters
     provided by the programmer)
   @{b}ALT CURSOR LEFT@{ub} - Move to the previous word (using the delimiter characters
     provided by the programmer)
   @{b}ALT CURSOR UP@{ub} - Move to first character in gadget
   @{b}ALT CURSOR DOWN@{ub} - Move to last character in gadget
   @{b}ALT BACKSPACE@{ub} - Deletes the word to the left of the cursor starting at the
     current cursor position
   @{b}ALT DEL@{ub} - Deletes the word to the right of the cursor starting at the
     current cursor position
   @{b}CTRL X@{ub} - Deletes the whole line that the cursor is on
   @{b}RAMIGA [@{ub} - Switch to left justification (if @{i}TEXTFIELD_UserAlign@{ui} is set)
   @{b}RAMIGA \ or RAMIGA =@{ub} - Switch to center justification
     (if @{i}TEXTFIELD_UserAlign@{ui} is set)
   @{b}RAMIGA ]@{ub} - Switch to right justification (if @{i}TEXTFIELD_UserAlign@{ui} is set)
   @{b}RAMIGA E@{ub} - Erase all text in gadget (saved in undo buffer) (no read-only)
   @{b}RAMIGA V@{ub} - Paste text from clipboard to current cursor position (no read-only)
   @{b}RAMIGA A@{ub} - Mark all text
   @{b}RAMIGA U@{ub} - Undeletes (pastes) the last block of text marked, or recover
     from RAMIGA E (no read-only)
  @{u}When text is highlighted the following keys have functions@{uu}:
    @{b}BACKSPACE@{ub} - Erase marked text (saved in undo buffer)
    @{b}DEL@{ub} - Erase marked text (saved in undo buffer)
    @{b}RAMIGA X@{ub} - Cut marked text to clipboard (no read-only)
    @{b}RAMIGA C@{ub} - Copy marked text to clipboard
    @{b}RAMIGA V@{ub} - Replace marked text with text from clipboard
      (save marked text in undo buffer) (no read-only)
    @{b}(any text key)@{ub} - Replace marked text with that character
  @{u}Additional keys, added by ASense@{uu}:
    Numeric keypad can be used to scroll the text.
    '@{b}Num 7@{ub}' - move to top.    '@{b}Num 9@{ub}' - page up.   '@{b}Num 8@{ub}' - line up.
    '@{b}Num 1@{ub}' - move to bottom. '@{b}Num 3@{ub}' - page down. '@{b}Num 2@{ub}' - line down.
    Additionally,
    '@{b}Num 4@{ub}' - focus on left textfield. '@{b}Num 6@{ub}' - focus on right textfield.
  Menu actions are not inhibited while using the gadget, except for the
  overlapping keys (RAMIGA A, E, U, X, C, V).(@{i}Justification@{ui} is disabled.)
@endnode
///
///   Middle Row                                          //f
@node ASENSE-GADGETS-MIDDLE-ROW "ASense - Gadgets: Middle Row"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GADGETS-TEXTFIELD
@NEXT ASENSE-GADGETS-BOTTOM-ROW
@{b}@{u}Middle row@{uu}@{ub} - buttons to cast @{b}single@{ub} charts (with @{i}offsets@{ui}).

    These buttons are used to cast single charts (i.e. those that require data
  only from one side), unlike dual charts, which require data from both sides.
  @{u}Buttons from left to right@{uu}:
  '@{b}Rx@{ub}' - cast a simple @{i}@{b}radix@{ub}@{ui} (natal) chart @{i}@{b}without clearing the offsets@{ub}@{ui}.
      This switch is useful if one is analysing some cyclic chart, and wishes to
    take a quick glimpse on the natal chart and than to be able to return back
    to the cyclic chart without much trouble.To do this, one must press the '@{i}Rx@{ui}'
    button, observe the natal chart, and than return to the old chart by simply
    pressing the '@{i}0@{ui}' button (the old chart will be recalculated and displayed).
  '@{b}Cyc@{ub}', '@{b}Lo@{ub}', '@{b}La@{ub}', '@{b}Alt@{ub}' - select a @{"step type" link ASENSE-PICK-STEPS}.
  @{b}St@{ub} - cast a '@{"Star Chart" link ASENSE-SINGLE-STARS}'.
  @{b}(seven round push buttons)@{ub} - select a @{"step size" link ASENSE-PICK-STEPS}.
  '@{b}+@{ub}' - currently unused.
  '@{b}-@{ub}' - reset the accumulated offsets.
  '@{b}-20@{ub}'..'@{b}+20@{ub}' - offset buttons.
      Add this much of units selected by @{i}step-size@{ui} to a selected @{i}step-type@{ui} and
    cast a selected chart (cyclic or natal).(@{i}If it is cyclic, the unit is the
    number of cycles@{ui}.) Initial number of units are given by the input string.
      The resulting chart's data is printed on a text around the chart.@{i}@{b}When a
    chart is cast from the menu, all offsets are reset to zero@{ub}@{ui}.
  '@{b}0@{ub}' - recalculate the chart without adding any offsets.
      This switch is useful when one wishes to change some other parameters
    available on menus.Simply change the menu switches and then press '@{i}0@{ui}' to
    recalculate the chart with newly selected parameters.
@endnode
///
///   Bottom Row                                          //f
@node ASENSE-GADGETS-BOTTOM-ROW "ASense - Gadgets: Bottom Row"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-GADGETS-MIDDLE-ROW
@NEXT MAIN
@{b}@{u}Bottom row@{uu}@{ub} - buttons to cast @{b}dual@{ub} charts (with @{i}offsets@{ui}).

    These buttons are used to cast @{i}dual@{ui} charts (i.e. those that require data
  from both sides), unlike @{i}single@{ui} charts, which need data only from one side.
  @{u}Buttons from left to right@{uu}:
  '@{b}F@{ub}' - cast a @{"Davison relationship chart" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING} between 2 charts (data merge).
  '@{b}J@{ub}' - cast a @{"composite" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING} of 2 charts (arithmetic merge of coordinates).
  '@{b}C@{ub}' - cast a @{"coalescent chart" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING} between 2 charts (merge by @{i}harmonics@{ui}).
  @{b}(seven square buttons)@{ub} - cast a @{i}@{b}dual cyclic chart@{ub}@{ui} quickly.
      @{b}These buttons may be replaced in the future by a single '@{i}dual@{ui}' switch
    button, and then be cast as any other cyclic chart (with offset buttons
    from a middle row)@{ub}.This is only a temporary solution, because it is more
    convenient this way, and there was (still) enough free buttons for that.
  '@{b}Ef@{ub}' - create an @{"ephemeris" link ASENSE-CHARTS-EPHEMERIS} for time interval (@{i}dual@{ui} ephemeris).
      Starting time is a date/time from this chart, and the ending time is a
    date/time from the other chart.@{i}The accumulated time offsets for both sides
    are taken into account as well@{ui}.This option is NOT available from the menus.
  '@{b}2r@{ub}', '@{b}2c@{ub}' - the choice of @{"presentation modes" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION}.
    If none is selected, only 1 coordinate is presented (standard mode).
  '@{b}*@{ub}' - @{"Show Stars" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SHOW-STARS} switch (enables @{i}drawing of stars@{ui}).
  '@{b}Ľ@{ub}' - @{"Show in a Ring" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-RING} switch (enables @{i}@{b}double@{ub} charts@{ui}).
  '@{b}ř@{ub}' - @{"Very Tight Orbs" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC} switch (reduces the orbs by half).
  '@{b}Ec@{ub}', '@{b}Eq@{ub}, '@{b}Ho@{ub}' - the choice of @{"projection" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC} for aspects and draw.
      If none is selected, @{"3D aspects" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC} will be computed, and the required
    @{"zodiac" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC} will be drawn.
  '@{b}L+R@{ub}', '@{b}L+LR@{ub}', '@{b}L+RL@{ub}', '@{b}RL+R@{ub}', '@{b}LR+R@{ub}', '@{b}RL+LR@{ub}' - buttons to cast @{"synastry" link ASENSE-CHARTS-SYNASTRY}
    charts (@{i}with@{ui} offsets).
@endnode
///
@remark Project
/// Project                                               //f
@node ASENSE-MENUPROJECT "ASense - Menus: Project"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE
@{b}@{u}Project@{uu}@{ub} - About, I/O, stats, debug.

  @{b}About@{ub} - some important notes about the ASense.
  @{"Global Databases" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE} - external database support.
  - @{"Database Filters" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_FILTERS} - find the specific entries in a database.
  - @{"Sort Database by" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_SORT} - sort database entries by this parameter.
  @{"Sessions" link ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY} - the history of entered data strings.
  @{"Chart" link ASENSE-PROJECT-CHART} - saving of reports (data & picture(s)).
  @{"Stats" link ASENSE-PROJECT-STATS} - what has been used & how many times.
  @{"Debug" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DEBUG} - an easy way to capture bugs.
  @{"Hide" link ASENSE-PROJECT-HIDE} - menufy the ASense.
  @{b}Quit@{ub} - terminates the program.
@endnode
///
///   Database                                            //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE "ASense - Menus: Project Global Databases"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_FILTERS
@{b}@{u}Global Database@{uu}@{ub} - external database support.
  As of version @{b}v4.0+@{ub}, the ASense supports external databases.

    There is one database buffer which may be filled by loading a file into it,
  or by adding strings from a @{"string gadget" link ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING}. @{b}The entries may be browsed by
  the left/right arrow buttons@{ub}. They can also be selected by the @{i}pop-up@{ui} button.
  (The left/right arrows buttons @{b}from the @{i}keyboard@{ui}@{ub}, that is, NOT from the GUI!)
    Recalling of the stored values is possible from any of the sides...

  @{b}Load..@{ub} - load a previously created database.
    The @{"filters" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_FILTERS} will be preserved.
  @{b}Save..@{ub} - save the current database as a plain text file.
  @{b}Append@{ub} - flag to modify loading/saving process.
    If appending is enabled, database loading will append the current database
  instead of replacing it, whilst the saving will append the chosen file instead
  of replacing it.

  @{b}No Filters@{ub} - turn OFF the usage of database filters.
    @{i}When this item is checked@{ui}, the existing filters will remain in memory,
    but @{i}the current database will appear completely unfiltered@{ui}. Temporary
    removal of filters is useful when you wish to save the entire database
    and to conitnue the work later using the filtered entries only. There
    is no need to redefine the filters in this case, just use this option.
  @{b}Add Filter..@{ub} - define another filter for the database entries, and add
    it to the existing chain of already defined filters.
  @{b}Remove Filters@{ub} - flush the filters from memory, but keep the database.

  @{b}Flush@{ub} - flush the database buffer, (together with all defined filters).

    @{b}Statistics about the currently loaded database are displayed in a screen
  title area when the main window of ASense is the active one@{ub}. These include
  number of @{i}@{b}entries@{ub}@{ui} (@{i}total@{ui}, @{i}kept@{ui} and @{i}removed@{ui} ones), and number of @{i}@{b}filters@{ub}@{ui}.

  NOTE: @{b}Database files are the plain text files@{ub}, easily alterable. They may
    contain @{i}@{b}comments@{ub}@{ui}, which is their main difference from the @{"history files" link ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY}.
    Apart from that, @{i}duplicate entries are automatically removed@{ui} from the
    current database, unless they have different comments. This is NOT the
    case with duplicate @{"session" link ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY} entries in order not to tamper with history.
  NOTE: It is felt that the @{i}saving/loading of filters@{ui} is not of much use.
    hence this option is NOT implemented, and it is not planned to be.
      If you need this feature, make simple ARexx script(s) consisting of few
    'FILTER TYPE=...' commands. This will do the trick; and be readable...
@endnode
///
///     Database Filters                                  //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_FILTERS "ASense - Datebase: Filtering"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_SORT
@{b}@{u}Database Filters@{uu}@{ub} - find the specific entries in a database.

  @{u}The available types are@{uu}: (each filters a specific data field)
    @{b}Days Mons Year Cycl Cal Time TZ GLon GLat GAlt Temp Grd1 Grd2@{ub}
    @{b}Name Plac Comm@{ub} - types that perform string filtering ((sub)string search);
    @{b}Date JD@{ub} - types that filter several fields at once (@{i}day@{ui},@{i}mon@{ui},@{i}year@{ui} and @{i}zone@{ui}).

  String search may or may not be case sensitive, depending on user's choice.

  Filtering may be @{i}@{b}exclusive@{ub}@{ui}, meaning that the matching entries are to be
  removed, while the non-matching ones are to be kept.

  - @{b}Filtering to infinity@{ub} (one limit unspecified) is allowed for non-repeating
  @{i}fields@{ui}, like '@{i}years@{ui}'.

  - The @{i}repeating fields@{ui}, like '@{i}days@{ui}' (1..31, then again the same), can use the
  @{b}filtering over border@{ub}. By specifying something like @{b}25,6@{ub}, values from 25 to 6
  are going to be found (i.e. @{b}25,26,...5,6@{ub}).
@endnode
///
///     Database Sort                                     //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_SORT "ASense - Menus: Project Database Sort"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_FILTERS
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY
@{b}@{u}Database Sort@{uu}@{ub} - Sort database entries by this parameter (as indicated).

  @{u}The available parameters are@{uu}:
  - @{i}@{b}No Sorting@{ub}@{ui} - Do not sort the database.
  - @{i}@{b}Chart Name@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}name@{ui} (alphabetically).
  - @{i}@{b}Place Name@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}location's name@{ui} (alphabetically).
  - @{i}@{b}Julian Day@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}absolute julian day@{ui} (later values first).
  - @{i}@{b}Cycle@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}cycle@{ui} that the chart belongs to (later values first).
  - @{i}@{b}Time Zone@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}time zones@{ui} in order of appearance (E -> W).
  - @{i}@{b}E/W Coors@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by location's @{i}geographical longitude@{ui} (E -> W).
  - @{i}@{b}N/S Coors@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by location's @{i}geographical latitude@{ui}  (N -> S).
  - @{i}@{b}Altitude@{ub}@{ui}  - Sort by @{i}altitude@{ui} (high first).
  - @{i}@{b}Atm. Temp.@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by atmospheric @{i}temperature@{ui} (hot first).
  - @{i}@{b}Data Grade@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{"data grading" link ASENSE-GENERAL-DATA_GRADING} (best first).
  - @{i}@{b}Comment@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}comment@{ui} (alphabetically).
@endnode
///
///   Sessions                                            //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY "ASense - Menus: Project Sessions"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-CHART
@{b}@{u}Sessions@{uu}@{ub} - the record of the entered data strings.

    Whenever the user enters a string into string gadget, it's value is
  passed into history buffer and may be recalled by pressing the @{b}up/down@{ub}
  arrows while typing. The string gadget thus acts as a shell prompt.

  NOTE: @{b}Only actually @{i}entered@{ui} strings, and those acquired by pressing the '=±'
  button are remembered@{ub}. Those obtained by other string manipulating buttons
  in the first row ('@{b}Undo@{ub}', '@@{b}r@{ub}', '@{b}<-@{ub}', '@{b}->@{ub}'), @{i}@{b}are not@{ub}@{ui}, as the strings that
  they provide are the old ones, already stored elsewhere.

  NOTE: @{b}There is only ONE session buffer@{ub}, because it is not possible to
  type a string @{i}simultaneously@{ui} on both sides.(The history records time.)
    Recalling of the stored values is possible from any of the sides...

  @{b}Load..@{ub} - load a previously recorded session.
  @{b}Save..@{ub} - save the session as a history file.
  @{b}Append@{ub} - flag to modify loading/saving process.
    If appending is enabled, session loading will append the accumulated history
  instead of replacing it, whilst the saving will append the chosen file instead
  of replacing it.

  @{b}Flush@{ub} - flush the history buffer.

  Note: @{i}The history files are plain text files@{ui}, easily alterable.
    @{b}Only sane (valid) strings are being recorded@{ub}. The errors are ignored.
@endnode
///
///   Chart                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-CHART "ASense - Menus: Project Chart"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-STATS
@{b}@{u}Chart@{uu}@{ub} - saving of reports (data & picture(s)).

  @{b}Save Chart@{ub} - save chart with an automatically generated name, according
    to the relevant switches and tooltypes (explained below).
  @{b}Save Chart..@{ub} - prompts the user for a file name, and then saves the chart.

  @{u}Switches@{uu}:
  - @{b}Save as HTML@{ub} - if on, saves the report and picture as HTML file(s).
    If this switch is off, the reports are going to be saved as a plain text.
  - @{b}Save Data Tables@{ub} - if on, saves the displayed text in textfield as well.
    If this switch is off, only the chart's picture will be saved.
  - @{b}Overwrite?@{ub} - if on, overwrites the existing equaly named files without a
    warning, otherwise prompts the user if a file is going to be overwriten.

  @{u}Relevant tooltypes@{uu}:
  - @{b}TAPGIF_FILE@{ub} - full path to a @{b}tapgif@{ub} file (third party freeware executable
    required to create a gif picture from an iff file (temporarily created by
    the iff.library)).This file is supplied with the ASense.Place it wherever
    you want, and notify the ASense about its placement by this tooltype.
    Default is '@{i}tapgif@{ui}'.
  - @{b}SAVE_DIR@{ub} - path to a directory where the files are to be saved.
    '@{i}Project/Save Chart..@{ui}' changes this path to a new one, but this new path
    is NOT saved in a config file! Use the tooltype if you wish to change it.
    Default path is to use the @{b}ASense:map_shots@{ub} directory.
@endnode
///
///   Stats                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-STATS "ASense - Menus: Project Stats"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-PROJECT-CHART
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-DEBUG
@{b}@{u}Stats@{uu}@{ub} - what has been used & how many times.

    @{b}The ASense keeps track of how many time every menu item or gadget has
  been used by the user@{ub}.These usage statistics can afterward be used by a
  developer in various ways.
    For example, if there are some unused (or rarely used) pieces of the
  software, a developer may include a better manual or tutorial to explain
  these parts to users, or may focus the development to those parts of the
  software that the users really use and require.These statistics are here
  to easily point out which parts are the most interesting ones.
    Even more, the developer may choose to strip the unused parts from the
  subsequent versions in order to make the software smaller, cheaper and
  more efficient without burdening its size (and price) with the obscure
  features that rarely anyone ever uses.

    Therefore, please keep the ASense.stats file safe and write enabled.
  It is kept for your benefit.

    If you write a message to developer, please send the ASense.stats file
  as well.It may be helpfull...

  @{u}Relevant tooltypes@{uu}:

    Default is to keep the statistics in the '@{b}ASense.stats@{ub}' file.
@endnode
///
///   Debug                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-DEBUG "ASense - Menus: Project Debug"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-PROJECT-STATS
@NEXT ASENSE-PROJECT-HIDE
@{b}@{u}Debug@{uu}@{ub} - an easy way to capture bugs.

    If you find an unknown bug and you wish to report it to developer, there
  is an easy way to do it.If you are not using a @{b}KingCon@{ub} shell (or something
  similar (shell which has an ability to save the content of a console window)),
  then Start the ASense from a shell and redirect the output to a file

    1> ASense @{b}>ram:ASense.bugnotes@{ub}

  (Note: @{i}redirect to a file on a disk if there is a bug that causes a crash@{ui}.)

  Then,
    - @{b}adjust the configuration and save the config file@{ub} (@{i}Set/Settings/Save@{ui}..)
      as @{b}ASense_bugnotes.config@{ub} (or something like that),
    - turn ON the debug mode by selecting it from the menu (@{i}Project/Debug@{ui}),
    - reproduce the bug in as little steps as possible,
    - make a bugnote (@{i}Project/Make a note in debug@{ui}),
    (- reproduce other bugs if there are any and make notes about them as well,)
    - turn OFF the debug mode and close the ASense,
    - send the files @{b}ASense_bugnotes.config@{ub} and @{b}ASense.bugnotes@{ub} to developer.
      (If there are several of these files, enumerate them like
        @{b}ASense_bugnotes_000.config@{ub} and @{b}ASense_000.bugnotes@{ub} (add the number).)

      The @{i}subject@{ui} of the message should be: '@{i}@{b}Bugnotes from ASense@{ub}@{ui}'.

  Thank you for your support!

  NOTE: Before sending any bugs, please consult the @{"Known Bugs" link ASENSE-HISTORY-BUGS} chapter of
  the manual.Some of the 'bugs' may be hidden features...
@endnode
///
///   Hide                                                //f
@node ASENSE-PROJECT-HIDE "ASense - Menus: Project Hide"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@PREV ASENSE-PROJECT-DEBUG
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUPROJECT
@{b}@{u}Hide@{uu}@{ub} - menufy the ASense.

    In order to save chip memory if required, the ASense may be iconified.
  Actually, it can be @{b}menufied@{ub}, which means that in iconified state it will
  not appear as an icon on the workbench, but @{b}as a menu item on the @{i}Tools@{ui}
  menu on the workbench@{ub}.

    Additionally, '@{i}Project/Hide on Close@{ui}' menu item will (if turned on)
  @{i}force the ASense to become menufied whenever the main window is closed@{ui}.
  (The closure of this window would otherwise quit the program.) If this
  menu item is turned on, the only way to quit the program is to use the
  '@{i}Project/Quit@{ui}' menu item.

  Note: It is possible to start several instances of ASense by using the
  '@{i}Hide@{ui}' option.@{b}Although there can be only one active ASense screen, there
  can be upto 31 iconified versions of the program@{ub} (if anyone ever needs
  them).(The '@{i}Tools@{ui}' menu on the workbench has a limit of 32 items max...)
@endnode
///
@remark Decide
/// Decide                                                //f
@node ASENSE-MENUDECIDE "ASense - Menus: Decide"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@{b}@{u}Decide@{uu}@{ub}: Mayor decisions are held here.

    You have to chose between several options, and then to stick to your
  choice.Decisions are fundamental, and determine the way you approach
  astrology.
    Many of the available options are here for the academic reasons only,
  so the choices shouldn't be really difficult, if you have *any* experi-
  ence.Anyway, this guide will offer you some help in the process.
    Currently, these are the decisions that are considered to be of a
  fundamental importance:

    @{"Zodiac" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC} - Tropical, Sidereals (many options), or maybe Draconic.
    @{"House System" link ASENSE-DECIDE-HS} - The preferred system of house division.
    @{"Ephemeris" link ASENSE-DECIDE-EPHEMERIS} - Which ephemeris to use.

    @{"Year, Month, Day =" link ASENSE-DECIDE-YMD} - Choose how do you define 'year', 'month' and 'day'.
    @{"Arcs of Direction" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ARCS} - The preferred type of directions.

    @{"Sidereal Transits" link ASENSE-DECIDE-SID-TRANSITS} - A simple switch.
    @{"Coloring Policy" link ASENSE-DECIDE-COLORING-POLICY} - Tips on how to make your choices.

@endnode
///
/// Zodiac                                                //f
@node ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC "ASense - Menus: Decide Zodiac"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@PREV ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@NEXT ASENSE-ZODIAC-TROPICAL

  @{b}@{u}Basically, there are 2 choices@{uu}@{ub}: first one is to choose either a @{i}tropical@{ui}
  (moving) or a @{i}sidereal@{ui} (fixed) zodiac, and the second one is to choose
  either a normal zodiac (@{i}ecliptical@{ui}) or a @{i}draconic@{ui} one (as defined by the
  Moon's orbit).The latter is just a special flavour for special purposes.

    @{"Tropical" link ASENSE-ZODIAC-TROPICAL} (based on moving ecliptic) (Default.)
    @{"Sidereal" link ASENSE-ZODIAC-SIDEREAL} (based on fixed ecliptic)
    - @{"'Sidereal' vs 'Sid'" link ASENSE-SIDEREAL-VS-SID} dilema (accurate or not, that is the question)
    - @{"Anchor stars" link ASENSE-ANCHOR-STARS} (sidereal means anchored to the stars)
    - @{"'Sidereal'" link ASENSE-SIDEREAL-FLAVOURS} set of sidereal zodiac varieties
    - @{"'Sid'" link ASENSE-SID-FLAVOURS} set of sidereal zodiac varieties
    @{"Draconic" link ASENSE-ZODIAC-DRACONIC}, and @{b}sidereal draconic@{ub} (based on the Moon's orbit)

    House positions of the planets may change if a system that calculates
  them is based on the ecliptical or equatorial positions. @{b}Only a house
  system based on the local horizon's coordinates will always yield the
  same house positions@{ub}, no matter what zodiac is selected. The only such
  house system is @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-INTRO}, thus it is one more good reason for it's usage.

    If @{"3D mode" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC} for aspects is chosen (default mode, strongly suggested), then
  aspects are @{i}spatial@{ui}, and thus not plane related (i.e. identical for every
  zodiac that one may chose).
@endnode
///
///   Tropical zodiac                                     //f
@node ASENSE-ZODIAC-TROPICAL "ASense - Zodiac:Tropical"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@NEXT ASENSE-ZODIAC-SIDEREAL

    @{b}Tropical zodiac@{ub} is the one upon which the western astrology is based on.
  It defines it's beginning at 0° of *current* ecliptic, which is identical
  to 0° Aries at any time instant.Because of the effects of @{"precession" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-ECL},
  @{"nutation" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-ECL}, and the variations of ecliptical obliquity angle, the position
  of a current ecliptic is constantly changing.
    This is a default.

@endnode
///
///   Sidereal zodiac                                     //f
@node ASENSE-ZODIAC-SIDEREAL "ASense - Zodiac:Sidereal"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-ZODIAC-TROPICAL
@NEXT ASENSE-SIDEREAL-VS-SID

    @{b}Sidereal zodiac@{ub} is a snapshot of a tropical zodiac at some arbitrary time
  instant. Therefore, there is only one tropical zodiac, but many of the
  sidereal ones, all of them being a snapshots from different times. Some
  of them, however, are not a very precise snapshots, and they conflict
  with the reality. The errors are mostly due to the imprecisions of the
  old age instruments that were being used at the time, but some of them
  also have the philosophical reason to define the starting position of
  the zodiac at the place where it actually hasn't been at the moment.

    @{b}Sidereal astrology@{ub} cancels the effects of precession and (traditionally)
  neglects the nutation and the change of ecliptical obliquity over time. It
  is the basement of the eastern astrology. Since traditional usage of the
  sidereal astrology is imprecise due to above mentioned neglections, this
  software also offers a correct transformation to the @{b}fixed@{ub} ecliptic of
  some chosen or predefined date.

  @{u}Thus, there are 2 possibilities@{uu}:
  1. @{i}@{b}Traditional method@{ub}@{ui} - nutation and obliquity changes neglected, as well
      as the influence of precession on the planetary speeds. As a result,
      fixed objects on the sky, a Galactic centre for example, seem to move.
  2. @{i}@{b}Accurate method@{ub}@{ui} - rigorous computations, all above mentioned movements
      of the ecliptic correctly canceled, together with their influence on
      planetary speeds. Objects like Galactic center remain stationary in
      this mode, as they were intended to be. (Default.)

  These options are selectable from the @{"Choose Sid. Mode" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES} menu item.
@endnode
///
///     Sidereal vs Sid                                   //f
@node ASENSE-SIDEREAL-VS-SID "ASense - Zodiac: 'Sidereal' vs 'Sid' zodiacs"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-ZODIAC-SIDEREAL
@NEXT ASENSE-ANCHOR-STARS

@{b}@{u}Sidereal vs Sid@{uu}@{ub}:

    One may immediately notice that some sidereal zodiacs from a menu
  are marked '@{i}@{b}Sidereal@{ub}@{ui}', while the others have only '@{i}@{b}Sid@{ub}@{ui}' in their names.
  The main difference between them is that those marked with 'Sid' are not
  defined for the time when the shift ("@{i}the ayanamsha@{ui}") has been zero,
  but for some other fixed ecliptic, a time of which is given within the
  brackets behind a name.Consequently, @{b}zodiacs marked with 'Sid' are only
  suitable for traditional method of sidereal chart's calculation@{ub}, which
  gives incorrect results.An attempt to use @{i}accurate@{ui} sidereal computations for
  '@{i}Sid@{ui}' subset of shifts would first force everything to refer to the ecliptic
  mentioned in the brackets, and then a traditional method would be applied to
  give the planetary positions, as was the intention of the original authors
  of these '@{i}sid@{ui}' shifts.If you think that a year J1900 (1st Jan 1900 AD), or
  29th Dec 102 BC (~-100) is the most important moment ever, then this is a
  correct approach.
@endnode
///
///     Anchor stars                                      //f
@node ASENSE-ANCHOR-STARS "ASense - Zodiac: Anchor stars of sidereal zodiacs"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-SIDEREAL-VS-SID
@NEXT ASENSE-SIDEREAL-FLAVOURS

@{b}@{u}Anchor Stars@{uu}@{ub}:

    @{b}In ancient times it was unknown that the stars have their own proper
  motion, and they were considered to be 'fixed'@{ub}.So, the precessional
  movement of the heavens, once discovered, needed only to be anchored to
  some suitable star to be properly defined.That was what they thought at
  the time, and that is whereupon a word '@{b}Sidereal@{ub}', i.e. "@{i}@{b}anchored to the
  stars@{ub}@{ui}", came into existance.

    Several stars were chosen by different people from different times
  to play the part of an anchor.These are:

  - @{b}Spica@{ub}, brilliant first magnitude star, at ~29° Vir ... ~0° Lib,
  - @{b}Aldebaran@{ub} at 15° Tau, coupled with @{b}Antares@{ub} at 15° Sco,
  - @{b}Zeta Psc@{ub}, since it was the closest star to the Vernal point
  - @{b}Eta Psc@{ub}, because it has had the same R.A. as the Vernal point

    Due to the lack of sophisticated instruments, @{b}all star positions were
  rounded to the nearest 10'@{ub}, which has been a maximal available precision.

@endnode
///
///     'Sidereyal' subset                                //f
@node ASENSE-SIDEREAL-FLAVOURS "ASense - Zodiac: 'Sidereal' zodiacs "
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-ANCHOR-STARS
@NEXT ASENSE-SID-FLAVOURS
@{b}@{u}Standard ecliptics/eqinoxes@{uu}@{ub}: These are the ecliptics and equnoxes that are
  commonly used in astronomy to refer data to.Star catalogs are usually
  referred to the one of that is nearest to the time of their publication.
  @{u}They are@{uu}:
    J2000 - 2nd Jan 2000, noon,       UT (JD = 2451545.0)
    B1950 - 1st Jan 1950, 10:09:46.9, UT (JD = 2433282.42345905)
    J1900 - 1st Jan 1900, noon,       UT (JD = 2415020.0)

  Usage of these ecliptic/equinoxes might be usefull to astronomers.Just
  remember to select the @{"accurate mode" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES} of the sidereal computations.
  UPDATE: @{b}Accurate mode is @{i}forced@{ui} for these three ecliptics@{ub}. They are of
  no use to traditional siderealists anyway...

@{b}@{u}Sassanian zodiac@{uu}@{ub}: At the year of 556 AD, ancient astronomers/astrologers
  gathered in Persia to redefine their astronomy tables.Around that time
  the Vernal equinox should have coincided with 0°Ari, and so it was the
  appropriate time to recalibrate their data tables.Persians worshipped
  the Jupiter, and the most important event was the Jupiter's conjunction
  with the Sun.They thought that it was Jupiter, a supreme divine, who is
  responsible for the precession of equinoxes.Today we know this isn't
  true, but back then, they have had other opinion about it.
    (@{i}On the other hand, one should notice that Jupiter IS the largest
  planet, and alone contains more mass than the rest of the solar system
  put together@{ui}. Without the Sun, of course. (Which it was conjuncting.))

    As a coincidence, on the year 564 AD the above mentioned Jupiter - Sun
  conjunction took part only two days after the Vernal equinox, on 22nd
  Mar 564.These conjunctions happen once every, and perhaps every 100 years
  in such vicinity of the Vernal point.Although relatively rare, this was
  still quite frequent in comparing to the length of a precessional cycle
  of ~26,000 years.But, that wasn't all about it.@{b}@{i}On the year 564, about
  on time when the center of the apparent topocentric Sun entered the sign
  of Aries (i.e. crossed the Vernal point) it was the APPARENT noon at
  the site of ancient Babylon (44E26, 32N33).@{ui}@{ub}
    Aries ingress: @{b}20-Mar-564, 11:09:30 (+3:00:00) (UT)@{ub} (JD = 1927135.88691);
    Apparent noon: @{b}20-Mar-564, 12:09:45 (+3:00:00) (UT)@{ub} (JD = 1927135.92876).
  The dates here are expressed in @{i}Gregorian@{ui} calendar, be aware of that.

  (NOTE: @{b}Apparent culmination happens when a body achieves it's highest
  altitude for the day, which is close, but NOT identical, to the time when
  it crosses a local meridian.In the Sun's case, this is the time of the
  @{i}apparent noon@{ui}@{ub}, the time when shadows are the shortest during that day.)

    When the Sun culminated over Babylon, it was already crossed the Vernal
  point, for about 3' of arc.However, the best measurements of that time
  have had an error of 10' arc. Thus, for ancients, the Vernal Crossing
  and the culmination of the Sun were simultaneous.
    Now this was really a *HUGE* event, so they revised their tables.
    Upon those observationaal tables (which do not exist any more), others
  were derived later in history.Sassanians were the only ones who actually
  observed the heavens at the time when both sidereal and tropical zodiacs
  coincided and who made valuable notes.

    Astronomically, 2 zodiacs coincided in the year 560 (more or less).
  Four years of precession yields us some 3.5' of arc difference, well
  below the acceptable observational tolerance of 10 arc minutes.Thus,
  the above mentioned time was adopted as the beginning time for a new
  precessional cycle.

    Exact conjunction with the Jupiter took place @{b}@{i}2 days later, and if observed
  from the same spot (suburbs of ancient Babylon), Jupiter was just 1'
  of arc away to the west from the Sun, which was 32' wide at the time,
  when both bodies have had their local apparent culmination, some 10
  minutes of time after they have crossed the local meridian of place.@{ui}@{ub}

    The other advantage of this sidereal zodiac, apart from being very
  precisely defined, is that it doesn't depend on a position of any
  particular star.This is good because stars have their own proper motion
  and are not really fixed at all.Not in a long term anyway.

    @{b}This is a default sidereal zodiac@{ub}, one that is chosen if one selects
  a draconic sidereal zodiac without deciding which one of many to use.

@{b}@{u}Galactic Center at 0°Sgr@{uu}@{ub}: This sidereal zodiac is defined on a time when
  Galactic center entered a tropical sign of Sagitarius.Galactic center
  is a black hole with 2,600,000 sun masses in itself.It is the point
  around which everything in the Galaxy rotates, and due to that fact,
  it may be considered as the only really fixed and stable point of
  reference.At least within the scope of Milky Way.

    It's entering point to a sign of Sagitarius is taken arbitrarily,
  because it is the closest in time to the classicaly defined set of
  sidereal zodiacs.Still, it is several degrees away from them.

@{b}@{u}From given date@{uu}@{ub}: This one uses a date in the input string for it's
  starting points.Purpose of this is to enable sidereal corrected
  transits, sidereal returns and other similar things.There is no
  need for additional date inputs.Just select this one, and all
  time shifted charts (@{i}transits, progressions, directions, returns@{ui})
  will be corrected for the precession according to the preferred
  sidereal mode (accurate or traditional).
@endnode
///
///     'Sid' subset                                      //f
@node ASENSE-SID-FLAVOURS "ASense - Zodiac: 'Sid' zodiacs"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-SIDEREAL-FLAVOURS
@NEXT ASENSE-ZODIAC-DRACONIC
@{b}@{u}Hipparchan tradition@{uu}@{ub}: (Greek-Babylonian-Hindu)
  In his work, Hipparchos said "@{i}@{b}Aries rises, when Spica sets@{ub}@{ui}.", as observed
  from Rhodos, his home place, at 36° N latitude.From that place, Alp Ari,
  Bet Ari, Zet Psc and Spica looked at that time as if they are on a great
  circle.They were not, but star positions were rounded to 10' precision,
  so they appeared to be.Thus they anchored a Vernal point to be @{b}~20' E of
  Zet Psc@{ub}.(@{i}Hipparchos, ~129.5 BC@{ui}) (ecliptic from 24th Jun 129 BC, noon)

    Babylonians maybe had similar ideas at the same times, but they used a
  star @{b}Eta Psc@{ub}, which they said @{b}culminated together with the Vernal point
  (i.e, it has had a 0° of R.A.)@{ub}.(@{i}Babylon, ~130 BC@{ui}) (29th Dec 131 BC, noon)

    @{i}Ushashashi@{ui} hindu tradition has used @{b}Zet Psc itself as a Vernal point@{ub}.
  (One of many offests available from hindu tradition, but anchored to
  J1900 (1st Jan 1900, noon).

@{b}@{u}Babylonian tradition@{uu}@{ub}: Kugler and later Huber have found that there are
  also several other sidereal shifts used by the ancient babylonians.
  Several dates are available, thought to be anchored to Spica at ~29°,
  the all most probably stem from the @{b}Aldebaran/Antares at 15°Tau/15°Sco@{ub}
  couple.The errors in ancient documents caused by the rounding errors.
  (All of these shifts refer to the fixed ecliptic of 29th Dec 102 BC,
  midnight. @{b}Note that there is no year 0 BC, but there *is* a 0 year
  (astronomically speaking), so a year ~-100 is identical as ~101 BC@{ub}.)

@{b}@{u}Hindu tradition@{uu}@{ub}: Boom of sidereal astrology in the west at the beginning of
  XX century has yielded numerous shifts, taken from hindu tradition, all
  anchored to J1900 (1st Jan 1900, noon).
  Origins of them are unknown.

    @{i}@{b}Cyril Fagan@{ub}@{ui}, founder of modern sidereal astrology eventually came up
  with a shift that places @{b}Spica near 29° Vir@{ub}, which @{i}@{b}Donald Bradley@{ub}@{ui} later
  refined to be @{b}29° 6' 5''@{ub} (like if there was such precision in ancient
  times).As the most recent, this shift refers to the ecliptic of B1950
  (1st Jan 1950, 22:09:46.9).

@endnode
///
///   Draconic zodiac                                     //f
@node ASENSE-ZODIAC-DRACONIC "ASense - Zodiac:Draconic"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-SID-FLAVOURS
@NEXT ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC

    @{b}Draconic 'zodiac'@{ub} is defined by the (current) orbital plane of the
  Moon. It's starting point is the North Moon's node. This orbital plane
  is *very* volatile and doesn't have the shape of an ellipse at all,
  since it is heavily perturbed by the Sun. It's inclination to the plane
  of the ecliptic is about 5 degrees.

    @{b}Philosophically, if the Earth represents a human body, then Earth's
  satellite, the Moon, represents a human's soul, or @{i}psyche@{ui}@{ub}. Together,
  they make a system. @{b}The @{i}ecliptic@{ui} is a path of the Earth around the Sun
  and hence it represents a path of a human body@{ub} throughout it's life. On
  the other hand, @{i}@{b}draconic 'zodiac'@{ub}@{ui} is a (current) path of the Moon around
  the Earth, and, @{b}by the analogy with the ecliptic@{ub}, it @{b}represents a path
  of a human's soul@{ub}. Thus, it is used in @{b}Karmic astrology@{ub}, but it may also
  be used for @{i}emotional psychoanalysis@{ui} and for any other Moon related issue.

    Technically, planets are projected to the Moon's orbital plane, either to
  a current one or, in a case that a sidereal chart is required, to a Moon's
  orbital plane attached to the fixed ecliptic connected with a chosen
  @{"sidereal zodiac" link ASENSE-ZODIAC-SIDEREAL}.

    @{b}@{u}DO NOT CONFUSE THE 'SIGNS' OF DRACONIC ZODIAC WITH THE SIGNS OF REGULAR@{uu}@{ub}
  @{b}@{u}ECLIPTICAL ZODIAC!@{uu}@{ub} They have nothing in common with each other, except
  that identical glyphs were used to depict them.

    For the sake of conveniance, draconic houses are not computed.Instead, a
  regular house positions are calculated, as derived from a normal ecliptical
  planetary positions.Note that house positions would remain identical unless
  one chooses to replace the plane of the ecliptic with the plane of lunar
  orbit, in which case all house systems that depend in their definitions
  upon the position of the ecliptic would yield a different results.However,
  those which are horizon or equatorial based would suffer no changes at all.
  @{i}Campanus, Regiomontanus, Horizon, Meridian@{ui} and @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} house systems belong
  to the latter category, which is why the @{i}draconic houses@{ui} are NOT an option.
@endnode
///
/// Houses                                                //f
@node ASENSE-DECIDE-HS "ASense - Menus: Decide House System"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-ZODIAC
  @{b}@{u}House System@{uu}@{ub}: Daily division of the sky, as on the sundial.
    After defining a zodiac which one wishes to use, the second major decision
  one has to make is to choose between many different house systems. This
  issue has been a source of a great dispute among the astrologers throughout
  the history.
    @{i}@{b}The author of this software attempts to solve this problem once for all@{ub}@{ui},
  so the lenghty explanation follows:
                                 
  @{u}Chapters@{uu}:
    1. The @{"zodiac" link ASENSE-HS-ZODIAC} (origins, division)
    2. The @{"houses" link ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-ORIGINS} (origins)
    3. @{"Delineation" link ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-DELINEATION} of houses (origins)
    4. @{"Equal" link ASENSE-HS-EQUAL-HS} house system varieties
    5. @{"Porphyry" link ASENSE-HS-PORPHYRY} (final compromise of the old age)
    6. The @{"Arabs" link ASENSE-HS-ARABS} (advances that they made)
    6. @{"Next step" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} (Pseudo and true house systems)
    7. The Arabic house systems (@{"Albategnius" link ASENSE-HS-ALBATEGNIUS} and @{"Alcabitus" link ASENSE-HS-ALCABITUS})
    8. @{"Middle age's" link ASENSE-HS-MIDDLE-AGE} house systems (@{"Campanus" link ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS} and @{"Regiomontanus" link ASENSE-HS-REGIOMONTANUS})
    9. XVII century's house systems (@{"Morinus" link ASENSE-HS-MORINUS} and @{"Placidus" link ASENSE-HS-PLACIDUS})
   10. Clean pseudo house systems (@{"Horizon" link ASENSE-HS-HORIZON} and @{"Meridian" link ASENSE-HS-MERIDIAN})
   11. Modern times (@{"Gauquelin" link ASENSE-HS-GAUQUELIN}, @{"Koch" link ASENSE-HS-KOCH}, @{"Topocentric" link ASENSE-HS-TOPOCENTRIC}, @{"Krusinski" link ASENSE-HS-KRUSINSKI})
   12. @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} house system (first XXI century design)

  @{u}Appendix@{uu}:
    I  The @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST} (systems on trial of validity)
   II  @{"Special cases" link ASENSE-HS-SPECIAL_CASES} (houses within polar circle)
  III  @{"Extreme situations" link ASENSE-HS-EXTREME_POINTS} (poles and their vicinity)
   IV  @{"Test of the Polaris star" link ASENSE-HS-POLARIS-TEST} (house positions of stars)
    V  @{"Porphyry in Poland test" link ASENSE-HS-PORPYRY-TEST} (an interesting observation)
   VI  The comparative @{"results" link ASENSE-HS-RESULTS} (of the above tests)
  VII  @{"Conclusion" link ASENSE-HS-CONCLUSION} (the final advices)

 VIII  @{"Overview" link ASENSE_HS_OVERVIEW} of the house systems
@endnode
///
///   origins of zodiac                                   //f
@node ASENSE-HS-ZODIAC "ASense - House Systems: Origins of the Zodiac"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-ORIGINS

    The intention of zodiac is to define the @{b}yearly@{ub} path of the Sun across
  the sky. It is arbitrary divided onto @{i}12 equal signs@{ui}, each measuring a
  30° span. This has been done, because during the year we also have some
  @{i}12 synodic lunar months@{ui} (i.e. periods between 2 identical lunar phases).

    This was certainly among the first things that ancient skygazers have
  noticed. There is a slight discrepancy, but this has deliberately been
  ignored, because appart from the fact that the synodic lunar cycle lasts
  almost 30 days (29.53059 days currently), the ancient astronomers also
  have noticed that certain angles between planets are more important than
  the others. They called them '@{"aspects" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS}'.
    The main aspects are 0°, 180°, 90°, 120°, 60°, all being a plain
  multiplications of the number 30 with an integer.

    And so the zodiac (the ecliptic, which is the same) has been divided
  onto 12 equal parts. Names to these parts were given in accordance with
  the names of the constellations that have approximately coincided with
  them at the moment of history when this naming has been done. The fact
  that constellation have shifted away due to precession of equinoxes is
  irrelevant, because the @{i}@{b}signs of zodiac and constellations are two@{ub}@{ui}
  @{i}@{b}entirely different things@{ub}@{ui}.
    (It certainly makes things easier to say that a body is located on
  13° Sco, than to say that it is on 223° of ecliptic longitude, or
  (even worse) at 13° of the eight sign of zodiac.)

    Originally the zodiac has been a ring on the sky centered on the
  ecliptic and measuring 8° up and down from it. This is because other
  visible planets do not exactly follow it's path, but are inclined to
  it, and therefore have a latitude that differs from zero.

    Today, however the signs are lunes that strech from N to S pole of
  the ecliptic (i.e. slices of a sphere like mellon slices). These are
  actually a projections onto the ecliptic. So even the star Polaris
  has it's place on the zodiac in the sign of Gemini, although it is
  actually in the constellation of Ursa Minor, because its current
  ecliptic longitude of ~88° puts it at the end of the Gemini sign.
  (In @{i}tropical@{ui} zodiac of course.)

@endnode
///
///   origins of houses                                   //f
@node ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-ORIGINS "ASense - House Systems: Origins of the houses"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-ZODIAC
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-DELINEATION

    The intention of houses is to describe a @{b}daily@{ub} path of the Sun across
  the sky. Since the zodiac has already been divided onto 12 equal parts
  the first idea was to also divide a daily path of the Sun onto twelve
  parts. But there, a problem arised.

    Daily path of the Sun is not at all as uniform as is it's yearly
  glide across the ecliptic. If observed on a sundial (which was the
  original instrument for time measuring), equal division would cause
  irregular time lengths to occur, and unequal division was overly too
  complicated. From this original conflict stems the variety of house
  systems proposed over centuries of it's consideration.

    Additional problem comes from the fact that the length of a day is
  unequal during seasons, and across different geographical latitudes.
  This was way too complicated for the ancient scholars, who had no math
  skills and tools at the time, other than plain algebra and geometry.
  So, they opted for the simplest solution: simple division onto 12 equal
  parts.

    Both day and night were divided onto 12 equal parts on the time of
  the eqinoxes, when day and night are of equal lengths, and this division
  held throughout the history.Therefore, today we have a 24 hours day
  (we have chosen to measure it that way).

    A day begins with the sunrise and finishes with the sunset, when the
  night begins. So, the start of the houses has chosen to be the Sun's
  ascensional point (i.e. the point where the path of the Sun, the
  ecliptic, crosses the horizon). The direction was chosen to be in the
  direction of the ecliptic (arbitrary), since this was considered to be
  more appropriate at the time. Once made, a decision held.
    (All house systems follow this rule, except for Gauqelin sectors,
  but those are really a Placidus house system taken in reverse and
  divided onto 36 instead of 12 parts for the purpose of statistical
  measuring.)

@endnode
///
///   delineation of houses                               //f
@node ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-DELINEATION "ASense - House Systems: Delineation of houses"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-ORIGINS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-EQUAL-HS

    The '@{i}houses@{ui}' represented different areas of human activity. @{i}@{b}The
  acitivity that most often took place at a certain part of a day was
  attributed to a house in which the Sun was usually found during that
  part of a day@{ub}@{ui}.

  - @{i}Children@{ui} are often born before dawn, and so the @{b}first house@{ub} became
  the house of @{i}beginning@{ui} (sunrise also starts a day), and of a @{i}body of
  a perso@{ui}n.

  - @{i}Marriage@{ui} was consumed at sunset, so this activity fell into @{b}seventh
  house@{ub}.

  - @{i}Deaths from natural causes@{ui} mostly occured around 4 pm, so this was
  connected with @{b}8th house@{ub}, which also became a @{i}house of sex@{ui}, because
  rapes and pillages after the battles took place at that time. For the
  same reason it became a house @{i}of other people's money@{ui}.

  - @{i}Executions of prisoners@{ui} were held at dawn, so they were attributed
  to @{b}12th house@{ub}, which also became a house @{i}of convicts, prisons and other
  conceiled institutions@{ui}. An execution is an action of a sword, so that
  time also became associated with the @{i}medical operations@{ui}, since at those
  times they were also being done with the swords (knives, axes, and other
  weapons).

  - @{i}Trials@{ui} were held after the lunch, so they belonged to @{b}9th house@{ub}, and
  since this is the warmest time of a day, this became a house @{i}of religion,
  and of rulership and nobility@{ui}. Priests and rulers were the guardians of
  a wisdom, so the @{i}higher education@{ui} was attributed to this house as well.

  - Most important work was being done when a sunlight was most intense,
  so @{i}carrier@{ui} was connected with a @{b}10th house@{ub}.

  - First @{i}social contacts@{ui} with friends and neighbours occured early in
  a day, so they fell into @{b}11th house@{ub}.

  - @{i}Cattle, the treasure of ancient times@{ui}, was taken care of very early
  in a day, hours before a sunrise, so the @{b}second house@{ub} became a house of
  @{i}money and food@{ui}.

  - @{i}Slaves@{ui} went to bed after their masters, which means after the dark,
  and so a @{b}sixth house@{ub} became their house and also a house of @{i}pets and
  common workers and their work@{ui}, since they all were a same category at
  those times.

  - @{i}Wild parties@{ui} of the nobles were held deeply to the night, so
  they were attributed to a @{b}5th house@{ub}, which became a house of
  @{i}common pleasures and enjoyment and relaxation@{ui}.

  - @{b}First child@{ub} is attributed to a @{i}5th house@{ui}, because a loosing of
  virginity usually took place during the wild orgies held by the
  nobles at a time of house 5. With no contraception, this often
  led to conception.
  - @{b}Second child@{ub} was attributed to a @{i}7th house@{ui}, because it is a house
  of marriage, from which a children should stem.
  - @{b}Third child@{ub} was attributed to a @{i}9th house@{ui}, to follow the pattern,
  and to honour the goverment.
  - @{b}Forth child@{ub} went to @{i}11th house@{ui}, because women were shared between
  friends in some cultures and in some others the women were not so
  much loyal to their husbands, especially when they went to war and
  never returned, leaving them with a pack of little children of whom
  they had to take care of.
    And so on, the pattern goes around a circle...

  - @{b}Third house@{ub} is the house of @{i}brothers and sisters and close
  neighbours@{ui}, because at a time of darkness, they were the only
  ones who shared a humble (ancient) room (and maybe the same
  bed if they have had one). Between the illiterate people, the
  basic knowledge was being thought within a family by the family
  elders, and since a third house among all houses has the largest
  association with a family, the @{i}basic education@{ui} went there.

  - The time of @{i}the thickest darkness@{ui} (the @{b}4th house@{ub}) was associated
  with @{i}graves, tombs, sleep@{ui}, but also with the @{i}political parties
  and states@{ui}, since the common folks usually knew nothing about their
  affairs and murky businesses (and were not supposed to know).
  It is also a house of @{i}homes@{ui}, because the homes of other people
  and the activities that are going there are @{i}@{b}private@{ub}@{ui}, and therefore
  envailed into obscurity and darkness for all outsiders. Perfect
  description of a 4th house.

@endnode
///
///   equal HS                                            //f
@node ASENSE-HS-EQUAL-HS "ASense - Houses: Equal House Systems"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-DELINEATION
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-PORPHYRY

    Without knowledge of anything better, the ancients divided the
  ecliptic onto @{b}12 equal parts, and the start was at the ascendant@{ub},
  and called these parts '@{"houses" link ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-DELINEATION}'.

    The second most important point on the Sun's path is the point
  of it's @{i}culmination@{ui}, which happens when it crosses the meridian
  of the place during it's diurnal movement. This point is called
  @{b}MC@{ub}, and the opposite point in the zodiac is called @{b}IC@{ub}.
    MC is approximately located 90° (equatorial) from the ascendant,
  and is the natural beginning of the 10th house. However, 90° on
  equator is something else when projected onto the ecliptic, and
  so there lies a discrepancy: MC is not at the start of the 10th
  house if the equal houses along the ecliptic have started from the
  ascendant. So, to solve this issue, those who considered the MC
  more important point than the ascendant, placed the @{b}beginning of
  the 10th house at MC, and then proceeded with the equal division
  along the ecliptic@{ub}.
    This version of house division therefore has a discrepancy
  between the ascendant and the start of the 1st house.

    @{u}There are other varieties of the equal house system with the@{uu}
  @{u}division on the ecliptic@{uu}:

  - @{i}@{b}Ptolemy@{ub}@{ui} thought that the day begins when the sunrise ends
  (i.e when the Sun is no longer red), which happens several degrees
  up from the ascendant, and so in his house system, the point
  @{b}5° up from the ascendant (across the ecliptic) became the start
  of the 1st house@{ub}.

  - @{i}@{b}Vedic@{ub}@{ui} system (after Vehlow) does the same, but they @{b}used 15°
  as an offset@{ub}. They probably have noticed the same thing that
  Gauquelin once did in his research: @{i}@{b}the space around the angles@{ub}@{ui}
  @{i}@{b}is important@{ub}@{ui}.
    Thus, they shifted the house edges.
    (@{b}Angles@{ub} are @{i}ascendant@{ui}, @{i}descendant@{ui} (the opposite point from
  the ascendant across the ecliptic), @{i}MC@{ui} and @{i}IC@{ui}.)

  - Finally the last variety present in this software places
  the tip of the @{b}1st house at the beginning of the zodiac sign
  preceeding it@{ub}.
    This is just a variety on the theme, one with the idea that
  if the houses exist, they should coincide with the signs of
  zodiac and not to intersect them.
    Since it is an equal house system with the division on the
  ecliptic, the houses are equal with whole signs, and thus the
  name: @{i}@{b}Whole@{ub}@{ui} house system.

    @{i}@{b}First 2@{ub}@{ui} equal house systems above have @{i}@{b}failed@{ub}@{ui} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST},
  @{i}@{b}Ptolemy@{ub}@{ui} house system has @{i}@{b}partially fullfilled it@{ub}@{ui} (only one planet
  OK, the other in the wrong house), but the @{i}@{b}last 2 have passed it@{ub}@{ui}.

    However, although they passed the test on that issue, they are
  still only @{"pseudo" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house systems, and therefore they provide only
  a greatly simplified, and thus a false picture of the local sky.

@endnode
///
///   porphyry + Neo-porphyry orig                        //f
@node ASENSE-HS-PORPHYRY "ASense - House System: Porphyry"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-EQUAL-HS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-ARABS

    @{b}Porphyry@{ub} (233 - 333 AD) was a neoplatonists whose house system is
  the last one from the old age. Soon after him, the Roman Empire
  crumbled, and the barbanians took the world.

    To solve the Asc - MC issue he made a compromise: He placed the
  ascendant at the tip of the 1st house and the MC at the tip of the
  10th house, and then divide each of the quadrants into 3 equal parts
  on the ecliptic. Angles were correctly placed, and the division onto
  quadrants was a compromise, which yielded two different sizes for the
  houses, none of them being a 30° span, except by accident.

    In 1994, Walter Pullen, the author of astrolog, has made an attempt
  of modernizing this ancient house system by using today's math tools
  to make the house sizes more equal among themselves, but to still
  hold the division onto quadrants.
    He calls his house system a '@{"Neo-Porphyry" link ASENSE-HS-NEO-PORPHYRY}'.
  (Under the link there is the original lenghty description of that house
  system, as posted by the author on the alt.astrology newsgroup.)

    Both of the Porphyry house systems have failed the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.

@endnode
@node ASENSE-HS-NEO-PORPHYRY "ASense - House System: Neo-Porphyry"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-PORPHYRY
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-ARABS

    Here is the original description of the '@{b}Neo-Porphyry@{ub}' house system,
  as posted by the author on the @{i}alt.astrology@{ui} newsgroup.

  @{b}Newsgroups@{ub}: @{i}alt.astrology@{ui}
  @{b}Date@{ub}: 1994-02-21 00:49:59 PST
  @{b}Subject@{ub}: @{i}A new system of house division@{ui}.
                                   @{i}@{ui}
    I'd like to describe a new system of house division that has
  occurred to me. I've been calling it the @{i}Neo-Porphyry@{ui} system of
  houses in that it is similar in philosophy to the standard Porphyry
  system. What I did was try to logically @{i}deduce@{ui} a good system from
  scratch and then find a way to compute it. This way doesn't seem to
  already be an established method of house division (although I could
  be wrong) hence I made up the name and would like to describe it here:

    House systems in general are a way of dividing the local horizon
  into the twelve zones or houses. Each house is always about 30
  degrees, however the Earth's tilt to the ecliptic among other things
  can make them vary and cause the complications. There are two main
  points which are clearly defined without ambiguity: the Ascendant
  (Asc) and the Midheaven (MC). Most systems of division have the 1st
  house the same as the Asc and the 10th the same as the MC. Some, such
  as the Equal house system, can disassociate these. I personally like
  their definitions, and hence for my deduced system I started with the
  angular cusps the same as or opposite to the standard Asc and MC.

    Most of the differences between systems start when we try to
  place the eight remaining @{i}minor@{ui} cusps, or, not counting opposing
  cusps, we have to determine where to place four points on the
  zodiac. The Asc and MC are usually about 90 degrees apart from each
  other, although this changes over time, with the picture being that
  the distance wobbles back and forth like a swing. Now, I am looking at
  this from the astrologer's point of view when displayed in a wheel
  chart, i.e. that we have our 360 degree zodiac, with the Asc and MC
  visibly plotted at known points, with the angle between them varying,
  and we then want to find logical points to place the other cusps on
  the wheel. Since we are trying to determine the actual zodiac
  positions of where to plot the minor cusps, I am treating the zodiac
  or ecliptic, as the item to be focused upon, hence this is a
  @{i}subdivision along the ecliptic@{ui} system, like Porphyry itself is.

    The Porphyry system of houses takes a very simple approach to
  this division. In Porphyry houses, we simply trisect the angle between
  the Asc and MC and use that to plot the 11th and 12th cusps, with a
  similar action being done between all the other angles, as shown below:

                            Porphyry Houses.
  Asc        12th       11th        MC        9th        8th
   |          |          |          |          |          |
   +----------+----------+----------+----------+----------+----------
         ^         ^          ^          ^          ^          ^
    \    x         x          x    / \   x'         x'         x'   /
     ----- Trisect this angle -----   ----- Trisect this angle -----

    Now, I don't think this is a perfect system, as it is
  @{i}discontinuous@{ui} around the zodiac. In other words, we have a
  particular angle x which is the same size of the 10th, 11th, and 12th
  houses, and a second angle x' which is the size of the 9th, 8th and
  7th, then we go back to x for the 6th and so on. We have a
  discontinuous @{i}jump@{ui} in relative sizes when we hit the angles which
  seems inappropriate for our smooth circular zodiac.

    My revised model is to look at the zodiac as a chart wheel, with
  the angles plotted on them. As the angle between the Asc and MC
  changes the minor cusps between them compress or expand like an
  accordion. Now, I see this compression as happening all around the
  zodiac, where each house influences the ones next to it. In other
  words, the Asc and MC are merely by-products of the model, and aren't
  special points, where, using our accordion model, @{i}hands@{ui} are applied
  at the angles which causes an equal trisection compression of each
  quadrant. In other words, if we know there has to be compression in
  the upper left quadrant and expansion in the upper right, then the
  amount of this @{i}force@{ui} should gradually change as one moves from one
  to the other. The angles aren't exactly trisected, but vary based on
  whether the particular house is @{i}on the edge of@{ui} or @{i}in the middle of@{ui}
  a compressed quadrant. The following diagram, based on the assumption
  that the Asc/MC angle is presently less than average or 90 degrees,
  should make this paragraph more clear as to how to divide the houses:

                          Neo-Porphyry Houses.
  Asc        12th       11th        MC        9th        8th
   |          |          |          |          |          |
   +----------+----------+----------+----------+----------+----------
        ^          ^          ^          ^          ^          ^
      small     smaller     small      large      larger     large
      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle

    The question now becomes how to properly and technically divide
  the quadrants, and determine what the difference between the @{i}small@{ui}
  and @{i}smaller@{ui} angles should be based on our present angular difference
  between the Asc and MC. A more mathematical way of looking at these
  angles is as follows:

                          Neo-Porphyry Houses.
  Asc        12th       11th        MC        9th        8th
   |          |          |          |          |          |
   +----------+----------+----------+----------+----------+----------
        ^          ^          ^          ^          ^          ^
      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle
       x+a         x         x+a        x+b        x+c        x+b

    This is where x is size of the smallest house, i.e. in the middle
  of a compressed quadrant, and a, b, and c are increasingly large delta
  angles such that x+c is the size of the largest house in the middle of
  a expanded quadrant. Now, we just need to reason out what logical
  values for a, b, and c could be. We could have them just be linearly
  increasing values, i.e. where b = 2a and c = 3a. However this would
  have a similar problem to standard Porphyry in that we would have
  @{i}discontinuities@{ui}. This time the problem is that we have a linear
  @{i}velocity@{ui} change from the middle of each quadrant which keeps on
  suddenly negating itself at these points.

    The solution is to have a gradual change starting in the middle
  of a compression and increasing to where we level off as we near the
  middle of the expansion and vice versa. As this is a circular wheel we
  are dealing with and we want a continuous function which starts at
  zero, rises, rises at a faster rate, and levels off then descends in
  the same way, and on around the circle, the obvious function to use is
  a sine wave. Applying the sine wave to our diagram above, we start
  with the most compressed house at the bottom of the sine wave, and go
  up the wave to the maximum point. The following shows 180 degrees of a
  sine wave, showing common angles, the sines of those angles, and
  finally some of the sine values adjusted but still proportionate so
  that they run from 0 at the minimum to 1 at the maximum to be in line
  with our diagram:

  angle     : -90     -60     -30   0  30      60     90
  sin(angle):  -1  -sqr(3)/2  -0.5  0  0.5  sqr(3)/2   1
  adjusted  :   0              1/4 1/2 3/4             1

    So if we give the minimum point the 11th house (whose angle is x
  + zero), and the maximum point the 8th house (whose angle is x + 1 or
  x + 1c), then we have two more points to plot along the sine curve to
  give us the ratios relative to @{i}c@{ui} of the 10th and 9th houses. The
  nice thing is that trisecting the 180 degrees gives us 60 degrees
  each, which in our graph above gives us the sines of -30 and +30
  degrees, which are conveniently + and - 1/2, which doesn't require any
  trig terms even though we still have our sine curve properties. With
  the adjusted values we can give the 10th house 1/4 or let a = c/4, and
  give the 9th house 3/4 or let b = (3/4)c. Using @{i}z@{ui} as our variable
  for the difference between the largest and smallest house instead of
  @{i}c@{ui} we can re-express our house division as follows:

                          Neo-Porphyry Houses.
  Asc        12th       11th        MC        9th        8th
   |          |          |          |          |          |
   +----------+----------+----------+----------+----------+----------
        ^          ^          ^          ^          ^          ^
      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle
     x+(1/4)z      x       x+(1/4)z   x+(3/4)z     x+z      x+(3/4)z

    Now we just need to determine the values of x and z (relative to
  the present angular distance between the Asc and MC which is always
  easily available and which we'll call @{i}d@{ui}). By definition and from the
  diagram looking at the upper left quadrant we know that 3x+(1/2)z =
  d. And, looking at the entire upper hemisphere we have the identity
  that 6x+3z = 180. Solving for x and z in these two equations gives us
  x = (1/2)d-15 and z = d-90. We now have all the information we need
  to compute all the cusps in our Neo-Porphyry house system based on the
  positions of the Asc and MC! Note that when d = 90, i.e. when the Asc
  and MC are exactly at right angles to each other, x = 30 degrees and z
  = 0, giving us an equal 30 degrees for each house and giving
  Neo-Porphyry the same results as Porphyry and Equal houses for this
  case. Note also it's always the case that x-z = 30. Hence we only
  need one variable in addition to d to express the sizes of each
  house. If we simply let y = (d-90)/4, then we can express the sizes of
  all the houses (in a symmetric form which works whether Asc-MC is > 90
  or > 90, i.e. whether the upper left quadrant is compressed or
  expanded) relative to y as follows:

                          Neo-Porphyry Houses.
  Asc        12th       11th        MC        9th        8th
   |          |          |          |          |          |
   +----------+----------+----------+----------+----------+----------
        ^          ^          ^          ^          ^          ^
      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle      angle
    30-(1/4)y  30-(1/2)y  30-(1/4)y  30+(1/4)y  30+(1/2)y  30+(1/4)y

    The complete computation can be easily expressed as a computer
  algorithm. For that matter, this can be done by hand almost as easily
  as Porphyry itself as it only requires one division and three
  additions for each cusp. Here is an @{i}Astrolog format@{ui} C language
  function to compute Neo-Porphyry houses:

  void HousePorphyryNeo()
  {
    real delta;
    int i;

    delta = (MinDistance(MC, Asc) - DEGQUAD)/4.0;
    house[_LIB] = Mod(Asc+DEGHALF); house[_CAP] = MC;
    house[_AQU] = Mod(house[_CAP] + 30.0 + delta   + SD);
    house[_PIS] = Mod(house[_AQU] + 30.0 + delta*2 + SD);
    house[_SAG] = Mod(house[_CAP] - 30.0 + delta   + SD);
    house[_SCO] = Mod(house[_SAG] - 30.0 + delta*2 + SD);
    for (i = _ARI; i < _LIB; i++)
      house[i] = Mod(house[i+6]-DEGHALF);
  }

    There you have it! This system of houses is simple and easy to
  compute, but yet produces results very close to several other common
  house systems. The idea came to mind last Sunday the 13th. I'd be
  interested in any comments of approval or disapproval, especially from
  those who commonly use Porphyry houses (this means you Brian! :) If
  there's enough interest I might even stuff it in the next Astrolog.

  #+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#
  +    Walter D. @{i}Cruiser1@{ui} Pullen   |   cruiser1@stein.u.washington.edu    +
  #+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#+#

@endnode
///
///   Arabs                                               //f
@node ASENSE-HS-ARABS "ASense - Arabs: Advances that they made"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-PORPHYRY
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE

    After several hundred years of dark ages in Europe, the Arabs got
  civilized, and created a strong civilization which in turn enabled
  further advancements in the fields of science.

    Among the other things @{i}@{b}the Arabs improved mathematics a lot@{ub}@{ui}. They
  invented the arabic numbering system that we currently use and the
  cyphers assigned to it.
    (No real math with the Roman numbers was possible.)

    They also invented @{i}trigonometry@{ui} (sin, cos, tg,...), which severely
  helped the developments in the field of astronomy.

    In 770 AD an Indian astrologer came to Baghdad and found the
  Arabic astrology. First they started translating the old Greek
  and Latin manuscripts and later they wrote many of their own.

    Since the sky in a desert is clear, and the dunes are boring and
  useless, they gazed the skies during desert nights, and as a result
  today most of the named @{"stars" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-SELECT-STARS" 0} on the sky hold names that the Arabs
  once gaved to them.

    They also invented the system of 'lots' (i.e. '@{"Arabic parts" link ASENSE-SELECT-PARTS}' as are
  called today), actually the collection of the named angles usually
  starting at the ascendant, and proceeding over ecliptic to a point
  that had the same distance from the start, as was the distance
  between some two planets. The planets gave the meaning to a part.
  Today, the only part in common use is a part of Fortune, but this
  software currently also provides the part of Marriage, and in
  future will probably include all known parts as they were defined
  by Arabs at the time.

@endnode
///
///   pseudo & true                                       //f
@node ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE "ASense - Houses: Pseudo and true house systems"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-ARABS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-ALBATEGNIUS

    @{i}@{b}Pseudo@{ub}@{ui} house systems had their poles at the poles of the ecliptic.
  In this situation, even when the ascendant is the tip of the 1st
  house, the horizon does not coincide with the line that divides the
  12th from the 1st house, and the same is true with the MC, even
  when MC coincides with the tip of the 10th house.
    Therefore, a planet with latitude that differs from zero, may
  have been placed into 1st house, although it was actually above
  the horizon.
    All of the systems mentioned so far were the pseudo house systems,
  since the math skills of the ancients were not good enough to provide
  anything better.
    (No real math with the Roman numbers was possible.)

    The invention of @{i}trigonometry@{ui} by the Arabs enabled them to design and
  calculate @{i}@{b}true@{ub}@{ui} house systems (i.e. those whose poles are the poles
  of the @{i}prime verticale@{ui}). The advantage of those house systems is
  the true placement of planets above or below the horizon and left
  or right from the meridian.

    From the Arabs, we have inherited 2 systems of house divisioning,
  '@{"Albategnius" link ASENSE-HS-ALBATEGNIUS}' and '@{"Alcabitus" link ASENSE-HS-ALCABITUS}'.

@endnode
///
///   Arabic HS                                           //f
@node ASENSE-HS-ALBATEGNIUS "ASense - House system: Albategnius"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-ALCABITUS

    The name '@{b}Albategnius@{ub}' is a shortcut that comes from a lenghty name
  @{i}@{b}Abu-'ab'dullah Muhammad ibn Jabir Al-Battani@{ub}@{ui} (858? - 929), an Arabic prince,
  mathematician and astronomer (also astrologer, which was the same at the
  time).

    Al-Battani was born at Haran (Turkey), and died near Samara (Iraq).
  He discovered (among other things) @{i}the moving of the Sun's aphel@{ui} (self
  rotation of the ecliptical ellipse). He also designed a system of house
  divisioning for the astrology, the very first of the @{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} systems.

    In his system poles are the poles of prime verticale (true), the
  division occurs on the prime verticale, starts at ascendant, and
  edges of the houses are found by trisecting the declination of the
  prime verticale. The planes that go through these points of trisection
  and above mentioned poles are the borders of the houses.

    This house system is not yet on the menu of this software, but it
  will be included in the future.

@endnode
@node ASENSE-HS-ALCABITUS "ASense - House system: Alcabitus"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-ALBATEGNIUS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-MIDDLE-AGE

    @{b}Alcabitus@{ub} is an Arab from XII century. The house system itself may
  not be his work, but he was the one who wrote about it, and so it
  currently holds his name. The house system itself may have been
  created in the X century at the earliest.

    There are few references on the www that it may stem from the
  I century AD Arab Alcabitius, and that it was the system used by
  old Greeks, but it was hard to believe.
    First, there were NO Arabs at the time, only Romans, Egyptians,
  Numibians, Persians,...
    Second, math tools from that era were not sufficiently good to
  provide necessary calculations, since trigonometry was still unknown.
    (No real math with the Roman numbers was possible.)

    Once, when the Arabs adopted atrology, they translated the old
  manuscripts. It is quite possible, that they also replaced the old
  equal house systems used by the Greeks, with their newly invented
  one (the Alcabitus house system). Somehow, this maybe got mixed
  with the old ones, and a 1,000 years later, people who discovered
  them thought that they were made by the Greeks.
    This is only an opinion, however.

    The system itself has it's poles on the prime verticale (@{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} one),
  division occurs on the equatorial arcs of ascendant, which are trisected,
  and it's start is at the ascendant. The planes that go through these
  points of trisection and above mentioned poles are the borders of
  the houses.

    Although it is a true one, this system does not pass the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.

@endnode
///
///   Middle age                                          //f
@node ASENSE-HS-MIDDLE-AGE "ASense - Houses: Middle ages"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-ALCABITUS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS

    Once the Europeans got civilized again during the Middle ages, they
  started collecting their long lost knowledge again (at least the rare
  literate scholars did). They observed the glorious civilization of the
  Arabs, and learned from them throgh cultural exchange and trade that
  took place. Among other things, they also rediscovered the astrology.

    Eventually, some of them mastered enough knowledge to be able to do
  some innovative work. As a result of the confrontation with the house
  system problem, several solutions were offered by them during those
  times. Before the invention of the printing press 2 new house systems
  were invented. Today, they are called '@{"Campanus" link ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS}' and '@{"Regiomontanus" link ASENSE-HS-REGIOMONTANUS}'.

@endnode
@node ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS "ASense - House systems: Campanus"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-MIDDLE-AGE
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-REGIOMONTANUS

    @{i}@{b}Giovanni di Campani@{ub}@{ui} (1293 - 1396), mathematician and astrologer
  who was a chaplain and physician to Pope Urban IV and to several of
  his successors. He invented the 'Campanus' house system.

    This invention was also attributed to @{i}@{b}Joseph@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}Mathew Campanus@{ub}@{ui},
  physicians who published the tables for this house system in 1495.

    The invention of printing press came too late for a Campanus
  house system, so the lack of the house tables restricted it's
  popularity.

    @{b}Campanus@{ub} is a @{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house system with @{i}@{b}clean@{ub}@{ui} geometrical definition.
  Poles are the poles of prime verticale, start is at the ascendant,
  and the division is equal division of the prime verticale itself.
  This means that spacing of 30° on the prime verticale creates
  points, which, when coupled with the poles of the prime verticale
  define the planes of the house borders.
    Their intersection points with the ecliptic, however, are NOT
  equaly spaced.

    '@{b}Clean@{ub}', as mentioned above means that all of the houses have
  the same @{b}volume@{ub}. This is true for all equal house systems
  mentioned before, but not for the other true system. It is also
  true for the '@{"Meridian" link ASENSE-HS-MERIDIAN}' , and '@{"Horizon" link ASENSE-HS-HORIZON}' house systems.
  (The latter 2 house systems will be talked about later in this text.)

    However, although it may look nicer, it is not at all neccessary
  for a house system to be '@{i}clean@{ui}' to work.
    In fact, Campanus house system @{i}@{b}fails@{ub}@{ui} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}, and the other two
  mentioned above do so also.

@endnode
@node ASENSE-HS-REGIOMONTANUS "ASense - House systems: Regiomontanus"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-MORINUS

    @{i}@{b}Johann Muller@{ub}@{ui} (1436 - 1476), with the pseudonym '@{i}Regiomontanus@{ui}', as
  derived from the Latinized name of his birth town @{i}Königsberg@{ui}, Franconia,
  was a German mathematician and astronomer.

    He introduced the arabic trigonometry and algebra to Germany,
  translated the '@{i}Almagest@{ui}' and published the ephemeris later used
  by Columbus. Due to his reputation, he was summoned to Rome by
  Pope Sixtus IV to reform the calendar, but, unfortunately, he
  died there by plague without being able to finish his task.

    @{b}Regiomontanus@{ub} is a @{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house system, since it's poles are those
  of the prime verticale, the division occurs on the equator as an equal
  spacing of 30° for each house. Start is at the ascendant. Planes that
  pass through these points and the poles of prime verticale make the
  borders of the houses.

    This house system is the first true house system that has @{i}@{b}passed@{ub}@{ui}
  the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}, but it is @{b}undefined for the equator@{ub}, and poorly defined in
  tropics, thus incomplete. Disregarding this limit, it is the best
  house system among those mentioned so far.

@endnode
///
///   XVII century                                        //f
@node ASENSE-HS-MORINUS "ASense - House systems: Morinus"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-REGIOMONTANUS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-PLACIDUS

    @{i}@{b}Jean Baptiste Morin@{ub}@{ui} (1583 - 1656), also known as @{i}@{b}Morin de Villefranche@{ub}@{ui},
  a french physician, mathematician and astrologer, reinterpreted Ptolemy
  in the light of the XVII century science. His major work was '@{i}Astrologia
  Galica@{ui}', published in 1661.

    As a personal astrologer of cardinal Richelieu, he correctly predicted
  cardinal's death, as well as death of Louis XIII (french king), and also
  deaths of Wallenstein and Gustavus Adolphus.

    @{b}Morinus@{ub} is a @{"pseudo" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house system, @{i}independant of geographic latitudes@{ui}.
  Hence, the tables are not needed for it's calculation (once calculated,
  the house edges are identical for all places. This feature makes it easy
  to use and practical, suitable for quick calculations with no equipment.
  During the XVII century this was a clear advantage.
    It is just a simplified variation of the @{"Regiomontanus" link ASENSE-HS-REGIOMONTANUS} house system,
  with the aim to provide the above mentioned improvements.

    Poles of this house system are the poles of the ecliptic, the division
  occurs on the equator (equal segments of 30° each), and it's start is at
  the @{i}equatorial ascendant@{ui} (east intersection point between equator and the
  horizon). Planes through the points on equator acquired by it's division
  and through the poles of ecliptic make the borders of the houses.

    A disadvantage of this system is that neither the ascendant, nor the MC,
  coincides with the tips of the 1st and 10th houses, respectively.

    This house system has @{b}passed@{ub} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.

@endnode
@node ASENSE-HS-PLACIDUS "ASense - House systems: Placidus"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-MORINUS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-MERIDIAN

    @{i}@{b}Placidus di Titus@{ub}@{ui} (1603 - 1668), italian monk, first published the
  tables for the house system that later acquired his name. However, he
  was probably NOT the author of it.

    @{b}Placidus@{ub} system evolved from the @{"Albategnius" link ASENSE-HS-ALBATEGNIUS} house system. It is a
  @{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house system, whose poles are the poles of the prime verticale,
  it's start is at the ascendant, and the trisection occurs on a diurnal
  and nocturnal arcs of the ascendant. The planes that pass through
  these points and the above mentioned poles make the house borders.

    The computations of this house system involve iterative solving
  of a transcendental equations. Usually applied method for this is
  a @{i}Newton-Raphson@{ui} iterative method, which is able to quickly reach
  the desired precission, usually with just 1 or 2 iterative steps.

    Placidus is currently the most popular house system. It owes it's
  popularity to the wide availability of the printed tables, and to
  it's inclusion into the @{i}Raphael@{ui}'s ephemeris. Printing press came
  too late for it's predecessors, @{"Regiomontanus" link ASENSE-HS-REGIOMONTANUS} and @{"Campanus" link ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS} house
  systems, and the other competitive, the @{"Morinus" link ASENSE-HS-MORINUS} house system,
  didn't need any tables at all.

    This house system has @{b}passed@{ub} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}, but is @{b}undefined within polar circles@{ub},
  hence largely incomplete.

@endnode
///
///   clean systems                                       //f
@node ASENSE-HS-MERIDIAN "ASense - House systems: Meridian"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-PLACIDUS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-HORIZON

    @{i}@{b}David Cope@{ub}@{ui} (@{i}Zariel@{ui}), australian astrologer, proposed this house
  system in the early 1900s, and so it also sometimes called '@{b}Zariel@{ub}'
  house system.

    @{b}Meridian@{ub} (also called '@{i}@{b}Axial Rotation@{ub}@{ui}', '@{i}@{b}Zariel@{ub}@{ui}', and '@{i}@{b}Equatorial@{ub}@{ui}')
  house system is a @{"clean" link ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS} @{"pseudo" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house with it's poles being the poles of
  Earth's rotation, and the division (equally spaced) occurs on the
  equator. Therefore, the planes of the house borders coincide with the
  lines of the meridians, consequntly giving this house system a name.
  Start is at the @{i}equatorial ascendant@{ui} (i.e. east point of intersection
  between the planes of equator and horizon).

    This house system @{i}@{b}fails@{ub}@{ui} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.

@endnode
@node ASENSE-HS-HORIZON "ASense - House systems: Horizon"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-MERIDIAN
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-GAUQUELIN

    @{b}Horizon@{ub} (also called '@{i}@{b}Azimuth@{ub}@{ui}' or '@{i}@{b}Zenith@{ub}@{ui}') house system is a '@{"clean" link ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS}'
  @{"pseudo" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house system. It's poles are poles of horizon, and division on
  equal segments occurs on horizon. Start is on the ascendant.

    @{u}@{i}Campanus@{ui} house tables may be used for computation@{uu}: add 12 h to
  sidereal time, find tabular values for colatitude of place, add 180°
  to obtained ecliptic longitude, and thats it.

    The origin of this house system is unknown, but it is probably
  from the XIX century.

    This house system @{i}@{b}fails@{ub}@{ui} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.

@endnode
///
///   Modern times                                        //f
@node ASENSE-HS-GAUQUELIN "ASense - House systems: Gauquelin"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-HORIZON
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-KOCH

    During the XX century @{i}@{b}Gauquelins@{ub}@{ui} have conducted a massive statistical
  research in order to prove that the astrology doesn't work. At the end,
  their result have shown the opposite. They were heavily attacked from
  both the astrological, and scientific communities. Former did so because
  they have shaken their world of magic, and the latter because they have
  shaken their world of established reality.

    @{b}Gauquelin@{ub}, a house system that they have used in their studies, is
  actually a Placidus house system with a few modifications. First, the
  houses are taken in the reverse order, and second, there were 36 of
  them and they are called 'sectors' (each of the 12 houses is further
  divided on 3 parts). This approach was taken to allow more detailed
  statistical study, and the Placidus is taken because it was the most
  popular among all of the house systems.

  @{u}Their results were the following@{uu}:
  1. @{b}The angles have more importance than other house tips@{ub}.
  2. @{b}House placements are hereditary@{ub}, if the births are natural.
  3. '@{b}The Mars effect@{ub}'. It was found that the chance of finding a
     Mars planet near the angles in a chart of an extremely successfull
     sportsman (olimpic gold medal winner, for example) is some 15,000
     times more higher than implied by mere statistical chances.
     Similar is true for the other profesions and other planets, but
     the effect there is not so outstandingly pronounced.

@endnode
///
///     Koch                                              //f
@node ASENSE-HS-KOCH "ASense - House systems: Koch"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-GAUQUELIN
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-TOPOCENTRIC

    @{i}@{b}Friedrich Zanzinger@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}Heinz Specht@{ub}@{ui} created this house system, and
  it was only made known by @{i}@{b}Walter Koch@{ub}@{ui} (1895 - 1970), a german astrologer.
  Tables for the this house system first appeared in 1971 in an english
  translation of the Koch's work, and hence the name.

    @{b}Koch@{ub} (also known as a '@{i}@{b}Birthplace@{ub}@{ui}' house system) is a simple modification
  of the @{"Alcabitus" link ASENSE-HS-ALCABITUS} house system. As in Alcabitus, the arcs of ascendant are
  trisected, but then the altitude circles are constructed through these
  points. Basically, the borders of the houses are defined by the horizon
  lines at different times. The division starts at the ascendant.

    It is a @{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house system, but the above definition, however, is a
  very poor one, since it makes the system @{b}undefined within the polar
  circle@{ub}. Although it's other name may suggest so, it is not at all
  related to the birthplace any more than any other house system presented
  so far.

    This house system @{i}@{b}fails@{ub}@{ui} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.

@endnode
///
///     Topocentric                                       //f
@node ASENSE-HS-TOPOCENTRIC  "ASense - House systems: Topocentric"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-KOCH
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-KRUSINSKI

    @{i}@{b}Wendel Polich@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}H.P. Nelson Page@{ub}@{ui}, argentinian astrologers, introduced
  this house system in the 1961., after laborious testing with primary
  directions in order to establish the borders of houses. @{b}First, they have
  found the approximate borders, and only THEN they tried to design a house
  system that fits them@{ub}.
    This is the first time that someone has actually tried to do it this way,
  which is actually a correct scientific way to deal with a problem. So far,
  all the others have just came up with some idea, formulated their thoughts,
  and then published it, without ever doing any serious testing.
    Consequently, a myriad of systems appeared. Most of them were obviously
  wrong or incomplete, as previously shown, but still, without any real
  testing, they never seized their existance, and continued to cause a
  dispute among astrologers.
    If you have any doubts that this is true, try reading the story about
  @{"houses within the polar circle" link ASENSE-HS-SPECIAL_CASES}.
                 
    @{b}Topocentric@{ub} is a @{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} house system. The equator is divided on 12 equal
  parts from a cone of rotation, and the resultant ascensional circles are
  projected to the ecliptic. Planes that pass through these points of
  intersection and the poles of prime verticale make the house borders.

    This description is quite abstract. To simplify things, tangens of
  the polar height of the 11th house is 1 / 3 of the tangens of the
  geographic latitude, 2 / 3 for the 12th house.

    Surprisingly, this concept yields almost the same results as the
  Placidus system does. The @{b}tips of the houses calculated with this
  system are within 1° of those calculated by the Placidus house system@{ub}.
  Except for very high geographical latitudes (above the polar circle).

    Unlike Placidus, the topocentric house system @{i}@{b}IS defined for the places
  within the polar circle@{ub}@{ui}, and so it has been thought to be an improvement
  of or even a replacement for the popular Placidus.
    However, the results that it yields within the polar circles are
  occasionally @{i}really@{ui} weird. For example the ascendant may be sometimes
  located BETWEEN the 11th and 12th house. @{i}@{b}Really@{ub}@{ui} weird!

    Apart from that, obscure definition and the lack of philosophical
  reasoning have been the main arguments of it's opponents.

    The name '@{i}Topocentric@{ui}' is a bit missleading, because it is not any
  more topocentric than any other house system presented so far. The
  authors probably thought that it IS for some reason, and thus the name.

    This house system has @{b}passed@{ub} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.

@endnode
///
///     Krusinski                                         //f
@node ASENSE-HS-KRUSINSKI  "ASense - House systems: Krusinski"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-TOPOCENTRIC
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE

    The @{b}Krusinski@{ub} house system was invented by @{i}@{b}Bogdan Krusinski@{ub}@{ui}, Poland.
  First tables of this house system appeared in 1995, while fron Feb 2006
  exists the computerized version of this house system.

    The system itself is a merger between the @{i}Campanus@{ui}, @{i}Horizon@{ui},
  and the @{i}Meridian@{ui} house systems. It is a complex transformation
  performed in order to keep this house system both @{"clean" link ASENSE-HS-CAMPANUS} and @{"true" link ASENSE-HS-PSEUDO-TRUE} on
  the same time. The transformation consists of 3 projections and two
  rotations. In this way it effectively workarounds some of the obsticles
  from the earlier house systems. Note that the Krusinski house system
  merges all other 3 clean house systems, starting from the Campanus,
  which is the only true one among them, in order to itself remains true
  on the end.

    First, the division of houses occurs on the PV, starting from the Asc,
  like in Campanus HS. The houses are projected from the poles of the PV,
  not on to the ecliptic, which Campanus does, but on the horizon plane.
    Azimuth of Asc is added then (first rotation, around the poles of hor).
    The resulting points are then projected from the poles of horizon to
  the equator (2nd projection). This is similar to the Horizon HS, except
  that the target plane of projecting is not the ecliptic, but the equator.
    The second rotation, around the poles of rotation, shifts the plane by
  the equatorial coordinates of the Asc.
    The third projection occurs from the poles of rotation, and projects
  the resulting points to the ecliptic. This is similar to the Meridian HS,
  except that the starting points are no longer equally spaced due to the
  previously performed transformations.

    The Krusinski house system is quite unique, as it was the first house
  system to use a complex layer of transformations in calculation of cusps.

    The main flaw is that the house positions of planets loose their sanity
  after about ±80° of geo. latitude and converge into two points for all
  objects in the chart. (1 point for objects above, and 1 for those below
  the horizon.)

    The second flaw is that the house positions of stars are not handled
  very well (i.e., outside of ecliptic, the house positions are biased).
  This occurs as an inevitable consequence of numerous transformations.

    This house system has @{b}passed@{ub} the @{"Test" link ASENSE-HS-TEST}.
@endnode
///
///   Altitude                                            //f
@node ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE "ASense - House systems: Altitude"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-TOPOCENTRIC
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-INTRO

   12. @{b}@{u}Altitude house system@{uu}@{ub} (@{FG shine}First@{FG text} XXI century design):

   12a. @{"Intro" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-INTRO} (short, with a point)
   12b. @{"Angles" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-ANGLES} of the chart (extended definitions)
   12c. @{"Circumpolarity" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-CIRCUMPOLARITY} issue (considerations)
   12d. @{"Definition" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-DEFINITON} (simple indeed)
   12e. @{"Example" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-EXAMPLE} (how to calculate manually)
   12f. @{"Advantages" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-ADVANTAGES} (5 of them, but not a 6th)
   12g. @{"Dynamic Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-DYNAMIC} (with @{b}time@{ub} included)
   12h. @{"Blur of the longitudes" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-BLUR} prevented (6th advantage)
   12i. @{"Dance of the meridian" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-DANCE} escaped (7th advantage)
   12j. @{"Tidal effects" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-TIDES} acknowledged (8th advantage)
   12k. @{"Apparent noon" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-NOON} recognized (9th advantage)
   12l. @{"Refraction" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-REFRACTION} applicable (10th advantage)
   12m. @{"Topocentrism" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-TOPOCENTRISM} optional (11th advantage)
   12n. @{"Choice of a zodiac" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-ZODIAC} is irrelevant (12th advantage)
   12o. @{"Last words" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-LAST-WORDS} (static vs dynamic)

   UPDATE: (more advantages)
   12p. @{"House positions of stars" link ASENSE-HS-POLARIS-TEST} are correctly computed
   12q. @{b}Easily measurable@{ub} (the altitudes are obvious for an observer)
   12r. @{b}No distortions by projections@{ub} - the Altitude HS is the rare one that
        doesn't use @{i}projections@{ui} in it's computations. Instead, it calculates
        the house positions of each point on the sky, whether static or not,
        solely from it's @{b}altitude@{ub} coordinate in the local coordinate system.
        This way, it avoids distortions, which are inevitable with other HSs.
        (Note that @{b}the @{i}altitude@{ui} of every point depends on it's @{i}azimuth@{ui}@{ub}, thus
        both of the coordinates of the local coordinate system are utilised.)

   (@{i}@{b}This house system has been created by the author of the ASense software@{ub}@{ui}.)

@{b}@{u}Abstract@{uu}@{ub}:

    Description of a @{b}Altitude house system@{ub}, the only house system entirely
  @{i}@{b}based on altitudes@{ub}@{ui}.This is the @{i}first@{ui} house system designed in XXI century,
  with the aim to become the @{i}@{b}Ultimate house system@{ub}@{ui}.There are 2 '@{i}flavours@{ui}':
  @{i}static@{ui} (simple), and @{i}dynamic@{ui} (complex).Dynamic flavour takes the effects
  of @{i}time@{ui} into account too.It has been tested, has no known flaws, and fixes
  even those potential problems that no one has realized and uttered before.

@{b}@{u}Birth data of the Altitude house system@{uu}@{ub}:
  @{b}8-Jan-2004 (Greg. cal.), 15:56:?? (CET, +1h) (LCT), @{i}data rating@{ui} AA; (± 2 m)
  Subotica (address classified), 19E38, 46N06, 130 m, @{i}coors grade@{ui} VI;
  @{i}Temperature@{ui}: quite warm for the season (10..15° C)@{ub}.
    (@{i}Event is taken as the first public announcement of this system, which has
  occured during a short phone conversation between the author and his brother.
  Time was recorded by phone and noted by the author immediately afterward@{ui}.
  Given error of time is here because the clock's inaccuracy wasn't ruled out.)
@endnode
///
///   Test                                                //f
@node ASENSE-HS-TEST "ASense - House System: Test"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-SPECIAL_CASES
@{b}@{u}The Test@{uu}@{ub}: House systems on a trial of validity.

  IMPORTANT NOTE: @{b}The purpose of this test is to ELIMINATE, NOT to approve@{ub}!

    @{i}@{b}So many house systems, how to choose which one to use@{ub}@{ui} ?

    The answer is: @{i}to put them all on a trial (a severe test), and
  to dismiss and abandon those that fail@{ui}.

    @{i}@{b}So what kind of a chart makes a severe test@{ub}@{ui} ?

    The answer is: @{i}one that meets @{b}ALL@{ub} of the following criteria@{ui}:

  @{u}Precondition@{uu}:
    0. @{b}The birth data is extremely well known@{ub}. Recorded @{i}and@{ui} verified by
    rectification. (Birth time must be known to a precision of several seconds,
    and birth location down to a kilometer.)

  @{u}Conditions@{uu}:
    1. @{b}Two (or more) planets together have rulership over @{i}all@{ui} major points
    in the chart@{ub}: Sun, Moon, Asc, MC, part of Fortune, part of Spirit and
    perhaps over several other planets.
    (Both parts mentioned above are a synthesis of the Sun, Moon, and Asc.)
    2. @{b}These (two) planets are in a tight conjuction@{ub}.
    3. @{b}That conjuction is located at the edge between two houses, but not
    on angles@{ub}, since their definition is not disputed.
    4. @{b}The planets within conjunction are /only @{i}moderately@{ui} aspected@{ub}.
    - If the conjunction is the @{i}most@{ui} aspected point in the chart, it's planets
      would be overloaded by the links and hence blocked to manifest in full. [@{"1" link ASENSE-GENERAL-REFERENCES}]
    - If the conjunction is the @{i}least@{ui} aspected point in the chart, it's planets
      would be isolated away from the angles. Thereupon, blocked again by the
      lack of links with the rest of the chart... [@{"1" link ASENSE-GENERAL-REFERENCES}]

  @{u}Consequencial conditions@{uu}:
    5. As a result of such placement, @{b}one of the houses is the center of
    all life activities, while the other, otherwise empty, helds none@{ub}.
    6. @{b}If those two planets are placed to the house that is thought to be
    empty, because it helds little or no real life activities at all,
    the standard meaning of that placement would severely conflict the
    reality@{ub}. ('@{i}There is no way that that conjunction is in that house@{ui}.')

  @{u}@{i}Optional criteria@{ui}@{uu}:
    7. @{i}@{b}The above mentioned conjunction in a certain house is a family
    heritage@{ub}@{ui}, as implied by Gauquelin. This might make a placement
    in a certain house more firm. [@{"2" link ASENSE-GENERAL-REFERENCES}]
    8. @{i}@{b}The above mentioned conjunction in a certain house is a signature
    of the trade of the person in question@{ub}@{ui}, as also implied by Gauquelin.
    This is valid only if the person is extremely successfull in his/her
    area of work. If met, this condition makes a placement in a certain
    house more firm. [@{"2" link ASENSE-GENERAL-REFERENCES}]

  @{u}General consideration@{uu}:
    a. @{b}A house system should be defined for all places on the Earth,
    especially for those where people actually live@{ub}. If it is not,
    it is an incomplete approximation at best.

    A house system should be valid for ALL people whose charts meet the
  above mentioned severe conditions. @{b}If there is a single person on whom
  the questioned house system fails the Test, then that system should be
  considered only as an incorrect attempt of a house problem solution@{ub}.
  To emphasize this statement, only one chart has been used for Testing
  (one that @{i}does@{ui} meet all of the above mentioned criteria).

@endnode
///
///   polar circle                                        //f
@node ASENSE-HS-SPECIAL_CASES "ASense - Houses within polar circles: Intro"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@PREV ASENSE-HS-TEST
@NEXT ASENSE-HS-EXTREME_POINTS
@{b}@{u}The polar circles@{uu}@{ub}: Behaviour of house systems within them.

    @{b}Within the polar circle@{ub}, one important thing happens: some parts of
  the zodiac become circumpolar. I.e. if Sun is located at these parts,
  it will never rise or set during a 24 h period, that we call '@{i}a day@{ui}'.

    This causes a dispute: whether the houses should be flipped when the
  southern part of the meridian (northern on the south hemisphere) sinks
  below the horizon due to this reason or not. If yes, than the MC point
  is always ABOVE the horizon, and if not, the MC is always in the same
  direction, and the order of the houses is preserved.
    A flip causes the order of houses to be reversed, because the point
  of the ascendant is always located eastward.

  Here is a lenghty discussion on this subject, as taken from the www:

  - @{"Part 1" link ASENSE-HS-POLAR-1} of a discussion,
  - @{"Part 2" link ASENSE-HS-POLAR-2} of a discussion.

  Bare in mind that persons involved in this discussion (and there are
  many similar discussions over the internet), actually never tried to
  experimentaly test their hypothesis on a real people. If there is any
  worth in the astrology, it SHOULD be fairly easy to distinguish between
  someone's 10th and 4th angle. They mean 2 completely different things!

    Southern part of the globe has only ocean within the polar circle (and
  the uninhabitated Antarctic of course), but the northern one has several
  industrial countries within that area (@{i}Alaska, Canada, Russia, Norway,
  Sweden, Finland, Greenland, Iceland@{ui}). @{b}Any astrologers out there reading
  this@{ub} ?
    Your opinion is valuable. Speak up and put an end to this dispute.

  NOTE: @{b}The house positions of bodies in the @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} house system do not
  depend on the outcome of this dispute. Although, it's @{i}philosophy@{ui} may be
  used to support the '@{i}flip hypothesis@{ui}'@{ub}.Experimental evidence should always
  take precedence, however, if some become available in the future.

    @{b}The ASense currently supports the 'flip hypothesis@{ub}'. If further evidence
  is presented, this policy may or may not change in the future.

@endnode
@node ASENSE-HS-POLAR-1 "ASense - Houses within polar circle: Part 1"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
