22 Equal (Sun)     ecl.      ecl.      Sun      30°     Pseudo   -     -    ???
23 Aries=Null      ecl.      ecl.     0 Ari     30°     Pseudo   -     -    ???
24 Krusinski     PV,equ.   prime vert  Asc      30°     True     +     +   1995
@endnode
///
/// ephemeris                                             //f
@node ASENSE-DECIDE-EPHEMERIS "ASense - Menus: Decide Ephemeris"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-HS
@NEXT ASENSE-DECIDE-YMD

    Currently, @{b}only built-in ephemeris are available@{ub}.This choice may be
  extended in the future.

  - @{b}Builtin@{ub} ephemeris: Precision of the built-in ephemeris closely
  matches the precision of the JPL, and their routines were heavily
  optimized to achieve maximal speed of computation.
  Errors are below ~.05'' of arc (comparing with JPL), except for the
  Moon, where a compromise has been made between precision and speed,
  in such a way that for the Moon errors are 10x larger (~0.5'').This
  allows for much faster and better optimized calculations, and is
  still more than sufficient enough for any astrological computation.

  @{u}Choices possibly available in the future@{uu}:
  - @{b}JPL@{ub} (Jet Propulsion Laboratory): The most accurate, but unfortunately
  too large, thus not supported.
  - @{b}Swiss@{ub} ephemeris (TM):Smaller, but still quite large.Very accurate,
  but not free, thus not supported in the initial version.Handling of
  asteroids will probably be done with the help of Swiss ephemeris in
  the future if there is enough interest for them to justify the price
  of the license.
@endnode
///
/// Year, month, Day                                      //f
@node ASENSE-DECIDE-YMD "ASense - Menus: Decide Year, Month, Day"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-EPHEMERIS
@NEXT ASENSE-DECIDE-ARCS
@{b}@{u}Year, month, day @{uu}@{ub}: Define them.
    One must simply choose between various available definitions of the
  standard time measuring terms.@{b}These choices affect some cyclic charts@{ub}
  (@{i}returns@{ui}, @{i}progressions@{ui} and @{i}directions@{ui}), but not simple time stepping,
  which is always based on a standard mean time intervals (24h for a day,
  365.25 days for a year, and a 30 days for a month.

  @{u}Offered are@{uu}: (true or mean)
  - @{b}Solar cycle for a year@{ub}  (@{i}sidereal@{ui}, @{i}tropical@{ui}, @{i}anomalic@{ui}, @{i}draconic@{ui})
  - @{b}Lunar cycle for a month@{ub} (@{i}sidereal@{ui}, @{i}tropical@{ui}, @{i}anomalic@{ui}, @{i}draconic@{ui}, @{i}synodic@{ui})
  - @{b}   MC cycle for a day@{ub}   (@{i}sidereal@{ui}, @{i}tropical@{ui}, @{i}synodic@{ui} (a.k.a. @{i}@{b}solar@{ub}@{ui}))

    All these values are marginally different from each other, except for
  the @{i}draconic (a.k.a. eclipse) year@{ui}, which is about 346 days long, and is
  substantially shorter than the other year types.

  @{b}True@{ub} - differs from cycle to cycle.
  @{b}Mean@{ub} - average rate.

  @{b}Sidereal@{ub} - return to the @{i}same position according to the stars@{ui}
  @{b}Tropical@{ub} - return to the @{i}same position in a tropical ecliptic@{ui}
  @{b}Anomalic@{ub} - @{i}perihel@{ui} to @{i}perihel@{ui}
  @{b}Draconic@{ub} - return to the @{i}same angle to the lunar nodes@{ui}
  @{b}Synodic@{ub} - return to the @{i}same angle to the governing body@{ui} (Sun)

  IMPORTANT NOTE: @{b}All of the above returns are earthly-based ones@{ub}.This means
  that they can be derived for both @{i}topocentric@{ui} and @{i}geocentric@{ui} observational
  points, although one may argue that 'a day' doesn't have much sense from a
  geocentric point of view.However, @{b}heliocentric and barycentric returns are
  NOT supported@{ub}.@{b}If one of the latter centers is selected for a calculation,
  the result is going to be a *@{i}topocentric@{ui}* return@{ub} of the selected type @{b}from
  a @{i}heliocentric/barycentric@{ui} point of view@{ub} (i.e. expressed in those coors.).
  (@{i}Topocentric is a default@{ui}, unless @{i}sidereal draconic@{ui} return is required,
  which (@{i}by default@{ui}) always uses @{i}geocentric point@{ui} to find a time for return.)
  When a time is found, the cyclic chart is computed and the results expressed
  as observed from @{i}whatever-is-selected@{ui} center of observation.

  @{u}If one *@{b}requires@{ub}* @{i}heliocentric/barycentric@{ui} returns as such, the following@{uu}
  @{u}should be noted@{uu}:
  1. @{b}'A day' for a Sun is meaningless@{ub}, because Sun is a source of radiation in
     our system, and it also has a differential rotation, with varying speeds
     from the poles to equator (25.4 days on equator, 36+ days on poles).
                                                                    
  2. @{b}'A month' from a Sun's point of view is an ambiguous term.@{i}If 'month' is a
     period of rotation of a largest satellite, then it's duration is 11.86
     years, which is a Jupiter's period of rotation.Otherwise, there are as
     many 'months' as there are recognised planets@{ub}@{ui}, or at least large ones.
     Earth related, @{b}Sun's 'Earth-month' is equal to 1 year of our calendar@{ub}.

       @{b}'Solar-month returns' are possible to calculate only manually, by using
     a @{i}time-step-by-step@{ui} method@{ub}.These returns may eventually become supported.

  3. @{b}'A year' is meaningless from the solar perspective@{ub}.Sun is a single star,
     and there are no other (larger) stars in the solar system about which to
     revolve to have 'a year' of its own (i.e. no superior governing objects).
     (@{i}@{b}Unless, of course, one considers duration of a 'solar year' to be equal
     to the Sun's period of revolution around the Galactic centre@{ub}@{ui}.If so, this
     cycle is too long to be used in astrology (@{i}millions@{ui} of years, that is).)
@endnode
///
/// Arcs of Directions                                    //f
@node ASENSE-DECIDE-ARCS "ASense - Menus: Decide Arc of Directions"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-YMD
@NEXT ASENSE-DECIDE-SID-TRANSITS
@{b}@{u}Arcs of directions@{uu}@{ub}: Solar, lunar, Asc, or MC.
    @{b}Solar arcs are standard ones@{ub} to be used for directions, but there
  are other possibilities.However, Moon moves very fast, and the angles
  are literally 'flying' around the chart, thus the effective usage of
  the other available options is directly limited to the accuracy of the
  birth data.According to my experiance, @{i}the Asc arcs have shown some
  surprisingly remarkable results@{ui}.

    @{b}Directions are probably the most powerfull predictive tool in the
  astrology currently available.They also play an important role in a
  process of chart @{i}rectification@{ui}@{ub} (i.e. determination of the accurate
  birth time / place, based on the biographical data).

  NOTE WELL: @{i}1' of solar arc equals about 1 week of a lifetime.Moon is
  about 12 times faster, thus 1' of lunar arc covers only about half a day.
  1' of Asc and MC arcs cover about the same time span as the solar ones@{ui}.

    @{b}For solar and lunar arcs, about 24 minutes of error in a birth data
  would result in a week of error in predictions@{ub}.

    @{b}For angles however@{ub}, the margin of error is much tighter, because
  @{b}just 4 seconds of error in a birth data would result in an error of
  a week in a lifetime predictions@{ub}.Additionaly, @{b}@{i}just 1 km of birth
  positional data error may represent a 1' of error in the ecliptical
  positions of the angles, which corresponds to an error of about a
  week of a lifetime@{ui}@{ub}.
@endnode
///
/// Sidereal Transits                                     //f
@node ASENSE-DECIDE-SID-TRANSITS "ASense - Menus: Decide Sidereal Transits"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-ARCS
@NEXT ASENSE-DECIDE-COLORING-POLICY
@{b}@{u}Sidereal transits@{uu}@{ub}: Turn this switch ON to enable them.

    @{i}@{b}In a double chart mode@{ub}@{ui} transits would be drawn in a ring around the
  main chart.If this switch is ON, @{b}the precession would be removed from
  the transit chart according to the selected @{"sidereal mode" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES}, even if a
  tropical chart is required@{ub} (in a sidereal chart it is removed anyway).
  Transits would therefore refer to the same ecliptic as to which the main
  (inner) chart would be cast upon.

    @{i}@{b}In a single chart mode@{ub}@{ui}, there is nothing to be removed, and thus, this
  switch would have no effect.
@endnode
///
/// Coloring policy (not on the menu)                     //f
@node ASENSE-DECIDE-COLORING-POLICY "ASense - Menus: Decide Coloring policy"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@PREV ASENSE-DECIDE-SID-TRANSITS
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUDECIDE
@{b}@{u}Note well the following@{uu}@{ub}:

    When a chart is drawn, all selections would be mentioned in a text
  surrounding it.@{i}@{b}Check out the colors of the text@{ub}@{ui}.Their meaning is:

  - @{b}black@{ub} - either a default, or very much OK.
  - @{b}blue@{ub} - OK, might be useful,
  - @{b}green@{ub} - @{i}fair@{ui} (approach cautiously),
  - @{b}red@{ub} - @{i}poor@{ui} (exotic wilderland).

    Choose your selection according to these indicators, unless you
  are willing to test the validity of a myriad of offered options by
  yourself.(@{i}There are thousands of possible combinations@{ui}...)

    Note also that most of the options available are here just because
  of the sake of completeness.Most of them differ from each other very
  little, but they @{i}do@{ui} differ.
    Available options are usually discussed within this guide in more
  details.So, please read on.
@endnode
///
@remark Choose
/// Choose                                                //f
@node ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE "ASense - Menus: Choose"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS
@{b}@{u}Choose@{uu}@{ub}: Secondary decisions are held here.

    You have to choose between several options, but you would probably want
  to change some of them often.They are here to fork a generation of a variety
  of different chart types, based on the available modes of computation.

  @{u}Cyclic chart types@{uu}: (available types of secondary charts)
  - @{"Returns" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS} - chart for a time when a specified body returns to its origin.
  - @{"Progressions" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS} - chart for a time when a specified shorter cycle ends.
  - @{"Directions" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS} - shifting of a main chart for an arc which a previously
    selected body sweeps during a selected symbolic period.
  @{"Mergings" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING} - available @{"methods" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING 52} to create @{"subtypes" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING 68} of merged charts.

  @{u}Modes of computation@{uu}:
  - @{"Show in a Ring" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-RING} - switch to enable double chart mode for cyclic charts.
  - @{"Angle Crossings" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ANGLE-CROSSINGS} - modes of handling the crossing of an angle.
  - @{"Aspects Calc." link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC} - modes referring to the calculation of aspects.
  - @{"Sid. Modes" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES} - traditional or accurate one.
  - @{"Show Stars" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SHOW-STARS} - switch to enable drawing of stars in a chart.
  - @{"Mark Retrograde *s" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-R-STARS} - switch to enable special coloring for these stars.
  - @{"Orientation to Sky" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ORIENTATION} - southern, northern or mixed view.
  - @{"Presentation Modes" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION} - normal chart or a planetarium one (ring or conic).
  - @{"2nd Coor to Present" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-2ND_COOR} - extra coordinate for planetarium chart.
@endnode
///
///   Returns                                             //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS "ASense - Menus: Choose Returns"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS
@{b}@{u}Returns@{uu}@{ub}: cyclic charts for a time when a specified body returns to its
  original position.

    Available returns are @{i}@{b}solar@{ub}@{ui} (occurs once a year), @{i}@{b}lunar@{ub}@{ui} (monthly chart)
  and @{b}@{i}solar@{ui} enneads@{ub} (a special type of return which occurs whenever a sun
  returns to any angle from the 9th serie of aspects (i.e. n * 40°).These
  aspects act as '@{i}quasiconjunctions@{ui}', which means that their effects are
  similar to those of a real conjunctions.The logic of that idea implies
  that a return chart may also be cast whenever a body reaches any of these
  angles.Only @{i}solar@{ui} enneads are available because lunar enneads would cover
  only very short periods of time (about 3 days only).It would be pointless
  to erect charts for such small time intervals, especially because the
  initial position of the Moon may itself be inaccurate (very likely), due
  to the errors in the chart input data (time and place errors).
    Enneads were invented by @{i}Garth Allen@{ui}, a well known sidereal astrologer
  from the XX century.

    The importance of solar and lunar cycles for life on Earth in general
  should be obvious for everyone and I believe that it doesn't need any
  further elaboration.

    @{i}@{b}Planetary returns are not supported@{ub}@{ui}, simply because they can not be
  unambiguously determined.(@{i}A planet may go retrograde and thus return
  several times to the same position during a single revolution (Pluto
  may do that for 7 times sometimes, Neptune for 5, while other planets
  do that for 3 times, although Uranus comes very close to doing it, like
  a Neptune, 5 times in a row)@{ui}).@{i}@{b}Heliocentric and barycentric returns@{ub}@{ui}
  *are* ambiguous, but my experience indicates that there is not much
  merrit in using them (just as well as the heliocentric and barycentric
  charts), simply because we live on Earth, and the focus of the chart
  should be there, topocentric if possible.The Sun based centers are,
  however, very useful for astronomical purposes.(Some astrologers use
  them too, and this is the reason for their inclusion in the ASense.)
    Casting of a planetary return chart is still possible, but it has to
  be done manually, by using a @{i}time-step-by-step method@{ui}.I admit that this
  is quite cumbersome, but than again, planetary returns are quite rare.
  @{b}The only planetary returns that justify the bothering about them may be
  those of a Saturn, Jupiter, maybe Mars and possibly Uranus@{ub}.

    @{b}Cycle of a Saturn@{ub} is an especially important one.It occurs after 29
  years of life and is described as "@{FG shine}@{i}entering silence@{ui}@{FG text}".@{i}@{b}At the age of 29
  time seems to stop, and one enters the emptiness beyond time.This is
  the end of learning phase, the end of fascinating row of new events.
  Up to that moment a direction of one's movement (course of life) was
  the most important thing, but then a philosophy shift occurs: the
  most important thing becomes the comfort of one's 'vehicle', the mode
  of travelling, instead of the destination.This is because the 'ship'
  now sails to eternity and there are no particular places to go any
  more.This event usually hits like a wall of bricks, no matter how
  prepared one may be.Older ones may tell to the young ones what to
  expect, but the young listeners cannot hear that well@{ub}@{ui}...

    @{b}Cycles of Jupiter@{ub} are connected with growing phases in our lives.
  The @{i}first cycle@{ui} ends at the age of 11.9, at the time when we reach
  @{i}puberty@{ui}.The @{i}second cycle@{ui}, at the age of 23 marks the beginning of
  @{i}adultship@{ui}.The @{i}third cycle@{ui}, at the age of 35 marks the time of full
  @{i}maturity@{ui}.And so on...

    @{b}Cycle of Mars@{ub} is very fast, and it ends in just 1.9 years.The end
  of the first Martian cycle coincides with the discovery of emotions
  and first attempts to struggle for independence.Because of their
  frequent occurence the cycles of Mars are not that prominent like
  those of the large gas giant (Jupiter and Saturn).

    @{b}Cycle of Uranus@{ub} lasts 84 years, almost too long to be relevant for
  humans.However, quaters of this periods (i.e. years 21, 42 and 63)
  may hold some importance.Apart from that, the mundane astrology may
  utilize this planetary return cycle.

    @{b}Cycles of Neptune@{ub} (164.8 yr), and especially @{b}Pluto@{ub} (247.7 yr) are
  way too long to fit into a single human lifespan.Thus it is pointless
  to analyze them in the charts of humans.However, @{i}@{b}some organisations
  and states may survive long enough without disruption to justify the
  usage of these cycles as well@{ub}@{ui}.

    The real problem with any of the planetary cycles, but especially
  with the long lasting ones, is that @{i}@{b}if the planet in question was
  about to change direction in the radix chart, it is impossible to
  accurately cast a return chart@{ub}@{ui}.This is because at these times the
  planets move so slow, that they may take hours to show any movement.
    Even Mercury, as the fastest moving planet, needs about 1..2 hours
  to move a single arc second in the vicinity of the stationary point.
  Neptune and Pluto may take a full 24 hours for the same arc distance.
  @{i}@{b}Gross insensitivity of planets to time in the calculation of stations
  is the main reason for sometimes radical discrepancies between the
  results obtained with the help of different ephemeris@{ub}@{ui}.
    There is nothing that can be done about it.
  (Note: @{i}Fortunately, only small amount of cases are affected by this@{ui}.)

    In a future versions of ASense, the planetary returns might get
  handled as well.

    @{i}@{b}Quaterly and semi returns are not supported@{ub}@{ui}.Their usage is hereby
  discouraged.Their computation is however, possible by the utlisation
  of the same method as for the above mentioned planetary returns (i.e.
  manual @{i}time-step-by-step@{ui} chart casting).

    @{i}@{b}Phase returns@{ub}@{ui} (i.e. return of 2 objects to the same angle as it was
  in the radix chart) @{i}@{b}are not supported, except for draconic and synodic
  returns of the Sun, Moon and MC@{ub}@{ui}, which are available as @{"progressions" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS}.

@{b}@{u}Secondary returns@{uu}@{ub}: (@{i}Tertiary@{ui} chart types.)
    These are returns of objects to their position as it was in some
  @{i}secondary@{ui} chart.For example,

  - @{b}'kinetic' returns@{ub} are returns of objects to their positions within
    a progressed chart.A progressed chart is by itself a @{i}secondary@{ui}
    (derived) chart type because it stems from the @{i}natal@{ui} (a.k.a. @{i}radix@{ui}
    (root)) chart.Because kinetic returns stem from a secondary chart
    type, they themselves are a kind of a @{i}tertiary@{ui} chart.

  - @{b}anlunars@{ub} are lunar returns within the scope of a solar return chart
    (i.e. returns of the Moon to the same position as it was inside a
    specified solar return chart).

    @{i}@{b}Casting of these and other tertiary charts is easy with ASense.A
  secondary chart's data has to be promoted to become a primary chart@{ub}@{ui}.
  This is done by a simple clicking on the '@{b}±=@{ub}' button below the input
  string.After that, any tertiary chart to the former primary chart
  now becomes a secondary to the current primary one and may be cast
  in a regular way for casting a secondary chart.The order of charts
  is simply decreased by this operation.
    @{i}One must take care not to loose the primary chart data, either by
  saving it on the disk, copying it to the other input string or even
  by remembering it manually@{ui}.

  @{b}NOTE WELL@{ub}: @{i}@{b}The return time also depends on the chosen way of aspects
  calculation@{ub}@{ui} (i.e. whether they are @{i}2D@{ui} (and which type if so) or @{i}3D@{ui}).
  @{i}@{b}This multiplies the number of possible chart outputs with the number of
  implemented projections@{ub}@{ui}.Currently, this is an increase by the factor 5.

@endnode
///
///   Progressions                                        //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS "ASense - Menus: Choose Progressions"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS
@{b}@{u}Progressions@{uu}@{ub}: Symbolic charts, cast for the specified time.

    @{i}@{b}Progressions are regular chart cast for a time when a specified@{ui} shorter
  @{i}cycle ends@{ui}@{ub}.Their philosophy is that whatever happens during a short cycle
  will replicate itself during a longer cycle.The exception from this rule
  are @{i}primary@{ui} progressions (daily charts), where both cycles are equal.
    Cycles which are usable for this purpose must have utter importance.
  They are '@{i}year@{ui}', '@{i}month@{ui}' and '@{i}day@{ui}', and have to be defined in a @{"Decide" link ASENSE-DECIDE-YMD}
  menu before a progressed chart can be cast.Optionally, one may always
  use a default values for everything, including for these definitions.

  @{u}Types of progressions@{uu}:
  1. @{b}Primary@{ub} (daily chart) - a @{i}day@{ui} represents a @{i}day@{ui}.
     This is a natural progression of time.They differ from regular transits
     because they must be cast for times when MC (representing a daily cycle)
     returns to its starting position.(Once a day, that is.)
       User is advised to use @{"very-tight-orbs" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC 69} when casting this type of chart,
     and to ignore all, but the most prominent factors (@{i}the Moon@{ui}, @{i}angles@{ui}, @{i}part@{ui}
     @{i}of Fortune@{ui}, @{i}ruler of the chart@{ui}, @{i}the strongest pattern(s) of the aspects@{ui}).

  2. @{b}Secondary@{ub} (classic progressions) - a @{i}day@{ui} represents a @{i}year@{ui}.
     This connects 2 of the most important solar based cycles: a @{i}day@{ui}@{i}@{ui} and a
     @{i}year@{ui}.It means that events during a first few months after birth have
     their impact on the whole lifespan.(The astrological events, that is.)

       Contrary to my expectations, the @{i}@{b}true synodic day = true trop. year
     progressions@{ub}@{ui} (which are a default choice) @{i}@{b}have proven to be extremely
     reliable@{ub}@{ui}.

  3. @{b}Tertiary@{ub} - a @{i}day@{ui} represents a @{i}month@{ui}.
     An attempt to connect one of the solar cycles (a day) with a lunar cycle.
     These charts are identical with those of the secondary progressions,
     but their symbolic meaning is limited to ~12 times shorter timespan
     of the monthly lunar cycle.Thus, they have to be cast ~12 times more
     frequently.

  4. @{b}Minor@{ub} - a @{i}month@{ui} represents a @{i}year@{ui}.
     An attempt to connect one of the solar cycles (a year) with a lunar cycle.
     These charts are the least used progression type, probably because of
     difficulties involved in the accurate computations of a lunar return.The
     Moon moves very fast in a complicated orbit, and it is thus harder to
     compute.Apart from that, small inaccuracies in birth time data may lead
     to larger discrepancies in these charts.(This observation is partially
     true for tertiary progressions as well.)

  @{b}NOTE on tertiary and minor progresions@{ub}: Both of these progressions involve
  a @{i}@{b}lunar cycle@{ub}@{ui}, and are therefore more likely to work in connection with
  those who are more sensitive to movements of the Moon.(The @{i}women@{ui}, that is.)

    Considering the number of possible variations of parameters involved,
  @{b}the ASense is able to compute several hundreds of different progression
  types and subtypes@{ub}. All of them differ only slightly one from another.
  However, one must not think that they are all meaningfull and valid ones.
  Please refer to the @{"coloring scheme" link ASENSE-DECIDE-COLORING-POLICY} to find out which choices are safe.

  @{u}Obsolete terms@{uu}:
  - @{b}Qoutidian 1 (Q1) progressions@{ub} - @{i}mean sidereal day@{ui} = @{i}mean sidereal year@{ui}
  - @{b}Quotidian 2 (Q2) progressions@{ub} - @{i}mean tropical day@{ui} = @{i}mean sidereal year@{ui}
  - @{b}Profections@{ub} - @{i}??? ??? year@{ui} = @{i}??? synodic month@{ui}
@endnode
///
///   Directions                                          //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS "ASense - Menus: Choose Directions"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS
@NEXT ASENSE-DIRECTIONS-COMPLEX
@{b}@{u}Directions@{uu}@{ub}: Symbolic charts, an @{"arc of direction" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ARCS} is added to the root chart.

    @{b}Directions are probably the most powerfull (reliable) predictive tool
  available in the astrology@{ub}.Especially useful are directions of the Sun to
  conjunctions with the other objects.The philosophy of directions is similar
  to those of the progressions.The difference is that instead of casting a
  whole chart for the selected time, only the position of a single body is
  calculated (which one it is is determined from a @{i}decide/arcs@{ui} menu item).
    The angular difference between a new position and the original position
  of the body in the root chart is an @{i}@{b}arc of direction@{ub}@{ui}.This arc is then
  added to all objects in the root chart.The resulting @{i}chart of directions@{ui}
  is then compared with the root chart (i.e. the aspects between them are
  checked).@{i}The orbs for these aspects are much smaller than a regular ones,
  and they are about equal to the angular size of the Sun or Moon (~30')@{ui}.
    Although this is the maximal orb for effective usage of directions,
  their influence @{b}in tight conjunctions@{ub} is so powerful, that @{b}these arcs
  themselves are almost strong enough to initiate an event to take place@{ub}
  (related to them, of course) inside a very narrow timespan.@{b}With the help
  of directions it is possible to predict mayor events with the accuracy
  of just one week@{ub} (for years in advance).

    @{i}@{b}An always-working-classic-example is the arc between the Sun and the
  Venus@{ub}@{ui}.When this arc is fulfilled, one finds itself in love.The romance
  may not appear only in the cases when this arc is completed before the
  puberty/adolescence time, or when there are some physical limitations.
  If there is any chance for love to blossom, it will do that during a
  very narrow timespan when this arc is active.Whether this spark will
  caught fire depends on the overall conditions in the natal charts of
  both persons involved (@{i}higher order charts always take precedence@{ui}).

    According to many astrologers, @{i}directions are the most powerful during
  the first 3 decades of life@{ui} (Saturn's cycle?).@{i}After that they loose their
  accuracy@{ui}.(@{i}@{b}ASense note@{ub}@{ui}: More likely is that the computation method was not
  the correct one, and the errors simply accumulated over time.@{b}The ASense
  offers a selection of several thousands of directional methods@{ub}, which all
  differ very little between each other.Methods that are able to withstand
  the test of time passing are more likely to be the good ones.Nevertheless,
  please refer to the @{"coloring scheme" link ASENSE-DECIDE-COLORING-POLICY} to find out which choices are safe.)
    Moreover, @{i}only the hard aspects@{ui} (@{b}0°@{ub}, @{b}90°@{ub}, @{b}180°@{ub}, @{b}45°@{ub} and @{b}135°@{ub}) @{i}are usually@{ui}
  @{i}used@{ui}, since they manifest. Although, this is @{i}true@{ui}, and is a good argument,
  one must notice, that @{b}the @{"plane of reference" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC} may be wrong@{ub}. (@{b}2D trines are
  @{i}NOT@{ui} equal as 3D trines, while the main hard aspects retain their positions@{ub}.)

  IMPORTANT NOTE: @{i}@{b}If a predicted event does not appear at all,it is not an
  error of astrology, it is an error in the judgment of astrologer who has
  issued the prediction in the first place.The astrology would be in error
  if the predicted event occurs@{ub}@{ui} *@{b}outside@{ub}* @{i}@{b}of the tolerable limit defined by
  the validity of directional arc, and only if without any similar influence
  by some other direction/progression/return/transit or anything else that
  can enforce such a shift@{ub}@{ui}.It may look that the number of combination for
  this is endless (the possible excusses to say that the astrology works),
  but it actually isn't so.@{b}If something has worked once, it also has to
  work on @{i}any@{ui} other time, at least regarding the root chart in question@{ub}
  (@{i}@{b}i.e. it has to be repeatable to be scientificly acceptable@{ub}@{ui}).Mayor cause
  of problems for testing of astrology principles is that there are no such
  things as isolated laboratory cases in controled environment.There are
  no *identical*, but only more or less similar situations that are taking
  place.@{i}Extraction of individual influences of different active factors is
  a job for a very skilled and dilligent person, dedicated to the task@{ui}.
  (Leave that to the proffesionals, that is.)

    Effective utilisation of these principles may quickly rule out many
  of the available methods and submethods of predictions.Thousands of them
  are theoretically possible (@{i}and also included as options in the ASense@{ui}),
  but only a few should ever be used (i.e. those that produce *reliable*
  results).

  @{u}To accurately test the reliability of predictive methods@{uu}:
  1. @{b}Birth times must be known with the accuracy of 1 second@{ub}.
  2. @{b}Birth places must be known with the accuracy of 1 km@{ub}.
     (Coordinates taken from the atlases and/or from the web are NEVER
     that accurate! @{b}ONE MUST USE GPS SYSTEM TO GET THE ACCURATE DATA!@{ub})
  3. @{b}Biographical data must be recorded prior to the testing by a person
     @{i}qualified@{ui} to make scientific observations, preferably in a form of
     a diary or of a log file@{ub}.

  SUMMARY: @{b}If any method of prediction is not as reliable as the weather
  forecast, it is not reliable enough, and a replacement or an improvement
  should be considered@{ub}.(It is assumed that the above mentioned conditions
  for the quality of input data should be fulfilled prior to the testing.)

  @{u}Basic types of directions@{uu}:
  1. @{b}Primary@{ub} (classic directions) - a @{i}day@{ui} represents a @{i}year@{ui}.
     These directions connect 2 main solar cycles.

  2. @{b}Secondary@{ub} - a @{i}day@{ui} represents a @{i}month@{ui}.
  3. @{b}Tertiary@{ub} - a @{i}month@{ui} represents a @{i}year@{ui}.
     These 2 connect a lunar cycle with one of the main solar cycles.

    (@{i}@{b}Note a difference in order, in comparison with the progressions@{ub}@{ui}.)

  @{"More complex types of directions" link ASENSE-DIRECTIONS-COMPLEX}: (still unimplemented)
  a. @{b}House system based arcs@{ub} - every house system has their own.
  b. @{b}Conform directions@{ub} - @{b}time@{ub}(@{b}MC@{ub}(@{i}arc@{ui})) based regular charts.

  @{u}Obsolete terms@{uu}:
  - @{b}Naibod arcs@{ub} - @{i}mean ecliptical solar arcs@{ui}, named after @{i}Valentin Naibod@{ui},
    a XVI cty astrologer.(Mean arcs were good enough for manual methods of
    computation, but nowadays the computers do the job.They are obsolete.)
  - @{b}Ptolemaic arcs@{ub} - same as @{i}zodiacal arcs@{ui}.
  - @{b}Placidian arcs@{ub} - same as @{i}equatorial arcs@{ui}.
  - @{b}Radix directions@{ub} - Naibod arcs for everything, except for the Moon,
    which has to be shifted at '@{i}minor rate@{ui}' (@{i}mean ecliptical lunar arc@{ui}).
    @{i}Minor rate@{ui} == 13°10'35.02750" (mean daily ecliptical lunar motion),
    @{i}Mayor rate@{ui} ==  0°59' 8.33041" (daily Naibod arc).
      These values change only marginally over the centuries.
@endnode
///
///   Complex directions                                  //f
@node ASENSE-DIRECTIONS-COMPLEX "ASense - Directions: Complex"
@TOC ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-RING
@{b}@{u}More complex kinds of directions@{uu}@{ub}:

 a. @{b}House system based arcs@{ub} - @{i}once an @{"arc" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ARCS} is found, it is represented as the
    percentage of movement within the chosen house system. The same percentage
    is then applied to all other objects of the chart, including the angles@{ui}.
    @{u}Directed positions of objects are calculated by answering this question@{uu}:
    '@{b}What point on a daily path of the object lies @{i}arc-percents@{ui} away in the
     chart's house system from it's current position@{ub} ?'

 b. @{b}Conform directions@{ub} (recently formulated by @{i}@{b}Svarogich@{ub}@{ui}) - @{i}calculate an arc
    with any of the previously described methods, then shift MC for the value
    of that arc@{ui}. @{b}Find the time of day which the shifted MC represents and cast
    a chart for that time@{ub}. This chart is a @{i}regular@{ui} one (i.e. @{b}NOT@{ub} symbolic).

    - For the @{b}conform @{i}primary@{ui} directions@{ub}, this means to @{i}@{b}represent the whole
    lifetime with several hours of planetary movement@{ub}@{ui}. Only the Moon will
    exhibit a significant shift and perhaps, some of the inner planets.

    - For the @{b}conform @{i}secondary@{ui} directions@{ub}, @{b}the time interval length grows
    by the factor 12+@{ub}. The planets will have that much more time to perform
    some movement across the sky. This means increassing discrepancy between
    the traditionally and conform directed charts as the time from the birth
    passes by. @{i}@{b}The average lifetime is here represented by more than a day
    of planetary movement@{ub}@{ui}.

    - For the @{b}conform @{i}tertiary@{ui} directions@{ub}, @{i}the arcs are about 30 times larger
    than the primary ones@{ui}. The discrepancies between conform and traditional
    directions are thus becoming even higher as the time progresses, as @{i}@{b}the
    average lifetime is represented by less than a week of planetary motions@{ub}@{ui}
    in this case. The shifts remain very small for the outer planets, though.
@endnode
///
///   Show in a Ring                                      //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-RING "ASense - Menus: Choose Double Chart Mode"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-ANGLE-CROSSINGS
@{b}@{u}Show in a ring@{uu}@{ub}: enables a double chart mode.

    Whenever a secondary chart is required (@{i}transits, returns, progressions,
  directions@{ui}), it will be drawn in a ring around the primary one.@{b}This is a
  double chart@{ub}.

    Note that together with planets, the stars from the secondary chart may be
  drawn if that is required.They will be sprinkled over the zodiac ring circle.
  (@{"Choose/Show Stars" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SHOW-STARS} menu item must be selected).
@endnode
///
///   Angle Crossings                                     //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-ANGLE-CROSSINGS "ASense - Menus: Choose Angle Crossings"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-RING
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC
@{b}@{u}Angle crossings@{uu}@{ub}: how to compute a conjunction with an angle.
    Large, non point-like bodies (Sun, Moon, and, to some extent, @{i}Jupiter@{ui})
  take their time to cross a horizon.Based upon this, it is possible to
  @{u}choose which of the moments should be considered as an angle crossing@{uu}:
  1. Moment when the @{b}upper limb@{ub} of a body is on the horizon.
  2. Moment when the @{b}disk center@{ub} of a body is on the horizon.
  3. Moment when the @{b}lower limb@{ub} of a body is on the horizon.

    Additionally, choice of whether the @{i}@{b}refraction@{ub}@{ui} is required to be taken
  into account may influence the @{i}rising@{ui} and @{i}setting@{ui} times.This choice does
  not influence the meridian crossing times, but it does influence the
  values of @{i}altitudes@{ui} that are derived from these crossings.Note that these
  values are *@{b}not@{ub}* the maximal and minimal ones, although they are close to
  them.The @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} house system takes this into account.
    All angle crossing times may additionally be required to be searched
  within a specified time interval.
  @{u}The available intervals are@{uu}:
  - @{b}on a given date@{ub} (local chart date, that is)
  - @{b}on a previous day@{ub} (24 h @{i}before@{ui} the chart time max.)
  - @{b}on ±half a day@{ub} (±12 h from the chart time)
  - @{b}on next day@{ub} (24 h @{i}after@{ui} the chart time max.)

    All these refer to a chart's date, as taken locally.When there are no
  crossings within those time spans, that would be noted in the output.@{i}@{b}The
  movement of the planets (of the Moon especially), may cause that sometimes
  there are no specified angle crossings during a single day, whilst on the
  other occasions there may be 2 of them.In this situation, only the first
  one will be found.(Change the chart time slightly to find the other one.)@{ub}@{ui}

    Angle crossings time computations are performed when they are required
  @{i}specifically@{ui} by the user (@{"Display/Format 2" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-2} menu), or when @{i}@{b}Altitude@{ub}@{ui} houses
  are wanted (they are *@{b}not@{ub}* triggered by the above mentioned choices).
    @{i}@{b}Parans@{ub}@{ui} would also require the usage of angle crossings, but they were
  not yet implemented at the time of this writing.

    The algorithms are quite optimized, but @{i}these calculations are still
  time consuming on a very low end machines@{ui} (few seconds on my 020+FPU).
@endnode
///
///   Aspects Calc.                                       //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC "ASense - Menus: Choose Aspects Calc."
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-ANGLE-CROSSINGS
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES
@{b}@{u}Calculation of aspects@{uu}@{ub}: (2D/3D), angles, stars, tight orbs.
    There are several general things about aspects that has to be decided
  here.The most important one is whether they should be calculated as @{i}@{b}true@{ub}@{ui}
  angles in 3D (@{b}2 dimensions are spherical angles, and the third one is
  time!@{ub}), @{i}or as projections to some of the axes of an arbitrary chosen
  coordinate system@{ui}.In the latter case they would be calculated in 2D (@{b}one
  spherical angle and time@{ub}).

    @{u}Available coordinate systems for 2D calculations are standard ones@{uu}:
  @{i}@{b}ecliptical@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}equatorial@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}horizontal@{ub}@{ui}.The coordinates that can be used
  are @{i}ecliptic longitude@{ui}, @{i}right ascension@{ui}, and @{i}azimuth@{ui}, respectively.
  @{i}Prime verticale@{ui} coordinates are not an option, nor is it a completely
  user defined coordinate system.This is because the @{b}@{u}usage of 3D angles@{uu}@{ub}
  @{b}@{u}is *strongly suggested*@{uu}@{ub}.(Please read the chapter about the @{"aspects" link "ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS"} to
  learn why.)

    @{i}Note@{ui}: @{b}If draconic zodiac is required in combination with 2D ecliptical
  aspects, the ASense would@{ub} respect that, and @{b}calculate aspects @{u}*within the@{uu}@{ub}
  @{b}@{u}plane of the lunar orbit*@{uu}@{ub} (which is inclined about 5° to the plane of the
  ecliptic).@{b}The ecliptic longitudes/latitudes would be replaced by '@{i}draconic@{ui}
  longitudes/latitudes'@{ub} everywhere (data tables and computation of aspects).

    The choice of angle projections significantly enlarges the available
  number of subtypes of @{i}cyclic@{ui} charts (@{i}returns@{ui}, @{i}progressions@{ui}, @{i}directions@{ui}),
  because it affects their methods of computation.

    As an optional exception of the rule, @{b}conjunctions may be calculated
  in 2D when 3D mode is required for other aspects@{ub}.This is because @{i}stars@{ui}
  were traditionally handled that way.@{i}Historically, only 2D ecliptical
  conjunctions with the stars were taken into account@{ui}, and the other
  aspects (whether @{i}true@{ui} or not) were neglected.) Rarely, @{i}oppositions@{ui} and
  @{i}squares@{ui} were also considered, but note that @{i}@{b}2D squares are identical
  with those in 3D, and the oppositions are close to being identical@{ub}@{ui}.
  (@{i}This is one more good reason to use the unambiguous '3D aspects' mode@{ui}.)

  @{u}Other choices that have to be made are simple switches@{uu}:
  - @{b}Force 2D Conj. for Stars@{ub} - when this switch is ON, @{i}the conjunctions which
    involve stars will be calculated in 2D, even if 3D conjunctions and other
    aspects are required for solar system bodies@{ui}.This switch is introduced to
    acknowledge the fact that latitudes of stars were historically neglected,
    and also because without it, only @{i}zodiac@{ui} stars will ever be able to form
    a conjunction, and @{i}even@{ui} them would usually be too far away from a passing
    planet to form a 3D conjunction with it.(With the aspects to stars turned
    @{i}off@{ui}, very few stars would ever show up in a chart (usually none at all)).
    @{i}This option is ON by default@{ui}.

  - @{b}Aspects to Angles@{ub} - angles are taken as regular points with orbs, and
    that allows the calculation of aspects in a normal way.However, there
    isn't much merrit in using this option, because the angles are not
    real objects and they actually work only by producing @{i}angularities@{ui}.
    (Which means that @{i}they work only when an object is conjuncting them@{ui}.)
    When this option is ON, the aspects to angles would be calculated.
    @{i}This option is OFF by default@{ui}.

  - @{b}Aspects to Stars@{ub} - stars were traditionally not treated in such a
    way.Those who have tried to use the aspects with stars (apart from
    the ecliptical conjunctions) have failed.This is because they
    a. haven't used @{i}true@{ui} angles for their computation, or
    b. @{i}allowed too large orbs@{ui} for stars (traditionally 1° is used,
       which is several times waaay too large).@{b}An orb of a star is
       a tricky thing, and is only a few minutes wide even for very
       bright stars@{ub}.The very faint ones have almost negligible orbs.
    c. @{i}perhaps the stars, as a skeleton of the sky, really do not
       affect the chart by aspects, and work only as projections to
       the solar plane@{ui}.This possibility has to be investigated, though.
    Nevertheless, a possibility to compute the aspects to stars exists.
    When this option is ON, the aspects to stars would be calculated.
    When this option is OFF, only conjunctions would be considered.
    @{i}This option is OFF by default@{ui}.

  - @{b}Very Tight Orbs@{ub} - when there are too many aspects in the chart, it
    may be useful to tighten the orbs to filter away the weaker aspects.
    It is also useful to turn ON this option when analyzing a temporary
    chart of low importance and duration, like a horary chart for example.
    @{b}When this option is ON, orbs of all objects would be reduced by half@{ub}.
    @{i}This option is OFF by default@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Sidereal Modes                                      //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES "ASense - Zodiac: Sidereal modes"
@TOC ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-SHOW-STARS 

  @{b}@{u}Sidereal modes@{uu}@{ub}: These methods are only usefull if one is using a sidereal
  astrology, and are completely useless otherwise.

    @{b}Traditional@{ub} method cancels the effect of precession ONLY during the
  transformation to the fixed ecliptic, thus making a slight error in
  calculations, one which is tolerable for manual chart calculations,
  but certainly *not* for a computer based ones.
    This method is very approximate, so that the error may reach several
  degrees after few 1,000 years.

    @{b}Accurate@{ub} method correctly cancels both the precessional and nutational
  shifts in the planetary positions during their projectings to the fixed
  ecliptic, as well as the changes in ecliptical obliquity over time.
    This is a default.

@endnode
///
///   Show *s                                             //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-SHOW-STARS "ASense - Menus: Choose to Show Stars"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-R-STARS
@{b}@{u}Show Stars@{uu}@{ub}: enables showing of a stars.

    If there are any stars checked in the '@{i}Select/Stars@{ui}' menu, and some of
  them are found to be @{b}prominent@{ub} (i.e. relevant to the chart being drawn),
  these will be then drawn as well if this switch is ON.
    When this switch is OFF, the required data about the prominent stars
  will only be displayed in a textfield area, but the stars themselves will
  not be drawn on the chart.
@endnode
///
///   Mark Retrograde *s                                  //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-R-STARS "ASense - Menus: Choose to Mark Retrograde Stars"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-SHOW-STARS
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-ORIENTATION
@{b}@{u}Mark Retrograde Stars@{uu}@{ub}: enables special coloring for these stars.

    If this switch is ON, when the glyphs of the stars are printed on the chart,
  the retrograde ones will be shown with a special color (default is @{i}black@{ui}).
  This, however, will override the spectra coloring information, which is going
  to be lost this way.Therefore, by default, this switch is turned OFF.(The
  spectra has priority.)

  NOTE: If you select @{i}geocentric astrometric positions, with precession and
  nutation switches turned OFF@{ui}, you may notice that @{i}one half of the stars
  are black@{ui} (i.e. found to be retrograde), @{i}and the other half are not@{ui}.This
  clearly points to direction of a solar system's movement within the Galaxy,
  as it seems that all stars are moving away from that point, and going
  toward an opposite point in space.(The solar @{b}apex@{ub} is currently in the
  constellation of @{b}Hercules@{ub} (the direction of movement), and we are moving
  away from the constellation of @{i}@{b}Columba@{ub}@{ui}, which contains the solar @{i}@{b}antapex@{ub}@{ui}.)
@endnode
///
///   Orientation                                         //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-ORIENTATION "ASense - Menus: Choose Orientation"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-R-STARS
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION
@{b}@{u}Orientation to Sky@{uu}@{ub}: a preferred view of the sky.

    A view of the sky differs, depending on which side of the Earth one
  stands.Thus, @{i}the Ascendant, which is always on the east side, may end
  up either on the left or on the right side of the observer@{ui}.

  @{u}3 possibilities exist@{uu}:
  - @{b}Northern@{ub} - always depict the sky, as it looks like when viewed from
    moderate northern latitudes (i.e. @{i}east is to the left of the chart@{ui}).

  - @{b}Southern@{ub} - always depict the sky, as it looks like when viewed from
    moderate southern latitudes (i.e. @{i}east is to the right of the chart@{ui}).

  - @{b}Combined@{ub} - selects one of the above 2 views, depending on the actual
    location of the chart (i.e. the local view is always presented in
    such a way that the ecliptic is in front of the observer).@{i}Within the
    equatorial regions of the globe this may be sometimes a northern, and
    sometimes a southern view, depending on a time of day@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Presentation                                        //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION "ASense - Menus: Choose Presentation"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-ORIENTATION
@NEXT ASENSE-CHOOSE-2ND_COOR
@{b}@{u}Presentation Modes@{uu}@{ub}: available projection types - standard or @{i}planetarium@{ui}.

    A regular astrological chart is a 1-dimensional entity: it presents
  only the ecliptical coordinate in a circle (or sometimes on a square).
  However, the sphere of heavens is described with the spherical system
  of coordinates, which has 2 angular coordinates.Thus, for one to have
  a realistic picture of the sky, it is neccessary to somehow depict the
  other angular coordinate in the chart (@{i}latitudes@{ui}, @{i}declinations@{ui} and
  @{i}altitudes@{ui} for @{i}ecliptic@{ui}, @{i}equatorial@{ui} and @{i}horizon@{ui} systems respectively).

  @{u}There are 3 available modes@{uu}:
  1. @{b}1 Coordinate@{ub} - Regular chart.

  2. @{b}2 Coordinates, Ringed@{ub} - both coordinates are displayed.@{i}@{b}The other
     angle is scaled to fit between the inner zodiac circle and the
     outer small circle in the centre of the chart, which is a form
     of a ring@{ub}@{ui}.Inevitably, this approach yields to overlapping of the
     planetary glyphs occasionally, which is a downfall of the method.
     @{b}@{i}Stars are drawn in the outside ring, as usual, unless it is a@{ui}
     'Star Chart', @{i}in which case they are drawn on the inside part@{ui}@{ub}.

  3. @{b}2 Coordinates, Conic, Sided@{ub} - the most realistic view of the sky.
     @{i}@{b}2 sides of the globe are presented as they are on 2 charts.One
     for the upper and the other for the lower half, with zero being
     a border@{ub}@{ui}.(For a horizon system, @{i}refraction@{ui} is handled automatically
     if it is required !) It is not possible to draw aspects in such a
     chart, and @{i}@{b}prominent stars are drawn together with the planets@{ub}@{ui},
     hence increasing the chance for the occurance of overlapping.

  Modes 2 and 3 are @{i}planetarium@{ui} modes.
@endnode
///
///   2nd Coordinate                                      //f
@node ASENSE-CHOOSE-2ND_COOR "ASense - Menus: Choose 2nd Coordinate"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@PREV ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE
@{b}@{u}2nd Coordinate to present@{uu}@{ub}: Required only in @{"planetarium" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION} modes.

  @{u}Available choices@{uu}:

  1. @{b}Pair of first@{ub} - The 2nd coordinate depends upon the choice of first.
     This means that if the first coordinate is @{i}ecliptic longitude@{ui}, the
     other would be the @{i}ecliptic latitude@{ui}.The other currently available
     pairs are @{i}right ascension & declination@{ui} and @{i}azimuth & altitude@{ui}.

  2. @{b}Declination@{ub} - Force the 2nd coordinate to always be the @{i}declination@{ui}.
     The auxiliary cirles are: (based on true ecliptic obliquity)
     inner blue - border of a polar circle (~66..67°).
     outer blue - border of equatorial regions (~23..24°).
     gray circle - geographic latitude of the place (declination of the place).
  3. @{b}Latitude@{ub} - Force the 2nd coordinate to always be the @{i}latitude@{ui}.
     Auxiliary circle is the border of ecliptic (latitude of 8°).
  4. @{b}Altitude@{ub} - Force the 2nd coordinate to always be the @{i}altitude@{ui}.
     Auxiliary circle is the circle of rotation of the acme point of the equator
     on local horizon (i.e. the colatitude of the place).

  5. @{b}Refr. Altitude@{ub} - Force the 2nd coordinate to always be the @{i}@{b}refracted@{ub}
     altitude@{ui}.
@endnode
///
@remark Charts
/// Charts                                                //f
@node ASENSE-MENUCHARTS "ASense - Menus: Charts"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-CHARTS-SINGLE
@{b}@{u}Charts@{uu}@{ub}: From this menu, you may quickly cast charts (*@{i}without@{ui}* offsets).

  @{"Single Charts" link ASENSE-CHARTS-SINGLE} - Charts that require data from only one side to be cast.
  @{"Dual Charts" link ASENSE-CHARTS-DUAL} - Charts that require data from both sides to be cast.
  @{"Synastry" link ASENSE-CHARTS-SYNASTRY} - Both sides are recalculated and compared with each other.
  @{"Ephemeris" link ASENSE-CHARTS-EPHEMERIS} - A versatile ephemeris generator.

  NOTE: Delineation of created charts is not the subject of this manual, nor
  is yet available as an automatic process in the ASense.The user is assumed
  to have some background knowledge about some basic astrology skills, like
  chart reading.If not, please consult some of the numerous astrology books.
@endnode
///
///   Single Charts                                       //f
@node ASENSE-CHARTS-SINGLE "ASense - Menus: Single Charts"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHARTS
@PREV ASENSE-MENUCHARTS
@NEXT ASENSE-SINGLE-STARS
@{b}@{u}Single Charts@{uu}@{ub} - Charts that require data from only one side to be cast.

  @{b}Natal@{ub} - a.k.a @{i}@{b}Radix@{ub}@{ui} (root) chart, a chart for the birth.
      A natal chart is cast for the birth's time and place and remains valid
    for the entire life span.This is the most basic chart type of all.You'll
    be using it a lot.
  @{b}Solar Return@{ub} - @{i}yearly@{ui} chart, cast for birthdays.
      Solar return is a chart which has to be cast for the moment when the
    Sun occupies identical position as it did on birth.The ASense forks a
    number of possibilities for this, depending on choices made by user in
    @{"Decide" link ASENSE-MENUDECIDE} and @{"Choose" link ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE} menus.A chart remains valid until the next birthday.
    This is a moderately important chart and requires some experience to
    be read successfuly.It is cast occasionally, to honor one's birthday.
      @{i}Methods of a day-by-day progression of the solar return chart aren't
    yet handled by the ASense@{ui}.
  @{b}Transits@{ub} - temporary chart, for a random moment (usually a current one).
    This chart is very frequently used.
  @{b}Return@{ub} - cast a chosen @{"return" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS} cyclic chart.
  @{b}Progress@{ub} - cast a chosen @{"progression" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS} cyclic chart.
  @{b}Directions@{ub} - cast a chosen @{"direction" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS} cyclic chart.
  @{b}Stars@{ub} - cast a @{"Star Chart" link ASENSE-SINGLE-STARS}.
    This is not an astrology chart, but a specific view of the sky.
  @{b}Harmonics@{ub} - cast a chart of a random harmonic.
    @{i}This option is not yet implemented@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///     Star Chart                                        //f
@node ASENSE-SINGLE-STARS "ASense - Single Charts: Star Chart"
@TOC ASENSE-CHARTS-SINGLE
@PREV ASENSE-CHARTS-SINGLE
@NEXT ASENSE-CHARTS-DUAL
@{b}@{u}Star Chart@{uu}@{ub} - the chart of stars only.

    A Star Chart is a chart without the planets that displays @{b}all@{ub} of the
  @{i}selected@{ui} stars.@{b}The second coordinate is distance@{ub} (in parsecs).Several
  stars which are further away than the limit are placed at the outside
  border (actually few pixels closer to the center than the inner ring of
  zodiac).Distance of 0 is the edge of the outer one of the inner circles.
    On the outside edge you may observe the @{i}@{b}Belt of Orion@{ub}@{ui} (3 purple stars
  of spectral type O at the end of Gemini sign, with a 1st magnitude blue
  star nearby (@{i}Rigel@{ui}, the foot of Orion).
    On the inside edge, there are 3 1st magnitude stars: the white one is
  the brightest star of all, @{i}@{b}Sirius@{ub}@{ui}, a star of spectral type A.The yellow
  one (with a small red dot sometimes visible in the middle of its glyph),
  is the closest star system of all, @{i}@{b}alpha Centauri@{ub}@{ui} (a.k.a. @{i}Bungula@{ui}, a.k.a.
  @{i}Toliman@{ui}), star identical to our Sun, but somewhat older, 4.4 light years
  away.It has 2 companions, a K star at a distant as Uranus is to our Sun,
  with a period of 80 year, and a small red dwarf @{i}@{b}Proxima@{ub}@{ui} (a faint M star,
  represented with the above mentioned red dot).As its name says, Proxima
  (@{i}The Closest@{ui}) is the closest star to ous, only 4.2 ly away.It is a part
  of the alp Cen system, but its orbit may be hyperbolic.
    The green one of the close 1st magnitude stars is @{i}Procyon@{ui}, an F star.
@endnode
///
///   Dual Charts                                         //f
@node ASENSE-CHARTS-DUAL "ASense - Menus: Dual Charts"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHARTS
@PREV ASENSE-CHARTS-SINGLE
@NEXT ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING
@{b}@{u}Dual Charts@{uu}@{ub} - Charts that require data from both sides to be cast.

  @{"Chart merging techniques" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING}:
  - @{b}Relationship@{ub} (a.k.a. @{i}Davison Relationship Chart@{ui}) - merge charts by merging
    their input data (date/time/location).
  - @{b}Composite@{ub} - merge charts by merging their content.
  - @{b}Coalescent@{ub} - other way to merge charts by merging their content.

  @{b}Return for time ONLY@{ub} - cast a chosen @{"return" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS} cyclic chart that is valid on a
    date and time on the other side, but use the location from a @{"cyclic string" link ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW 9}
    on this side.
  @{b}Return for time & space@{ub} - cast a chosen return chart that is valid on a time
    on the other side, and is cast for a place on the other side, instead on
    the one given by the cycle string on this side.
  @{b}Transits for time ONLY@{ub} - cast a temporary chart for a date and time from the
    other side, but use the locational data from a cycle string on this side.
  @{b}Transits for time & space@{ub} -  cast a chart for date, time and location from
    the other side.This is identical as casting a Natal Chart on that side.
  @{b}Progress for time ONLY@{ub} - cast a chosen @{"progression" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS} cyclic chart which is
    valid on a date and time from the other side, but use the locational data
    from this side's cycle string.
  @{b}Progress for time & space@{ub} - cast a chosen progression cyclic chart that is
    valid on a date and time from the other side, and also use the place from
    the other side.

  @{b}Directions (arc for date)@{ub} - cast a chosen @{"direction" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS} @{i}cyclic@{ui} chart which is
    valid on a date and time from the other side, but use the locational data
    from this side's cycle string.
  @{b}Directions for time&space@{ub} - cast a chosen direction @{i}cyclic@{ui} chart which is
    valid on a date and time from the other side, and cast it for the place
    from the other side.
@endnode
///
///     Chart merging techniques                          //f
@node ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING "ASense - Menus: Chart Merging Techniques"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHARTS
@PREV ASENSE-CHARTS-DUAL
@NEXT ASENSE-CHARTS-SYNASTRY
@{b}@{u}Chart merging techniques@{uu}@{ub}: Merge two (or several) charts into one.

    These charts were invented in an attempt to simplify a comparison
  between charts.@{b}While in synastry, there are always @{i}two@{ui} charts which
  have to be compared, these techniques yield only @{i}one@{ui} resulting chart
  that has to be analyzed@{ub}, which is a great reduction of complexity.

    @{i}@{b}These techniques also allow an easy merger between a large number
  of charts (for a group of people, for example), which is impossible
  in synastry@{ub}@{ui}.This is a great advantage.

  NOTE: @{b}In the case of multiple charts, a barycenter is to be found and
  then projected on the average distance of involved objects.The objects
  may have different '@{i}weights@{ui}', to handle the case when a single person
  dominates in a group with ease.The assignment of weights is a tricky
  thing in that case, and should be related to individual natal charts
  (or positions of bodies)@{ub}.The '@{i}weighting@{ui}' method is not yet handled by
  ASense (i.e. @{i}it is assumed that all objects@{ui} (or persons) @{i}are of equal
  importance in a chart, an assumptions which is rarely satisfied@{ui}).

   In this version of ASense, @{b}only mergers of 2 charts are supported@{ub}.

    A possible caveat is that the resulting chart is a @{i}@{b}derived@{ub}@{ui} one, which
  makes sense only if a group of people which is analyzed (consisting in
  our case of only 2 of them) really represents a single entity of some sort
  (i.e. a @{i}couple@{ui}, or a @{i}team@{ui}), pursuing a same goal.
                                                           
    One must also be aware of discrepancy between the @{"zodiacs" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC} when trying
  to merge charts into one.To avoid it, one must calculate all of the charts
  in a (@{i}real@{ui}) sidereal zodiac, using the @{i}accurate@{ui} @{"sidereal mode" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES}.
    Alternatively, one may turn ON the following menu switch:

  '@{b}Refer to Midtime Ecl.@{ub}' - If this switch is ON, the midtime ecliptic will
    be set as the user defined sidereal ecliptic, and @{i}both charts will be
    calculated as @{"sid(ereal)" link ASENSE-SIDEREAL-VS-SID} charts that refer to the midtime ecliptic@{ui}. In
    this way, the resulting chart will also refer to the same ecliptic.
      @{b}This switch works only if a default zodiac is @{i}not@{ui} a sid(ereal) one@{ub}.
    (Otherwise the sidereal settings would take precedence.) It affects only
    @{i}composite@{ui} and @{i}coalescent@{ui} charts.

    The second possible cause of discrepancies is the @{i}difference between the
  locations@{ui} for which the initial charts are cast.In a case when @{i}topocentric@{ui}
  planetary positions are wanted, small positional errors occur.To avoid them,
  one must either switch to @{i}geocentric@{ui} planetary positions or relocate both
  charts to the merged location (@{i}midplace@{ui}).This ensures the same topocenter.

  '@{b}Locate on Midplace@{ub}' - @{i}both charts are relocated to midplace of their data
    prior of calculating the planetary positions@{ui}.This appraoch is important
    only if @{i}topocentric@{ui} planetary positions are wanted, and it affects only
    @{i}composite@{ui} and @{i}coalescent@{ui} charts.
      @{i}Midplace@{ui} is the location obtained upon merging initial positional data.

  @{u}Methods of chart merging@{uu}:
  1. @{b}In 2D (midpoints of individual coordinates)@{ub} - simple, but @{i}unambiguous@{ui}.
       In this case, the individual coordinates of some coordinate system
     (usually @{i}ecliptical@{ui}, or @{i}equatorial@{ui}) are handled independently of each
     other.The resulting point thereupon differs from one plane to another
     and hence is unambiguous by it's nature (i.e. depends upon the choice
     of a coordinate system).
  2. @{b}In 3D (midpoints on a Great Circle)@{ub} - complicated, but @{i}unique@{ui} solution.
       Since there is only @{i}one@{ui} Great Circle that passes through a pair of
     points on a sphere, there is only @{i}one@{ui} possible solution in this case.
     (In extreme case, @{b}when the points are on the opposite side of a circle,
     the choice between 2 equally distant midpoints should be made upon the
     @{i}speeds@{ui} of their movement.If the speeds are equal@{ub} (usually equal to zero),
     @{b}the@{ub} (above mentioned) @{b}@{i}weighting method@{ui} of involved objects should be
     consulted to determine the result@{ub}.)

  @{u}Types of chart merging@{uu}:
  @{b}Relationship Chart@{ub} - @{i}@{b}combines 2 charts by merging their initial data.
      The result depends on@{ub}@{ui} whether a merging is to be done over the great
    circles connecting counterpairing objects, or by finding the midpoints
    of each one of their coordinates separately (i.e. on @{i}@{b}a chosen method
    of charts merging@{ub}@{ui}).
      This chart type was invented by @{b}Ronald Davison@{ub}, British astrologer,
    and hence it (frequently) bears it's name (@{i}@{b}Davison Relationship Chart@{ub}@{ui}).
    He originally used a 2D merging method (3D was added later by others).
      The comments say that @{i}this chart type describes only a @{b}potential for a
    relationship@{ub}, and not the relationship itself@{ui} (this stems from the fact
    that the merging occurs on the @{i}initial@{ui} data, and not on the @{i}obtained@{ui} one,
    which is an @{i}earlier@{ui} step during the computation)...
      @{i}There is no consensus on how to create a multiple relationship chart of
    people who do not have the same (or almost identical) place of birth@{ui}.
      This chart is a @{i}regular@{ui} chart (based on regular date/place combination),
    and thereby has no limitations of other types of merged charts (which are
    only @{i}derivations@{ui}).
      @{i}The ASense supports both ways of creating a Relationship@{ui} Chart (2D & 3D
    merge of geographical coordinates).

  @{b}Composite Chart@{ub} - @{i}@{b}combines 2 charts by finding midpoints of coordinates
    of charted objects (the closer ones).The result depends on@{ub}@{ui} whether a
    merging is to be done over the great circles connecting counterpairing
    objects, or by finding the midpoints of each one of their coordinates
    separately (i.e. on @{i}@{b}a chosen method of charts merging@{ub}@{ui}).
      The method appeared in 1920s, and has an unknown origin.It is rarely
    used, but @{i}the comments say that it describes @{b}the actual relationship@{ub},
    if one actually occurs...
      There is no consensus on how to make a composite of multiple charts@{ui}.
      Traditionally, for the sake of simplicity, composite charts were created
    from the ecliptical longitudes only.Latitudes and other planes of reference
    were usually ignored.The ASense, however, takes a more thorough approach,
    @{u}according to the chosen method of merging@{uu}:
    - in @{b}2D merging@{ub}, midpoints of 3 spherical coordinates are found @{i}separately@{ui},
    - in @{b}3D merging@{ub}, midpoint on a @{i}great circle@{ui} is found, and (separately)
    midpoint of distances.
      Initial coordinates for the computation are taken from the chosen @{i}plane
    of reference@{ui}.Other requested coordinates are then derived from the results.
      @{b}Currently supported planes of reference are @{i}ecliptic@{ui} and @{i}draconic@{ui}@{ub}, which
    means that there is a total of @{b}3 ways to create a composite chart in ASense@{ub}.
    (Merging can be done on one of the planes of reference or in 3D on a great
    circle.The chosen plane is the one that is selected to be drawn in a chart.)
      @{i}@{b}The speeds of objects are NOT recalculated, but merged instead.This
    is a compromise between correctness and simplicity@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}Coalescent Chart@{ub} - @{i}@{b}combines 2 charts by finding the lowest harmonic positions
    of charted objects.The result depends on@{ub}@{ui} whether a coalescing is to be done
    over the great circles connecting counterpairing objects, or by finding the
    coalescents of each one of their coordinates separately (i.e. on @{i}@{b}a chosen
    method of charts merging@{ub}@{ui}}).
      This chart type was invented by @{b}Lawrence Grinnel@{ub} (@{i}@{b}Dhruva@{ub}@{ui}) during the XX
    century.Although it is a very rarely used obscure chart, @{i}the comments say
    that it describes @{b}the outcome of a relationship@{ub} (the offspring)@{ui}, and that
    it also shows an unusual sensitivity to transits... (@{i}Delineation stems
    from the fact that this chart type is a derivation of a 2nd degree order@{ui}.)
      @{i}There is no consensus on how to coalesc multiple charts.@{ui}

    @{u}Finding of a (lowest) harmonic position is done with the formula@{uu}:

      @{i}@{b}pos_1h@{ub}@{ui} == @{i}@{b}pos_2h@{ub}@{ui} = (360.0 / fabs(@{i}pos_1@{ui} - @{i}pos_2@{ui})) * @{i}pos_i@{ui}; // @{i}i@{ui} = 1 or 2

    (@{i}pos_1h@{ui} == @{i}pos_2h@{ui} because all values are normalized to a 0..360.0° range.)
    (@{b}Both initial positions are multiplied with the same number (non-integer)
     to obtain identical result (when the results are renormalized to a circle).
     The number is called a @{i}harmonic number@{ui}, and the obtained position is a
     @{i}harmonic position@{ui}@{ub}.The harmonic number itself is not calculated, but is
     eliminated from the equations, since it is not important.)
      Traditionally, for the sake of simplicity, only the ecliptical longitudes
    were coalesced, but the ASense takes a more thorough approach, and offers

    VERY IMPORTANT WARNING: @{b}Coalescing of bodies which are very close to each
    other in zodiac is VERY sensitive to time errors in data@{ub}.For example, @{i}if
    one tries to coalesc the positions of the Sun in two charts for people who
    have the same birthday, one would promptly find out that even an error of
    1 s in input time data in any of two charts would significantly alter the
    resulting position of the coalesced Sun@{ui}.Locational data errors are also
    influental, but not to such extent.

    @{u}3 methods of coalescing@{uu}:
    1. @{b}Single, 1D coalescing@{ub} (simple coalescing) - first spherical coordinate
       is coalesced, the other 2 are merged by midpoints, separately.
    2. @{b}Double, 2D coalescing@{ub} (wild coalescing) - two spherical coordinates
       are coalesced separately, while the distance is merged by midpoints.
    3. @{b}Great Circle Coalescing@{ub} - Coalescing is done on a great circle that
       connects the points.The starting point is taken as the crossing of
       that great circle with a chosen plane of reference (usually ecliptic).

    IMPORTANT NOTE: @{b}Due to the presence of unresolved logical error in reasoning
    (which one of 2 crossing points is the origin of a great circle), the third
    method is temporarily disabled.@{ub} :-(

      @{b}Currently supported planes of reference are @{i}ecliptic@{ui} and @{i}draconic@{ui}@{ub}, which
    means that there is a total of @{b}12 ways to coalesc a chart in the ASense@{ub}.
    (The chosen plane is the one that is selected to be drawn in a chart.)
      @{i}@{b}The speeds of objects are NOT recalculated, but merged instead.This
    is a compromise between correctness and simplicity@{ub}@{ui}.

  IMPORTANT NOTE: Finding a @{b}house positions@{ub} of @{b}accurately@{ub} @{i}combined@{ui} or
  @{i}coalesced@{ui} bodies is a complicated procedure.In 3D world, the houses
  are slices of a sphere, and when calculated for different zodiacs,
  the central axes are not colinear.Hence, @{b}to find a resulting house
  system, one must find the @{i}midaxes@{ui} between central axes, and then the
  @{i}midplanes@{ui} between all planes that make the house borders@{ub} (in order of
  the houses).Taking into account the shear number of various currently
  existing house systems, this is a *huge* (and pointless?) task.
    To avoid the mess, the ASense takes into account that it presents
  the @{"(Aa)ltitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} house system as the most advanced of all house systems.
  It has the advantage that it doesn't need the house borders to obtain
  a house position of a body.Thereupon, it is a straightforward solution
  for this problem.However, since the speeds are cumbersome to calculate
  (they are only approximately calculated for the sake of simplicity), a
  @{i}dynamic@{ui} (Altitude) version of this house system is not yet available,
  which leaves the @{b}@{i}static@{ui} (altitude) house system as the only choice@{ub}.

  NOTE: @{b}For composite and coalescent charts, the houses are NOT merged, but
  instead recalculated from midpoints of times and of coordinates@{ub} (i.e., they
  are the same houses as in a Relationship Chart).@{b}@{i}Vertex@{ui}, @{i}equatorial ascendant@{ui},
  @{i}inclination of a lunar orbit@{ui} and @{i}arabic parts@{ui} were also recalculated in a
  similar manner@{ub}.@{i}@{b}The lunar nodes, however, ARE merged, and hence aren't the
  real nodes from a midtime ecliptic@{ub}@{ui}.This is a deliberate choice, since they
  are treated as bodies with orbs, and not as a part of a background scenery...
  @{b}Note that this doesn't affect the draconic transformations, which ARE done
  with the use of real nodes from the midtime ecliptic@{ub} (calculated separately).
  As a consequence of merging process, @{b}THE COALESCED NODES ARE NOT OPPOSITE TO
  EACH OTHER@{ub} (i.e. @{i}@{b}they can be anywhere, and even conjunct each other@{ub}@{ui}!).@{b}This
  is a feature of coalesced charts@{ub}, not a bug! @{i}Composite@{ui} nodes appear normal.
@endnode
///
///   Synastry                                            //f
@node ASENSE-CHARTS-SYNASTRY "ASense - Menus: Synastry"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHARTS
@PREV ASENSE-CHARTS-DUAL
@NEXT ASENSE-CHARTS-EPHEMERIS
@{b}@{u}Synastry@{uu}@{ub} - Both sides are recalculated and compared with each other.

  @{u}Available possibilities@{uu}:
  '@{b}Left & Left->Right@{ub}' - cast @{i}left@{ui} chart alone on the @{i}left@{ui} side, and also
   cast a @{i}right@{ui} chart on the @{i}right@{ui} side, with the @{i}left@{ui} chart in the outer
   ring of a @{i}right@{ui} chart.The aspects drawn on the @{i}right@{ui} side are those in
   between 2 charts (left & right).
  ... (and so on)

  @{b}@{u}Chart comparing techniques@{uu}@{ub}:
  - @{b}Synastry charts@{ub} are used as a method of comparison between two charts.
  They try to indicate how one person affects the other by analysing @{i}@{b}mutual
  aspects@{ub}@{ui} between their charts.
  - @{i}@{b}Mutual aspects@{ub}@{ui} are always calculated and displayed with synastry and other
  @{i}double@{ui} charts (second chart in a ring around the inner one).
  - @{i}@{b}Mutual house positions@{ub}@{ui} are usually analyzed in synastry charts, but the
  ASense is also capable of calculating them separately.Select a switch in a
  @{"Display/Format 1/House Pos. (Swap)" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1 48} menu item to force their computation
  and check out a @{i}Format 1@{ui} table for the results.The output depends on the
  chosen @{"house system" link ASENSE-DECIDE-HS}.
  - @{i}@{b}Structural similarity@{ub}@{ui} - Two charts may have similar @{i}patterns@{ui} of aspects,
  or same planets may be located in same houses, or same type(s) of aspect(s)
  may dominate the charts, or the focus of a chart may be in a same house for
  both charts, or both charts may have the same body in 'highlighted' position
  (with the strongest almuten, or as final dispositor, or something else),...
    @{i}These comparisons are representing a higher level of chart analysis, and
  are not yet implemented in this initial version of ASense@{ui}.They will added in
  future upgrades.

  NOTE: One must be aware of discrepancy between the moving @{"zodiacs" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC} during
  a creation of synastry charts.To avoid it, one must calculate @{b}both@{ub} charts
  in a (@{i}real@{ui}) sidereal zodiac with @{i}accurate@{ui} @{"sidereal mode" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES}.
@endnode
///
///   Ephemeris                                           //f
@node ASENSE-CHARTS-EPHEMERIS "ASense - Menus: Ephemeris"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUCHARTS
@PREV ASENSE-CHARTS-SYNASTRY
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUCHARTS
@{b}@{u}Ephemeris@{uu}@{ub} - A versatile ephemeris generator.

    The ASense has a very versatile ephemeris generator.It is possible to
  create ephemeris for random time intervals and for random steps.One may
  also turn @{i}on/off@{ui} whatever is available on a @{"Select/Physics" link ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS} (@{b}note this!@{ub}),
  @{i}@{b}Select/Planets@{ub}@{ui}, @{"Select/Nodes" link ASENSE-SELECT-NODES}, @{"Display/Header" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-HEADER} (except few local things),
  @{"Display/Format1" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1} (except of house positions) and @{"Display/Format2" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-2} menus.
    @{"Display/Format3" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-3} menu is not yet handled.

  @{u}Ephemeris@{uu}:
    @{b}Chart's Month(s)@{ub} - cast ephemeris for a month given in input string.
      (Or maybe 2 months if the '@{i}2 Nearest Months@{ui}' switch is turned on.)
    @{b}Current Month(s)@{ub} - cast ephemeris for a @{i}current@{ui} month.
      (Or maybe 2 months if the '@{i}2 Nearest Months@{ui}' switch is turned on.)
    @{b}Chart's Year@{ub} - cast ephemeris for a year given in input string.
    @{b}Current Year@{ub} - cast ephemeris for a @{i}current@{ui} year.
    ('@{b}Ef@{ub}' @{"button" link ASENSE-GADGETS-BOTTOM-ROW}) - cast ephemeris for a time interval between 2 input strings.
      This option utilises @{i}time offsets@{ui} and is not available from the menu.

  @{u}Switches@{uu}:
    @{i}@{b}2 Nearest Months@{ub}@{ui} - make ephemeris for 2, instead for just 1 month.
      This option is useful only when monthly ephemeris are required.

    @{i}@{b}Weekdays@{ub}@{ui} - include a column for weekdays.
    @{i}@{b}Sidereal Times@{ub}@{ui} - include a column for sidereal times.

    @{u}Tables@{uu}:
      @{i}@{b}Ecl. Long. ONLY@{ub}@{ui} - make ephemeris of @{i}ecliptic longitudes@{ui} only.
        (Ignore other switches on '@{i}Display/Format i@{ui}' menus.)
      @{i}@{b}Selected Coors.@{ub}@{ui} - make separate ephemeris of all @{i}coordinates@{ui} available
        on '@{i}Display/Format i@{ui}' menus.
      @{i}@{b}Rise/Set/Mer.Tr.@{ub}@{ui} - make separate ephemeris of @{i}angle crossing times@{ui} and
        @{i}daily extreme altitudes@{ui}.

    @{u}Events (things that happen occasionally, listed at the bottom)@{uu}:
      @{i}@{b}Stationary Times@{ub}@{ui} - find times when objects change direction of movement
        (@{i}prograde@{ui} <-> @{i}retrograde@{ui}).This is for the ecliptic longitudes only.
      @{i}Void-of-course ŕ@{ui} - find times when the Moon becomes @{i}void-of-course@{ui}.
        (Has no more major aspects before it changes sign).
        This option is not yet implemented.
      @{i}@{b}Ingresses@{ub}@{ui} - find times of ingresses (zodiac sign changes by objects).
        Lunar ingresses are listed separately because of their abundance.
      @{i}ŕ Phases@{ui} - find times of lunar phases.
        This option is not yet implemented.
      @{i}Eclipses@{ui} - find if an eclipse occurs, and display data about it.
        This option is not yet implemented.

      Precision of event times varies, depending not only upon the accuracy
    of the ephemeris, but also on the speeds of objects being analyzed.

    @{u}Time steps@{uu}:
      @{i}@{b}Noon, Steps of Days@{ub}@{ui} - values listed in the ephemeris are for @{i}noon@{ui}.
        @{i}Time-steps@{ui} are in @{i}days@{ui}.This was an early standard.
      @{i}@{b}Midnight (standard)@{ub}@{ui} - values listed in the ephemeris are for @{i}midnight@{ui}.
        @{i}Time-steps@{ui} are in @{i}days@{ui}.This is a current standard.
      @{i}@{b}Random, Chosen Steps@{ub}@{ui} - first line of ephemeris is for @{i}midnight@{ui} unless
        ephemeris for a time interval is wanted (created by the 'Ef' button),
        in which case it is for a date/time given by the input string.
        @{i}Time-steps@{ui} are those selected by the user ('@{"Pick/Time Step" link ASENSE-PICK-STEPS}' menu).

    @{i}@{b}Output to File(s)..@{ub}@{ui} - the user is prompted for a file name at the end of
      ephemeris generation phase.The ephemeris will be saved on a given file.
        If a '@{i}Project/Overwrite?@{ui}' switch is turned @{i}off@{ui}, the user will be asked
      for permission if an already existing file is going to be overwriten.
      @{u}Relevant tooltypes@{uu}:
      - @{b}EPHE_DIR@{ub} - sets an initial save directory path for a file requester.

    @{u}Accuracy of created ephemeris@{uu}:
      @{b}Very High (.1")@{ub} - values are rounded to @{i}.1" of arc@{ui}.
      @{b}High       (1")@{ub} - values are rounded to  @{i}1" of arc@{ui}.
      @{b}Normal    (.1')@{ub} - values are rounded to @{i}.1' of arc@{ui}.
      @{b}Low        (1')@{ub} - values are rounded to  @{i}1' of arc@{ui}.
      @{b}Very Low  (.1°)@{ub} - values are rounded to @{i}.1° of arc@{ui}.

      @{b}Compact Output@{ub}  - the output is rearranged for compactness.

@endnode
///
@remark Select
/// Select                                                //f
@node ASENSE-MENUSELECT "ASense - Menus: Select"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS
@{b}@{u}Menu Select@{uu}@{ub}: Select as many items as you like.
  Only selected items will appear in the chart.

  @{"Physics" link ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS} (advanced options)
  @{"Aspects" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS} (@{b}complete theory@{ub})

  @{"Nodes" link ASENSE-SELECT-NODES} (only lunar)
  @{"Stars" link ASENSE-SELECT-STARS} (all 400 named ones)
                         
  @{"Arabic Parts" link ASENSE-SELECT-PARTS} (Fortuna only)
  @{"Angles" link ASENSE-SELECT-ANGLES} (MC, Asc, IC, Desc)

@{b}@{u}Links to other part of the manual@{uu}@{ub}:

  @{"Planets" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS"} (planets and luminaries)
  @{"Minor Planets" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS"} (asteroids and comets)

  @{"Stars" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-SELECT-STARS"} (detailed analysis of stars)
@endnode
///
/// Physics                                               //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS "ASense - Select: Physics"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@PREV ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@NEXT ASENSE-PHYSICS-CTR
@{b}@{u}Physics@{uu}@{ub}: Several things may be set here, all of them concerning the means
  of positional calculations.

  @{"Centering" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-CTR} - select the placement of the observer.
  @{"Positions" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-POS} - which set of corrections do you want.
  @{"Corrections" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-CORR} - available positional corrections.
  @{"Ecliptic" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-ECL} - precession, nutation and other cycles.
@endnode
///
///   Centering                                           //f
@node ASENSE-PHYSICS-CTR "ASense - Menus: Select Physics Centering"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS
@NEXT ASENSE-PHYSICS-POS
@{b}@{u}Centering@{uu}@{ub}: Sky, as it is viewed from the selected location.

    @{b}Topocentric@{ub} places the position of the observer at the surface of the
  Earth, as defined by the given geographic coordinates.This selection
  makes a mayor difference for the position of the Moon, and only slight
  ones for the other bodies.
    The @{b}difference is zero for bodies at zenith, and reaches maximum when
  they are on horizon@{ub}.
    @{i}Oblateness@{ui} of the Earth @{i}is@{ui} taken into account.
    @{i}This is a default@{ui}.

    @{b}Geocentric@{ub} places the observer at the center of the Earth.This has
  always been @{b}a standard observational point in astrology@{ub}.Mainly because
  of the lack of computing power available to astrologers.Until the end of
  the XX century, there were no easy ways to compute topocentric positions
  from the geocentric ones.Astrologers were satisfied with the geocentric
  coordinates because they couldn't easily calculate the topocentric ones.
  (Only the Moon shows significant difference, depending on it's altitude.)

    @{b}Heliocentric@{ub} position places the observer at the center of the Sun.
  There are no house positions here, and there is no Sun itself in the
  chart, but there is the planet Earth. Moon occupies almost the same
  place as the Earth does, and there are no Moon nodes, since they are
  meaningless here.
    @{b}This chart presents the overall picture of the solar system@{ub}.

    @{b}Barycentric@{ub} places the observer at the gravitational center of the
  solar system (i.e. the point around which everything in the solar system
  rotates, including the Sun itself).Since the bulk of the solar system's
  mass is located inside the Sun itself, this point lies within the Sun,
  some 500 Mm from it's center. (Sun has a radius of 696 Mm for those who
  don't know, and is 332,943 times more massive than the Earth, and 1,047
  times more massive than the largest planet, the Jupiter.)
    @{b}This chart is very similar to the heliocentric chart@{ub}.

    @{i}@{b}Selenocentric@{ub}@{ui} is a view from the center of the Moon. This view is not
  available yet, but may be added in the future, since it might make some
  sense to do so.
    @{b}This chart will look very similar to the geocentric one, except that
  instead of the Moon, the Earth will be in the chart@{ub}.
    Since the Moon is tidally locked to it, the Earth always stands still
  on the same place above the lunar horizon.Therefore it's house position
  will always remain the same during time, and will vary only with the
  change of the selenographic coordinates.
    @{i}This option is not yet implemented@{ui}.

    @{i}Planetary nodes@{ui} may be added in the future versions of ASense, and if
  they do, they will be attributed to heliocentric and barycentric charts
  only.They are meaningless for other available centers, since the planets
  revolve around the Sun, and thus the only perspectives that make sense
  for them are heliocentric and barycentric ones.For the same reason, the
  lunar nodes are meaningful only for geocentric and topocentric charts.
@endnode
///
///   Positions                                           //f
@node ASENSE-PHYSICS-POS "ASense - Menus: Select Physics Positions"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS
@PREV ASENSE-PHYSICS-CTR
@NEXT ASENSE-PHYSICS-CORR
@{b}@{u}Type of positions@{uu}@{ub}: These options define which set of @{"corrections" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-CORR} for the
  planetary positions is being used.

    @{b}Apparent@{ub} positions include @{i}all@{ui} corrections (@{i}light-time@{ui}, @{i}grav. defl@{ui}. and
  @{i}aberration@{ui}) and, optionally, the @{i}refraction@{ui}.
    This is the position of the body as viewed from the observer's position.
    @{i}This is a default@{ui}.

    @{b}Astrometric@{ub} positions include only @{i}light-time correction@{ui}.They are used
  in star catalogs to describe their mean positions, without the shifts of
  parallax, aberration and gravity deflection.

    @{b}True@{ub} positions are those without any correction at all, as defined by
  the laws of celestial mechanics.

    @{b}Virtual@{ub} positions are any other available set of corrections that has not
  already been defined above.
    Their usage is only for the software testing purposes.
@endnode
///
///   Corrections                                         //f
@node ASENSE-PHYSICS-CORR "ASense - Menus: Select Physics Corrections"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS
@PREV ASENSE-PHYSICS-POS
@NEXT ASENSE-PHYSICS-ECL
@{b}@{u}Corrections@{uu}@{ub}: They are used for a transformation from @{i}true@{ui} to @{i}apparent@{ui} planetary
  positions.

    @{b}Light-time correction@{ub}: Since the speed of light is finite, there is some
  time before the light from a distant place reaches us. If an erruption
  happens on the Sun, 8 min and 20 secs has to pass before the light of that
  event comes to Earth. Before that happens, it is like nothing has happened
  at all. News must reach us before they can affect us.
    When applied, @{b}this correction presents the bodies where they were some
  time in the past@{ub}. For Moon, this time is ~1 sec, for Pluto more than 6 h.
    This option is ON by default.

    @{b}Gravity deflection@{ub}: gravity bends the space, and the light upon it's path
  follows the curve of it. The only object in the solar system that is massive
  enough to significantly bend the light is the Sun itself.
    When applied, @{b}this correction slightly shifts the position of the planets
  @{i}away@{ui} from the Sun@{ub}. (Light bends @{i}toward@{ui} the Sun, so the one that reaches us
  came from the place that is further away from the Sun.)
    This option is ON by default.

    @{b}Aberration@{ub}: (@{i}The raindrops effect@{ui}.) Those who walk on the rain (without
  an umbrella) will get more wetness on their front, and less on their back,
  since they tend to hit the raindrops that are located in front of them.
  The effect is greater if the speed of their movement is greater.
    Similar situation occurs with light (which has a finite speed). We tend to
  observe more stars in the direction of the Earth's movement.
    When applied, @{b}aberration tends to shift the planetary positions to the
  point 90° backward from the Sun in the zodiac@{ub}, since this is the direction
  that we are moving to, while revolving around the Sun. This is called the
  @{i}annual@{ui} (or @{i}stellar@{ui}) @{i}aberration@{ui}.
    (@{i}Planetary aberration@{ui} is actually a stellar aberration coupled with the
  light-time correction and is just another term. Light-time correction is
  applied to stellar positions by default, because the accurate distances of
  stars are not known unless they are a nearby ones.Therefore a distinction.)
    A @{i}diurnal aberration@{ui} (i.e. one caused by the rotation of the Earth itself)
  is also taken into account.
    This option is ON by default.

    @{i}@{b}Refraction@{ub}@{ui} is the bending of the light in the atmosphere. In thick, but
  transparent fluids like air and water, light moves slower than in vacuum,
  so when the body is observed through some of these fluids, it's apparent
  position will appear shifted. (A spoon in a glass of water looks dented
  at the surface of the water due to this effect.)
    @{b}Refraction is not defined below the horizon@{ub}.
    @{b}The refraction tends to shift the positions of planets toward the
  zenith@{ub}, since the air is less thick in that direction.@{b}The shifting is@{ub}
  the greatest on the horizon and is experimentally determined to be some
  @{b}34 arc mins on the horizon, the value falling sharply with altitude@{ub}.
    The visible diameter of the Sun in the sky is about 30 arc secs, so
  this means that @{i}when the Sun touches the horizon during the sunsets,
  it is already gone, and located below the horizon in the sixth house@{ui}.
  We only observe it's refracted image.
    (This is only true for those who are observing the sky from a flat area
  (plains or sea), and have their horizon located ~90° from the zenith.)
    Refraction is not useful for the astrology, but is very needed for sky
  watching, so if you wish to observe the sky, this option might help you.
    This option is OFF by default.
@endnode
///
///   Ecliptic                                            //f
@node ASENSE-PHYSICS-ECL "ASense - Menus: Select Physics Ecliptic"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS
@PREV ASENSE-PHYSICS-CORR
@NEXT ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS

    @{i}@{b}Precession@{ub}@{ui}: The backward movement of the ecliptic at the rate of approx.
  @{b}50 arc secs / yr@{ub}, as compared to background stars.This yields some @{b}26,000
  years@{ub} for a full circle. Accurate value of the rate of precession is not
  a constant value.This is one of 2 main effects (the other one is nutation)
  that make a difference between the sidereal and the tropical zodiacs.

    @{i}@{b}Nutation@{ub}@{ui}: Periodic tilt of the ecliptic from it's pole. It has a period
  of some @{b}20 years@{ub} and a @{b}maximum tilt of about 20 arc secs@{ub}. Accurate value
  vary with time.Nutation affects both latitudinal and longitudinal positions.
    This is one of two main effects (the other one is precession) that make a
  difference between the sidereal and the tropical zodiacs.
    This effect also makes a difference between a @{i}mean@{ui} ecliptic obliquity and
  a @{i}true@{ui} one (coupled with the nutation).

    @{b}Obliquity cycle@{ub}: Mean ecliptic obliquity is not a constant value either.
  It vacillates slowly with time, making a full cycle in @{b}41,000 years@{ub}, with
  an amplitude of @{b}±2°@{ub}.Currently, it is in the middle of a downswinging part
  of a cycle.This cycle is caused by the long term movement of planets and
  has a direct impact on seasons.@{i}Currently, it enlarges the temperate zones
  on both sides (tropicward and poleward) for about 1'/cty (14.4 m/yr)@{ui}.

    @{b}Polar drift@{ub}: 2 orders of magnitude smaller than the previous one.About
  @{b}0.3''/cty toward ~80°W@{ub}.This movement is caused by mass rearrangements in
  the Earth's crust due to tectonic activities.

    @{b}Rotation of the perihel@{ub}: @{b}21,000 years@{ub} long cycle.It affects the climate
  in a long term, in combination with other cycles mentioned here.Currently,
  the @{b}Earth is closest to the Sun around 4th Jan@{ub}, which makes the northern
  winters warmer and summers cooler.On south half of the globe, the effects
  are reversed.However, southern side of the Earth has more oceans than the
  northern and they act as a heat buffer, cooling the summer, and warming
  the winter.Nevertheless, the Australia is still being fried every summer.
    @{i}This cycle changes the time of the year when the Sun is closest/furthest@{ui}.

    @{b}Eccentricity cycle@{ub}: The Earth's orbit is almost, but not quite, circular.
  Eccentricity is a measure of how elliptic an orbit is.This value is zero
  for a perfect circle, and equal to one for a straight line.Earth has an
  eccentricity of @{i}0.0167@{ui}, which means that it is 3.3% closer to the Sun in
  perihel, than in aphel.Eccentricity slowly varies during a @{b}near 100,000
  years@{ub} long cycle, modulating the effects of a rotation of a perihel on a
  climate.The interference between these cycles occasionally causes the ice
  ages to appear.
    @{i}This cycle changes the duration of time that the Sun spends in each sign
  of the zodiac@{ui}.

    @{b}Inclination cycle@{ub}: The inclination of the Earth's orbit vacillates with
  a period of @{b}100,000 years@{ub}.@{i}This movement appears to us as a shifting of a
  ecliptic@{ui} (and the zodiac, which is attached to it) @{i}up and down through
  the constellations@{ui}.

    @{b}Chandler's wobble@{ub}: Oscillating movement of the Earth's crust around the
  rotational axis.This is an extremely small movement which seems slightly
  irregular since it is a superposition of @{b}two periods: one of 14 months, and
  the other with about 6.5 yr duration of a cycle@{ub}.@{i}Moreover, the amplitudes of
  these spiral ellastic deformations occasionally become too large and turn
  themselves into plastic ones (i.e. irreversible).The axis of Earth's rotation
  then shifts away for an inch or two, unpredictably@{ui}.
    Average drift values of this movement are only about 6 inches / yr.In arc
  secs this is about 0.00493"/yr, or @{b}0.493"/cty@{ub}.Very small, indeed.
    @{i}@{b}This movement is ignored by the ASense@{ub}@{ui} because of it's irregularity and
  unpredictability on a longer run, and because of it's negligible amplitude.

  NOTE: @{i}Sidereal astrologers should be aware that all of these cycles should
  be acknowledged in order to make an accurate transformation from a current
  to a chosen fixed ecliptic.The traditional method takes only precession
  in the account and neglects the other movements, sacrificing the accuracy
  for the sake of simplicity@{ui}.There is no need for such compromise in ASense.
  Just select '@{i}Choose/Sidereal Mode/Accurate@{ui}' to enable all transformations.
@endnode
///
/// Aspects                                               //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS "ASense - Select: Aspects"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@PREV ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@NEXT ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-I
@{b}@{u}Aspects@{uu}@{ub}: A way on which bodies in a chart interact between themselves.
    Aspects are a third most important part of a horoscope after planets
  and houses.They are actually @{i}@{b}angles@{ub}@{ui} that bodies form between themselves.
  @{i}Only particular angles are important, namely those that are a division
  of a full circle by an integer (180°, 120°, 90°, 72°, 60°,...) and their
  multiplications (144°, 135°,...)@{ui}.
    Different angles also have different *@{b}qualitative@{ub}* attributes, and
  although these attributes are quite well researched and determined,
  so far there was no explanation of the mechanism of their work.

    @{i}@{b}This manual attempts to resolve this issue as well, and to explain
  (or at least to offer some plausible explanation) not only how, but
  also *why* the aspects work the way as they do@{ub}@{ui}. So please read on.

  @{u}Chapters@{uu}:
    1. @{"Ptolemaic aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-I} (origins of mayor aspects)
    2. @{"Kepler and Morin" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-II} (origins of minor aspects)
    3. @{"Harmonics" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-HARMONICS} (full set of minor aspects, open questions)
*   4. @{"Properties of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PROPERTIES} (description of various aspect types)
*   5. @{"Parallels and parans" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PAR} (description of some special aspect types)
*   6. @{"Patterns of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PATTERNS} (definitions and descriptions)
    7. @{"Courses of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COURSES} (@{i}@{b}applying@{ub}@{ui}/@{i}@{b}separating@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}sinister@{ub}@{ui}/@{i}@{b}dexter@{ub}@{ui})
*   8. @{"Computation of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COMPUTATION} (@{i}@{b}orbs@{ub}@{ui} and their handling)
*   9. @{"Precision of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PRECISION} (details about drawing of aspects)
*  10. @{"Special aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-QUASICON} (handling of @{"quasiconjuctions" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PROPERTIES}, @{i}parallels@{ui} and @{i}parans@{ui})

** 11. @{"Quantum link" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-QUANTUM-LINK} (mystery unveiled)
   12. @{"Colors of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COLOR} (default colors selection notes)

     @{i}Chapters marked with asterisk ('*') contain some previously unknown
   things.They are introduced here for the very first time@{ui}.
     @{i}@{b}Chapter marked with double asterisk ('**') contains a revolutionary
   new hypothesis about the nature of aspects's mechanism of functioning@{ub}@{ui}.
   It has been proposed by the author of this software.
@endnode
///
///   Ptolemy                                             //f
@node ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-I "ASense - Aspects: Origins of mayor aspects."
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@NEXT ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-II

    At the beginning of astrology, people observing the sky noticed that
  when ecliptic planetary positions form a certain angles between them,
  they seem to interact in a certain way, depending on the angle's type.
  Set of angles that has been used in ancient Greece, as described by
  Ptolemy, was:

  -   0° (@{i}@{b}Conjuction@{ub}@{ui}, division of circle by 1),
  - 180° (@{i}@{b}Opposition@{ub}@{ui}, division of circle by 2),
  - 120° (@{i}@{b}Trine@{ub}@{ui},      division of circle by 3),
  -  90° (@{i}@{b}Square@{ub}@{ui},     division of circle by 4), and
  -  60° (@{i}@{b}Sextile@{ub}@{ui},    division of circle by 6).

  These aspects are known as @{b}Ptolemaic@{ub} set of aspects, or simply the @{i}@{b}mayor
  aspects@{ub}@{ui}.

    One may notice that they all are derived from a division of a circle
  by an integer number, and also that a @{b}division by 5 is missing from a
  set@{ub}.To explain that, we must remember that astrology uses a division
  of the zodiac on 12 signs, each measuring a 30° span.So, it is easy to
  spot those angles that are multiplications of a number 30, but quite
  harder with the others (16° @{i}Psc@{ui} - 16° @{i}Tau@{ui} (60°) is easier to spot than
  14° @{i}Lib@{ui} - 26° @{i}Sgr@{ui} (72°)).

    One must also note that a decimal numbering system hasn't yet been
  discovered, so Ptolemy had had to do his math using only plain geometry
  and *roman* numbers.Quite a mess, so anything complicated was left out.

    Ptolemy did make quite an effort to explain everything that he knew
  about the art of astrology in his mayor work '@{i}Tetrabiblos@{ui}', but his
  thoughts were heavily influenced by the limitations of the society
  that he lived on and the poor level of science in general during the
  ancient times.Namely, he has used terms like '@{i}moisture and feminine@{ui}'
  and '@{i}dry and masculine@{ui}' a lot to describe the heavens.For example, he
  classifies sextiles and trines as harmonious because they join signs
  that are either both male or both female.A square is inharmonious
  because it joins the signs "@{i}of different natures and sexes@{ui}".

    With the limited knowledge at his command, he was in a certain way a
  precursor of Freud, because he tried to explain everything in a terms
  of sex.Perhaps this style of writing was more appealing to the people
  of his time?

    Nevertheless, although cyclic planetary movements have nothing to do
  with the sexual terms that he used in his attempt to explain them, the
  contributions and philosophy of Ptolemy have been a beacon through the
  ages, while his work as a compiler has saved to us much knowledge that
  might otherwise have been lost.
@endnode
///
///   Kepler and Morin                                    //f
@node ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-II "ASense - Aspects: Origins of minor aspects."
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@PREV ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-I
@NEXT ASENSE-ASPECTS-HARMONICS

    On a previous page it was mentioned that aspects deduced from a
  division of a circle by 5 were not included in a set of mayor aspects
  due to the poor math tools on Ptolemy's disposal.It was not mentioned
  there, but it should be noted here that these aspects show rather
  milder effects than the others mentioned before.This may have been
  one more reason for their rejection if Ptolemy had ever considered
  them.

    Nevertheless, time has passed, and eventually one person with enough
  skills to do something about it came to conclusion that something was
  missing.It was @{b}Johannes Kepler@{ub} (1571 - 1630), a famous astronomer and
  physicist, who also discovered that the planets are moving in elliptical
  orbits and gave us 3 laws to describe such movement.That was a tremendous
  boost for astronomy, but also for astrology.Being an astrologer himself,
  Kepler extended the set of aspects by including some of the missing ones:

  -  72° (@{i}@{b}Quintile@{ub}@{ui},       division of circle by 5),
  - 144° (@{i}@{b}Biquintile@{ub}@{ui},     division of circle by 5), and also
  -  36° (@{i}@{b}Decile@{ub}@{ui},         division of circle by 10).

    These became known as @{i}@{b}minor aspects@{ub}@{ui}.

    Few decades later @{b}Jean Baptiste Morin@{ub} (@{i}@{b}Morin de Villefranche@{ub}@{ui}), also
  known by his invention of the @{"Morinus" link ASENSE-HS-MORINUS} house system, extended the set
  of minor aspects by including:

  -  30° (@{i}@{b}Semisextile@{ub}@{ui},    division of circle by 12), and
  - 150° (@{i}@{b}Quincunx@{ub}@{ui},       division of circle by 12).

  These two have also been considered by Ptolemy, who dismissed them as
  '@{i}inconjuncts@{ui}'.'@{i}@{b}Inconjunction@{ub}@{ui}' became a common name for quincunx, but not
  for the latter one. The former one should be better called '@{i}@{b}Cunx@{ub}@{ui}' (12th),
  as the word sounds like '@{i}skunks@{ui}', which is what these aspects really @{"are" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PROPERTIES}.

    Later 2 more aspects were added (by unknown astrologer):

  -  45° (@{i}@{b}Semisquare@{ub}@{ui},     division of circle by 8), and
  - 135° (@{i}@{b}Sesquiquadrate@{ub}@{ui}, division of circle by 8).

  They could have been called '@{i}@{b}Octile@{ub}@{ui}' and '@{i}@{b}Trioctile@{ub}@{ui}', but instead they
  got their names from the fact that their qualitative meaning is similar
  to that of the square, only milder. ('@{i}Quadrate@{ui}' is latin for '@{i}square@{ui}'.)
  '@{i}Sesqui@{ui}' is latin for '@{i}one and a half@{ui}'.
@endnode
///
///   Harmonics                                           //f
@node ASENSE-ASPECTS-HARMONICS "ASense - Aspects: Harmonics"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@PREV ASENSE-ASPECTS-ORIGINS-II
@NEXT ASENSE-ASPECTS-PROPERTIES
@{b}@{u}Harmonics@{uu}@{ub}: A hypothesis that any division of a circle by an integer is
  meaningful.

    Recently, astrologers begun to abandon the traditional division on
  @{i}mayor@{ui} and @{i}minor@{ui} aspects in favour of the full set of '@{i}@{b}harmonic@{ub}@{ui}' aspects
  (at least upto the number 12).Thus the following aspects were added:

  -  51°25'42.86'' (@{i}@{b}Septile@{ub}@{ui},        division of circle by 7),
  - 102°51'25.71'' (@{i}@{b}Biseptile@{ub}@{ui},      division of circle by 7),
  - 154°17'08.57'' (@{i}@{b}Triseptile@{ub}@{ui},     division of circle by 7),
  -  40°           (@{i}@{b}Nonile@{ub}@{ui},         division of circle by 9),
  -  80°           (@{i}@{b}Binonile@{ub}@{ui},       division of circle by 9),
  - 160°           (@{i}@{b}Quadrinonile@{ub}@{ui},   division of circle by 9),
  - 108°           (@{i}@{b}Tridecile@{ub}@{ui},      division of circle by 10),
  -  32°43'38.18'' (@{i}@{b}Undecile@{ub}@{ui},       division of circle by 11),
  -  65°27'16.36'' (@{i}@{b}Biundecile@{ub}@{ui},     division of circle by 11),
  -  98°10'54.55'' (@{i}@{b}Triundecile@{ub}@{ui},    division of circle by 11),
  - 130°54'32.73'' (@{i}@{b}Quadriundecile@{ub}@{ui}, division of circle by 11), and
  - 163°38'10.91'' (@{i}@{b}Quintundecile@{ub}@{ui},  division of circle by 11).

  '@{i}Nonile@{ui}' is also called '@{i}@{b}Novile@{ub}@{ui}'.

    In practice, however, 11th serie is almost never used, thus it is still
  unclear if it has any distinguishable meaning at all.

    A term '@{i}@{b}harmonic@{ub}@{ui}' comes from a theory of sounds and other vibrational
  movements (aka waves).We may have one fundamental frequency (say 500 Hz),
  and than many harmonics that are basically a multiplications of a basic
  frequency by an integer (1000 Hz, 1500 Hz,...).All these tones are in
  phase with each other, and thus they sound harmonious to our ears.
  This is where the term comes from.

    Moreover, a fundamental frequency has a largest pitch because it is
  augmented by all of it's higher harmonics.Wave summation yields to this,
  and it is a property of such waveforms.They resonate with each other.

    Hence, this hypothesis offers an explanation on why all of the aspects
  of a same serie have similar meanings to each other.It also explains why
  2nd, 4th and 8th series all seem to have @{i}similar@{ui} meanings, only gradually
  @{i}milder@{ui} in order of appearance.

    @{u}It doesn't, however, answer any of the following questions, which still@{uu}
  @{u}remain open@{uu}:

  1. @{i}What is it that oscillates in the first place to produce some sort
     of waves that can later interact as harmonics@{ui} ?
  2. @{i}Why only divisions of a circle by an integer are acceptable@{ui} ?
  3. @{i}Why is there a *@{b}qualitatively@{ub}* different delineation of dissimilar
     serie@{ui}s ?
  4. @{i}Why is the 11th serie so much undetectable, whilst the 12th isn't@{ui} ?
  5. @{i}Why is the meaning of the 12th serie conflicting with the meaning of
     it's lower frequency harmonics (3rd and 6th serie)@{ui} ?
  6. @{i}With an endless amount of harmonics, all amplitude sums would
     eventually reach eternity.Thus, there must be a finite number of
     harmonics, because amplitudes of aspects are not infinite.
     What is this number and why that one and not some other one@{ui} ?
  7. @{i}There is an inexplicable difference between the meanings of 2
     aspects in a 5th serie, although similarities do exist.
     What causes these differences@{ui} ?

    @{i}@{b}A plausible explanation that offers @{"answers" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-ANSWERS} to these questions will
  be offered later in the text, but first we must describe the @{"properties" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PROPERTIES}
  of various types of aspects@{ub}@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   courses                                             //f
@node ASENSE-ASPECTS-COURSES "ASense - Aspects: Courses"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@PREV ASENSE-ASPECTS-PATTERNS
@NEXT ASENSE-ASPECTS-COMPUTATION
@{b}@{u}Courses of the aspects@{uu}@{ub}: Influence of the movement of aspecting bodies.
  If the bodies are not in an exact aspect (they almost never are),
  then their speed and course of movement modifies the meaning and
  delineation of an aspect which they form.There are two possible
  distinctions that can be associated with the movement of bodies.

  @{b}@{u}Precision (distinction 1)@{uu}@{ub}:
  1. @{b}Applying aspects@{ub} - their precision @{i}increases@{ui} with time.
  2. @{b}Separating aspects@{ub} - their precision @{i}decreases@{ui} with time.
    @{i}@{b}Separating aspects seem to have narrower orbs than the applying ones@{ub}@{ui}.
    Their strength rapidly depletes.Good analogy of this effect is
    @{b}uphill and downhill movement@{ub}.The latter is obviously easier.

  @{b}@{u}Direction of movement (distinction 2)@{uu}@{ub}:
  1. @{b}Ingoing (sinister) aspects@{ub} - two bodies are moving toward a @{i}conjunctiom@{ui}
  2. @{b}Outgoing (dexter) aspects@{ub} - two bodies are moving toward an @{i}opposition@{ui}
    @{i}@{b}Dexter aspects seem to be more psychologically complicated@{ub}@{ui}.In a
    case of square they act destructively, whilst the sinister squares
    have more constructive power within themself.Good analogy is @{b}a flow
    of fluids@{ub}.It can be @{b}laminar@{ub} (@{i}slow@{ui}, @{i}ordered@{ui} and @{i}peaceful@{ui} like an
    ingoing aspect), @{b}or turbulent@{ub} (@{i}fast, chaotic, with whirlpools@{ui} like
    an outgoing aspect).
@endnode
///
///   computation (orbs handling)                         //f
@node ASENSE-ASPECTS-COMPUTATION "ASense - Aspects: Computation of aspects"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@PREV ASENSE-ASPECTS-COURSES
@NEXT ASENSE-ORBS-FORMULA
@{b}@{u}There are several orbs related problems to handle@{uu}@{ub}:
* @{"1." link ASENSE-ORBS-FORMULA} @{b}How to introduce thousands of stars and asteroids@{ub} without
      significantly altering a chart or making an unreadable mess ?
* @{"2." link ASENSE-ORBS-OF-ASPECTS} How to acknowledge the difference in strength between @{b}harmonics@{ub} ?
* @{"3." link ASENSE-ORBS-OVERLAPPING} @{b}Overlapping@{ub} of orbs of aspects should be prevented.
* @{"4." link ASENSE-ORBS-APP-SEP} Difference between @{i}@{b}applying@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}separating@{ub}@{ui} aspects.
* @{"5." link ASENSE-ORBS-RANDOM} Finding an analytical way to calculate a @{i}precise@{ui} planetary
      @{b}orb of a randomly selected body@{ub}, of a part or of an asteroid
      for example.(@{u}How to define the @{b}orb@{ub}(@{i}body@{ui}) function.@{uu})

* 6. @{"Orbs of the stars" link ASENSE-ORBS-STARS} (@{i}@{b}essay@{ub}@{ui}) - a tricky thing they are, indeed.

  Follow the links above to see how the ASense tackles these issues.

   @{i}Chapters marked with asterisk ('*') contain some previously unknown
 things.They are introduced here for the very first time@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   precision                                           //f
@node ASENSE-ASPECTS-PRECISION "ASense - Aspects: Precision"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@PREV ASENSE-ASPECTS-COMPUTATION
@NEXT ASENSE-ASPECTS-QUASICON
@{b}@{u}Precision of aspects@{uu}@{ub}: Gradation to several precisions instead of just ON/OFF.
    Aspects are usually denoted with just being ON or OFF.Sometimes they
  are drawn, but I have never seen a software that indicates their precision
  in a visually pleasing way.Well, that is going to change.@{i}The ASense puts an
  emphasize on qualitative presentation of obtained data in a visual form@{ui}.
    Precision of an aspects is denoted by the @{i}@{b}thickness@{ub}@{ui} of the line that
  connects the aspecting bodies.A general rule is: @{b}the more paint, the more
  importance@{ub}.
  @{u}Grades of @{"exactness" link ASENSE-ORBS-APP-SEP}@{uu}:
    1. @{i}perc_of_exactness@{ui} < @{b}50.0%@{ub}  (cos(60°) * 100.0%) - these aspects are
       dismissed as being too vague to be taken into account.
    2. @{b}50.0%@{ub} <= @{i}perc_of_exactness@{ui} <= @{b}86.60254038%@{ub}  (cos(30°) * 100.0%) - these
       aspects are marked with
       - @{b}dashed line if they are applying@{ub}, and with
       - @{b}dotted line if they are separating@{ub} (less paint - less importance).
    3. @{b}86.60254038%@{ub} < @{i}perc_of_exactness@{ui} <= @{b}98.4807753%@{ub}  (cos(10°) * 100.0%) -
       these aspects are marked with @{b}full line@{ub} and @{b}are considered to be @{i}exact@{ui}@{ub}.
    4. @{b}98.4807753%@{ub} < @{i}perc_of_exactness@{ui} <= @{b}99.95%@{ub} - these aspects are marked
       with @{b}@{i}duoble@{ui} thickness@{ub} line and @{b}are considered to be @{i}very exact@{ui}@{ub}.
    5. @{b}99.95%@{ub} < @{i}perc_of_exactness@{ui} -  the most precise aspects.They are marked
       with @{b}@{i}triple@{ui} thickness line@{ub} and @{b}are considered to be @{i}extremely exact@{ui}@{ub}.

    @{u}There is also a difference between @{"ingoing and outgoing aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COURSES}@{uu}:
    - @{b}ingoing aspects have@{ub} a @{i}laminar@{ui} flow of energy and @{b}no special marking@{ub}
    - @{b}outgoing aspects have extra dotted lines@{ub}, indicating a @{i}turbulent@{ui} flow
      of their energies.They are more complicated to handle.
@endnode
///
///   special aspects                                     //f
@node ASENSE-ASPECTS-QUASICON "ASense - Aspects: Special aspects"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS
@PREV ASENSE-ASPECTS-PRECISION
@NEXT ASENSE-ASPECTS-QUANTUM-LINK
@{b}@{u}Special aspects@{uu}@{ub}: @{"Quasiconjunctions" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PROPERTIES} (9th serie), @{"parallels and parans" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-PAR}.
    9th serie has similar properties as conjunction (1st 'serie').Hence,
  a surprisingly different approach is taken in the ASense in the handling
  of these aspects.Instead of marking them in a usual way, with lines of
  different color/pattern/thickness, @{b}9th serie aspects are marked in the
  same way as @{i}conjunctions@{ui} are: by drawing a *@{i}glyph@{ui}* of aspecting body
  above the aspected body.This glyph is @{i}of different color@{ui} of course, in
  order for the user to be able to easily distinguish between a @{i}real@{ui} body
  and a @{FG shine}ghostly@{FG text} image of a @{i}quasiconjuncting@{ui} one@{ub}.

    Since @{i}quasiconjunctions@{ui} are not marked with lines, the information held
  in @{i}thickness@{ui} and @{i}pattern@{ui} of a line have to be presented with the attributes
  that can be associated with glyphs, namely the @{i}@{b}styles@{ub}@{ui} (@{b}bold@{ub}, @{i}italic@{ui},
  @{u}underlined@{uu}, BIG/Normal/small font @{i}size@{ui}, and their combinations).
    @{u}Default styles of the quasiconjunctions are@{uu}:
      @{b}EXTREMELY EXACT@{ub} - BIG bold,   applying - normal,
      @{b}Very Exact@{ub} - Normal bold,     @{i}separating@{ui} - italic.
      Exact - Normal,               sinister (ingoing) - not underlined,
      not exact - small.            @{u}dexter (outgoing)@{uu} - underlined.

    @{i}@{b}Styles@{ub}@{ui} may (not) be changed from the @{i}Set/Styles@{ui} menu item.

    @{"Colors" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COLOR} of the aspects are setable from the @{"Set/Palette" link ASENSE-SET-PALETTE} menu item.

    Since @{b}both parans and parallels@{ub} stem from the rotation of the Earth,
  they @{b}are marked in a chart with @{i}arcs@{ui}@{ub}, instead with a strait lines.

  (NOTE: At the time of this writing, test for parans is not yet implemented,
  and parallels are marked with orange glyphs, like 9th serie (no arcs yet).)
  (NOTE 2: @{i}@{b}Deliberately, styles are not changeable at this point to allow a
  standardized output@{ub}.Whoever looks on a chart produced by ASense should be
  able to immediately spot what is what, without the trouble of checking the
  personal preferences of the astrologer who created the chart with the help
  of ASense software@{ui}.This policy may change in the future.)

@endnode
///
/// Nodes                                                 //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-NODES "ASense - Nodes"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@PREV ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@NEXT ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@{b}@{u}Nodes@{uu}@{ub}: Only lunar.
  @{b}@{u}Possible definitions@{uu}@{ub}:
  1. @{b}True nodes@{ub} are defined as a '@{i}@{b}line of intersection between the momentary
     plane of the lunar orbit and the ecliptic@{ub}@{ui}'.(@{FG shine}Implemented in the ASense@{FG text}.)
     @{b}This is a standard definition@{ub}, which makes no difference between the
     geocentric and topocentric nodes.@{b}Mean nodes@{ub} take the average values.

  2. @{b}True nodes@{ub} may be defined as a '@{i}line of intersection between the
     momentary planes of lunar and solar orbits@{ui}'.@{b}The Sun and the Earth both
     orbit around the barycenter of the solar system.Hence, the Sun is not
     actually on the ecliptic, but it has a latitude@{ub}.However, @{i}since 99.8%
     of the solar system's mass is located inside the Sun, the barycenter
     is always somewhere inside the Sun itself, close to its center.Thus,
     the latitude of the Sun is always below 1'' of arc@{ui}.This definition
     makes a few arcsecs of difference from the previous one, but it too
     makes no difference between the geocentric and topocentric nodes.
     (Not implemented in the ASense.)

  3. @{b}True nodes@{ub} may be defined as '@{i}@{b}points@{ub} of intersection between the
     momentary path of the Moon and the ecliptic@{ui}'.Since these points are
     not located in the infinity, but are actually quite close to Earth,
     this definition makes a similar difference between the geocentric and
     topocentric nodes as is between the topocentric and geocentric Moon.
     (Not implemented in the ASense.)

    Nodes are important, because when both Sun and Moon are located in
  their vicinities, an eclipse may occur.@{b}The orb of a lunar node in ASense
  is calculated upon the value of a possible offset that can still grant
  the appearance of an eclipse@{ub}.
    @{i}@{b}If the angular distance of the luminaries (both of them) from either
  of the nodes is less than 11°15', than an eclipse may occur, depending
  on their visible sizes (which depend on their distance from the Earth).
  An eclipse always occurs if both of the luminaries (Sun and Moon) are
  within 9°55' from either of the nodes@{ub}@{ui}.@{b}Arbitrarily, 1/2 of the latter
  value is taken for the orb@{ub}.Further experimentations are required to
  refine the orb values (for all bodies).Perhaps in a next version...

    Heliocentric @{FG shine}nodes of other bodies are not supported@{FG text}, because they are
  meaningless from the Earth's perspective.If a body doesn't revolve around
  the Earth, it's nodes (of any kind) are of no concern for us Earthlings.
  At least from the astrological point of view.
@endnode
///
/// Stars                                                 //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-STARS "ASense - Stars"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-NODES
@NEXT ASENSE-SELECT-PARTS
@{b}@{u}Stars@{uu}@{ub}: The background of heavens.

    Currently there are 400 available stars in ASense, distributed in groups.
  All of the named stars were included, and all stars upto 15 ly away in order
  to make the number even 400.Some of them are very faint ones, like @{i}Proxima@{ui}.
    When a group of stars is selected, stars within that group are checked for
  '@{i}prominence@{ui}'.Those found to be important will be displayed in the chart.
    The number in parentheses shows how many stars are in that particular group
  (many stars are members of several groups).

  '@{b}No Stars@{ub}' - prevents calculation of stars.

  @{b}Named (400)@{ub} - stars with @{i}proper names@{ui}, @{i}@{b}all stars currently@{ub}@{ui}.
  @{b}Bright (many)@{ub} - stars which are @{i}listed in @{"HR catalog" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-CAT 43} of bright stars@{ui}.
  @{b}Nearby (few)@{ub} - stars which are (possibly) @{i}closer than 25 pc@{ui} (81.54 ly).
  @{b}Close (rare)@{ub} - 15 stars, which are @{i}closer than 15 ly@{ui}.
  @{b}Zodiac (some)@{ub} - stars within the @{i}zodiac@{ui} (±8° wide belt around the ecliptic).
      Note that the ecliptic moves with time, and stars go in and out of this
    area rather quickly.Their own proper movement is being handled as well.
  @{b}Variable (?)@{ub} - stars with @{i}variable@{ui} light output.

  @{b}1- mag  (24)@{ub} -  @{i}first@{ui} magnitude stars and brighter (..1.50 visual mag.).
    (@{i}@{b}Sirius@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}Canopus@{ub}@{ui} are of magnitude -1, while 8 stars are of magnitude 0
  (@{i}alp Cen@{ui}, @{i}Arcturus@{ui}, @{i}Vega@{ui}, @{i}Betelgeuse@{ui}, @{i}Capella@{ui}, @{i}Rigel@{ui}, @{i}Procyon@{ui} and @{i}Achernar@{ui}).)
  @{b}2  mag  (67)@{ub} - @{i}second@{ui} magnitude stars (1.51..2.50 visual mag).
  @{b}3  mag (118)@{ub} -  @{i}third@{ui} magnitude stars (2.51..3.50 visual mag).
  @{b}4  mag (110)@{ub} - @{i}fourth@{ui} magnitude stars (3.51..4.50 visual mag).
  @{b}5  mag  (57)@{ub} -  @{i}fifth@{ui} magnitude stars (4.51..5.50 visual mag).
  @{b}6+ mag  (24)@{ub} -  @{i}sixth@{ui} magnitude stars and fainter (5.51.. visual mag).

  @{b}Messier (110)@{ub} - (messy) objects, listed in the @{"Messier" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-CAT 149} list.
    @{i}Objects from the Messier list are not yet available in the ASense@{ui}.

  @{b}Filter Mode@{ub} - @{b}include only stars that match @{i}all@{ui} selected criteria from the
    first group and also @{i}one@{ui} of the selected magnitude options@{ub}, otherwise
    include all stars that match @{i}any@{ui} selected criteria (magnitude or not)!
@endnode
///
/// Arabic parts                                          //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-PARTS "ASense - Select: Arabic Parts"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@NEXT ASENSE-SELECT-ANGLES
@{b}@{u}Arabic Parts (lots)@{uu}@{ub}: Only @{i}@{b}Fortuna@{ub}@{ui} is available.
    Arabic parts are a large collection of points, all derived in a similar
  way.For example a formula for the @{b}Part of Fortune@{ub} (@{b}PoF@{ub}) is:

    @{i}@{b}Moon@{ub}@{ui} - @{i}@{b}Sun@{ub}@{ui} + @{b}Asc@{ub} (@{i}daily@{ui} birth chart)
    @{i}@{b}Sun@{ub}@{ui} - @{i}@{b}Moon@{ub}@{ui} + @{b}Asc@{ub} (@{i}nightly@{ui} birth chart).

  Simplified, it means that the @{b}angle @{i}from@{ui} the Sun to the Moon is the same as
  the angle @{i}from@{ui} the Asc to the PoF@{ub} (reversed for the nightly birth chart):

    @{b}PoF@{ub} - @{b}Asc@{ub} = @{i}@{b}Moon@{ub}@{ui} - @{i}@{b}Sun@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{i}Part of Fortune@{ui} is marked with the @{FG shine}red cross@{FG text} in a chart, and it is @{b}a place
  where one is supposed to 'dig' to find happines and fulfillness@{ub}.

    Other parts are derived in a similar manner, usually, but not always,
  by using the @{i}Asc@{ui} in a derivation of a part.

    Strictly speaking, @{i}Arabs@{ui}, who invented this method, only used @{i}longitudes@{ui}
  in calculations, but @{b}in the ASense, a @{i}true angle@{ui} is used@{ub} (meaning that the
  @{i}@{b}latitudes@{ub}@{ui} are also being taken into acount).This gives a slight offset from
  a traditional method toward the direction of accuracy.

    The arabic parts are actually just sensitive points on the sky, reffering
  to some special activity or situation.Their meaning depends on the planets
  that are involved in their derivation.

    Being only points, @{i}@{b}they can activate only when something is occupying them@{ub}@{ui}
  (a planet, the Sun or the Moon, an angle, or perhaps an asteroid or a comet).
  Otherwise, they remain just a silent part of the skyscape.

    As for the other, not included parts, they are not included because of
  sometimes conflicting definitions, incompleteness of the list of defined
  parts, and problems that will arise if one includes a large number of them.
  Traditionaly, @{b}several hundred parts were defined@{ub}, but a complete list has
  thousands of them.@{i}There are enough material objects in a chart to explain
  almost everything, and reaching for imaginary ones to cover the rest would
  only serve to make a mess@{ui}.

    The only ones who can practically use arabic parts are @{i}psychohistorians@{ui}
  Those are the people who try to @{i}analyze a psychology of people through the
  history@{ui}.This can be done @{i}by analyzing different ways on which something
  was described by parts@{ui}.For example, the parts of @{i}@{b}Marriage@{ub}@{ui} and of @{i}@{b}Friends@{ub}@{ui}
  were defined on several ways through different times:

  o @{i}@{b}Marriage@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Desc@{ui} - @{i}Venus@{ui}                  (modern)
  o @{i}@{b}Fraudulent Marriage@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Venus@{ui} - @{i}Saturn@{ui}
  o @{i}@{b}Mother & Family@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Jupiter@{ui} - @{i}Venus@{ui}
  o @{i}@{b}Love & Marriage@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Jupiter@{ui} - @{i}Venus@{ui}
  o @{i}@{b}Love & Marriage@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Venus@{ui} - @{i}Jupiter@{ui}
  o @{i}@{b}Marriage of Women@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Saturn@{ui} - @{i}Venus@{ui}@{i}@{ui}       (with older man)
  o @{i}@{b}Marriage of Women@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Mars@{ui} - @{i}Moon@{ui}          (with young man)
  o @{i}@{b}Men's Marriage@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Venus@{ui} - @{i}Saturn@{ui}          (giving up freedom)
  o @{i}@{b}Men's Marriage@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Venus@{ui} - @{i}Sun@{ui}             (gaining up beauty)
  o @{i}@{b}Time of Marriage@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Moon@{ui} - @{i}Sun@{ui}

  o @{i}@{b}Friends@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Moon@{ui} - @{i}Venus@{ui}
  o @{i}@{b}Friends@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Mercury@{ui} - @{i}Moon@{ui}
  o @{i}@{b}Friends@{ub}@{ui} = @{i}Asc@{ui} + @{i}Moon@{ui} - @{i}Uranus@{ui}
  ..., and so on.
@endnode
///
/// Angles                                                //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-ANGLES "ASense - Select: Angles"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-PARTS
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUSELECT
@{b}@{u}Angles@{uu}@{ub} - @{i}@{b}MC@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}Asc@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}IC@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}Desc@{ub}@{ui}.

    When this menu item is selected, data about the @{i}angles@{ui} of the chart
  will be displayed.These points were already described in great details
  in the chapter about the @{"house systems" link ASENSE-DECIDE-HS}.

  @{u}Relevant links@{uu}:
  - Extended @{"definitions" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE-ANGLES} of the angles.
  - @{"Delineation" link ASENSE-HS-HOUSE-DELINEATION} of the houses.

  Note: Ecliptical longitudes of the house tips will be displayed separately
  if "@{i}@{b}Display/Header/No Houses@{ub}@{ui}' menu item is turned @{i}off@{ui}.Consequently, the user
  would have less need to use a '@{i}@{b}Select/Angles/Show Data of Angles@{ub}@{ui}' menu item...
@endnode
///
@remark Display
/// Display                                               //f
@node ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY "ASense - Menus: Display"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-HEADER
@{b}@{u}Display@{uu}@{ub}: Present what has been done in a tabular form.
    You have to select data items that you wish to be displayed.Undesired data
  may or may not be calculated.Sometimes, this may speed up the calculations.
  An exception is the '@{i}Round@{ui}' menu, which defines a desired level of precision.

  @{u}Anyway, these are the available tabular formats@{uu}:
   1. @{"Header" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-HEADER} - who, when, where, and some other derived data.
   2. @{"(Round)" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-ROUND} - define the precision of the output, no displaying here.
   3. @{"Format 1" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1} - ecl/equ coordinates and house positions.
   4. @{"Format 2" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-2} - local space coordinates and angle crossings.
   5. @{"Format 3" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-3} - constellations, cartesian coordinates, phenomena, orbs.
   6. @{"Aspects" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-ASPECTS} - sorting method, attributes, delta, angle, percentage, orbs.
   7. @{"Star Cat" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-CAT} - catalogue designations of prominent stars.
   8. @{"Star Syn" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-SYN} - stellar synonyms, other names and their english translations.
   9. @{"Stars 1+" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-1} - additional data to Format 1: @{i}rotation@{ui} and distances in ly/pc.
  10. @{"Stars 4" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-4} - colors, magnitudes, variability data.
  11  @{"Stars 5" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-5} - components, spectral types (very detailed), additional notes.
  12. @{"Stars 6" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-6} - derived data: temp., radius, luminosities, liquid water zone.

  @{i}Note@{ui}: Shortcuts given in the display menu are not yet used anywhere, but
  may be used for spreasheets output in the future (or something similar).
@endnode
///
///   Header                                              //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-HEADER "ASense - Menus: Display Header"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-ROUND
@{b}@{u}Header@{uu}@{ub}: Data from the input string and some general data.

  Switches '@{b}No Header@{ub}' and '@{b}No Houses@{ub}' prevent displaying of a header and
  (or) houses, respectively.

  @{u}Fields derived from the input string@{uu}:
  - @{b}Name@{ub}, @{b}Date@{ub}, @{b}Time@{ub}, @{b}Location's Name@{ub}, @{b}Coordinates@{ub}, @{b}Atm. Temp@{ub}.

  @{u}Other available fields@{uu}: (derived)
  - @{b}Absolute Julian Date@{ub} - date/time expressed as a single number, in a
    (standard) way that is suitable for astronomical computations.These
    dates begin and end at noon.For example, star catalogues frequently
    refer their data for the positions of stars on a date called J2000.
    This is actually 2-Jan-2000, 12:00 UT = 2451545.0 abs. julian date.

  - @{b}Sidereal Time@{ub} - value of the sidereal time derived for the chart.
    This is the measure of uniform Earth's rotation, and may be used
    (for example) to calculate the positions of house edges.

  - @{b}Delta t@{ub} - a discrepancy beetween universal time and ephemeris time.
    (Universal time is a clock time and is a measure of actual rotation
    of the Earth around it's axis.The ephemeris time is a uniform time
    used for astronomical calculations (i.e. generation of ephemeris).)
    This discrepancy is currently around 64 seconds (year 2004), and is
    unpredictable for the future (except for just a few years in advance).
    Values for ancient times are not well known either.The consequence is
    that sometimes a historicaly recorded total eclipse may not appear as
    total when calculated by the ASense.This is *not* a bug in the ASense,
    but an intrinsic inaccuracy of astronomical data for the ancient times.
    Position of the Moon is the most affected one by the errors in delta t.
    Values given for the recent centuries are very accurate ones, though.

  - @{b}Atmospheric pressure@{ub} - a value estimated from the given altitude and
    temperature data.It is used to compute refraction if this is needed.

  - @{b}True/Mean ecliptic obliquity@{ub} - angle between the equator and the ecliptic.
    This value is about 23° 45' and slowly changes over millenia, affecting
    the climate on the Earth as a consequence.The @{i}true@{ui} value includes the
    effects of @{i}nutation@{ui} on this angle (Nutation in Obliquity).

  - @{b}Nutation in Longitude/Obliquity@{ub} - @{i}@{b}Nutation is a small short term wobble
    of the polar axis.Its maximal valuĺ is about 20'' of arc, and it has a
    period of about 20 years.Two components of this motion are given@{ub}@{ui}.@{i}The
    one in obliquity makes a difference between the mean and true ecliptic
    obliquity@{ui} (angle between the equator and the ecliptic).@{i}The other one,
    in longitude, makes a difference between a mean and true precession
    rate@{ui}.Traditional @{"mode of sidereal calculations" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES} neglects the effects of
    nutation because of it's small size and complexity of involved math.
    The @{i}accurate@{ui} one (available in the ASense under @{i}Choose/Sid. Mode@{ui} menu)
    performs accurate sidereal computations, applying the nutation as well.

  - @{b}Inclination of the Lunar Orbit@{ub} - displays the angle between the path of
    the Moon and the ecliptic for the date/time of the chart.This is usually
    about 5° and changes slightly over time.It makes a difference for the
    draconic zodiac, though.
    NOTE: @{i}Traditionally, draconic positions of bodies are calculated by
    removing the rotational angle of the lunar nodes from their positions@{ui}.
    This is incorrect, because it is just one of the @{i}Euler angles@{ui} that must
    be removed (i.e. rotated back) to obtain the correct @{i}draconic positions@{ui}
    (i.e. positions within the lunar orbit).@{i}@{b}The other of the Euler's angles
    is the inclination of the lunar orbit@{ub}@{ui}, which hasn't been handled by a
    traditional method because of a complicated procedure, unsuitable for
    a quick manual computation.Small errors in the results were tolerated.
    Nevertheless, @{i}@{b}the ASense correctly handles this problem, and removes
    the inclination of the lunar orbit angle in draconic calculations@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{u}Several probably useless points@{uu}:
  - @{b}Vertex@{ub} - @{i}@{b}a projection to the ecliptic of the most western point of the
    sky@{ub}@{ui}.The opposite point is called @{i}@{b}antivertex@{ub}@{ui} (projection to the ecliptic
    of the most eastern point of the *sky*).

  - @{b}East point@{ub} - @{i}@{b}a projection to the ecliptic of the most eastern point of
    the equator@{ub}@{ui}.(Note the difference from a definition of the antivertex).
    The opposite point is called the @{i}@{b}west point@{ub}@{ui} (projection to the ecliptic
    of the most western point of the equator).
@endnode
///
///   Round                                               //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-ROUND "ASense - Menus: Display Round"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-HEADER
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1
@{b}@{u}Round to@{uu}@{ub}: Establishes the level of precision for the output.

  NOTE: @{b}These choices do not affect the levels of precision during the
  calculations, which are always set to maximum@{ub}.They are only here to
  reduce the size of the output tables by reducing the precision level
  of the output values.

  NOTE: The '@{i}No rounding@{ui}' choice @{b}exceeds the accuracy of the ephemeris@{ub}.
  (The ephemeris are accurate to the level of 0.05'' of arc for planets,
  and 0.5'' for the Moon (this was a speed compromise).More precision
  in the output is here only for the software testing purposes.)

  @{u}'@{i}Precision@{ui}' vs '@{i}accuracy@{ui}' (example)@{uu}: "@{i}The train has arrived at the
  station@{ui} @{b}precisely@{ub} @{i}at 14:17.It wasn't very@{ui} @{b}accurate@{ub} @{i}though, because
  it was twelve minutes late.@{ui}"

    Apart from the notes above, the menu choices should be self-explanatory.
@endnode
///
///   Format 1                                            //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1 "ASense - Menus: Display Format 1"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-ROUND
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-2
@{b}@{u}Format 1@{uu}@{ub}: @{i}Ecliptical@{ui} and @{i}equatorial@{ui} coordinates, @{i}house positions@{ui}.

    This table offers a standard set of coordinates, used in both astrology
  and astronomy (ecliptical and equatorial).At the end, house positions are
  given, both regular and swap houses (house positions of bodies from a chart,
  as if they were located in the other chart (@{i}a chart comparison technique@{ui})).
    @{b}There is also a choice whether an object should be marked shortly with
  a glyph, or by its full name.This choice affects all other Format tables,
  but not the aspect table, which always uses glyphs for conveniance@{ub}.

  '@{b}No Format 1@{ub}' - blocks the output of this table.

  @{u}Ecliptical coordinates (yearly path of the Sun)@{uu}:
  - @{b}Longitude@{ub} - spherical angle measured along the ecliptic.
    Zero point of the longitude coordinate is the intersection point between
    the ecliptic and the equator (a.k.a. @{i}Vernal point@{ui}, 0° Aries).The ecliptic
    is inclined to the equator about 23°45'. (This value changes over time,
    an accurate temporary value may be found in the header table.) The angles
    along the ecliptic are measured in anticlockwise direction.
  - @{b}Latitude@{ub} - spherical angle measured perpendicular to the ecliptic.
    ±90° values above and below the ecliptic are possible.
  - @{b}Distance@{ub} - spherical radius, measured from the observer to the object.
    This is a true distance to the object.For non-material objects, like
    angles of the chart, and arabic part(s), a convenient value of 1 (AU)
    is taken.The 1 AU value is used only for the computational purposes,
    and should be ignored otherwise.

  @{u}Equatorial coordinates (standard geographical coordinate system)@{uu}:
  - @{b}Right Ascension (R.A.)@{ub} - spherical angle measured along the equator.
    Zero point of the right ascension coordinate is the intersection point
    between the ecliptic and the equator (a.k.a. @{i}Vernal point@{ui}, 0° Aries).
    The equator is inclined to the ecliptic about -23°45'. (This value
    changes over time, an accurate value may be found in the header table.)
    The angles along the equator are measured in anticlockwise direction.
  - @{b}Declination@{ub} - spherical angle measured perpendicular to the equator.
    ±90° values above and below the equator are possible.
  - @{b}Distance@{ub} - spherical radius, measured from the observer to the object.
    This is a true distance to the object.For non-material objects, like
    angles of the chart, and arabic part(s), a convenient value of 1 (AU)
    is taken.The 1 AU value is used only for the computational purposes,
    and should be ignored otherwise.

  @{b}House Position@{ub} - a placement of objects within the houses of a selected
    house system.
    @{i}Example@{ui}: '1.45' means that an object is located in the first house,
    45% of house width away from the starting point of the house (almost
    in the middle of the first house).

  @{b}House Position (Swap)@{ub} - a placement of objects within the houses of a
    selected house system, calculated for a time/place combination from
    the other chart.This is a @{i}chart comparison technique.@{i}@{b}The other chart
    must be already computed for this switch to work@{ub}@{ui}.

    NOTE: @{b}Swap houses calculated for the same time (same ecliptic), but a
    different location, differ if topocentric coordinates are required@{ub}.
    This is not a bug, this is a feature.
    @{i}Example@{ui}: Set the same date in both left and right chart, but choose
    different coordinates.House positions on the left side would differ
    from the swapped house positions on the right side if topocentric
    planetary positions are wanted.This is because the observed planetary
    positions would also differ between two charts, although their dates
    are identical.The differences are small, though, even for Moon.
    @{b}To avoid this issue, a geocentric positions should be used@{ub}.

      @{b}When using a swap houses technique, both charts should be cast with
    same parameters@{ub} (same @{i}zodiac@{ui} and same @{"Select/Physics" link ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS} menu settings).
    Otherwise weird results may occur.This is not done automatically
    (except for synastry charts), which means that upon setting the
    parameters, both charts should be recalculated by the user's request
    (@{i}for example LEFT, RIGHT, and then LEFT chart again to acknowledge
    the changes in the right chart@{ui}).
@endnode
///
///   Format 2                                            //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-2 "ASense - Menus: Display Format 2"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-3
@{b}@{u}Format 2@{uu}@{ub}: @{i}Horizontal@{ui} coordinates and @{i}angle crossing times@{ui}.

  '@{b}No Format 2@{ub}' - blocks the output of this table.

  @{u}Horizontal coordinates (relating to the horizon of the place)@{uu}:
  - @{b}Azimuth@{ub} - spherical angle measured along the horizon.
    Zero point of the azimuth coordinate is the intersection point between
    the horizon and the meridian of the place on the south side of the sky.
    The angles along the horizon are measured in a @{i}@{b}clockwise@{ub}@{ui} direction.
  - @{b}Altitude@{ub} - spherical angle measured perpendicular to the horizon.
    ±90° values above and below the horizon are possible.
  - @{b}Distance@{ub} - spherical radius, measured from the observer to the object.
    This is a true distance to the object.For non-material objects, like
    angles of the chart, and arabic part(s), a convenient value of 1 (AU)
    is taken.The 1 AU value is used only for the computational purposes,
    and should be ignored otherwise.(Seek this value in the @{"Format 1" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1} menu.)

  @{b}@{u}Refracted values@{uu}@{ub}: @{i}Refraction is the bending of the light in the vertical
    direction while passing through the Earth's atmosphere due to different
    speeds of movement of light in the vacuum and in the air@{ui}. (Put a stick
    in the glass of water to observe the effect).It is @{b}zero on zenith@{ub} (+90°
    altitude), and has an @{i}@{b}empirically established maximum of about 34' of arc
    on the horizon@{ub}@{ui} (0° altitude).Refraction is @{b}not defined below the horizon@{ub}.
      Refracted planetary positions are those that can actually be observed
    by the sky watchers on the surface of the Earth.Therefore, these values
    are of use to them.Additionally, the @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} house system may use them
    to take into account the effects of the refraction on the house division,
    and is the only house system that is able to do so.
      An interesting @{b}side effect of the refraction is that at any time ~181°
    of the sky is above the horizon and visible, while only ~179° is located
    below@{ub}.This also means that @{i}@{b}@{FG shine}when the ecliptic is observed from the pole of
    the ecliptic, the refraction causes the ecliptic to be entirely visible,
    34' of arc above the horizon@{FG text}@{ub}@{ui}.In this case, every other house system except
    @{"Altitude" link ASENSE-HS-ALTITUDE} would fail, because they would be unable to compute the angles.)

  @{b}@{u}Angle crossing times@{uu}@{ub}: Refraction affects the rising and setting times, and
    has to be turned ON (@{"Select/Physics" link ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS} menu) to be taken into account.Times
    of culmination and meridian crossings differ because the planets have
    their own speeds of movement which affect the times when they reach their
    daily extreme values of altitude.Acknowledgement of these speeds makes a
    difference between the '@{b}altitude@{ub}' (@{i}static@{ui}, no speeds) and '@{b}Altitude@{ub}' house
    systems (@{i}dynamic@{ui}, with planetary speeds).(@{i}Extreme@{ui} daily altitudes of the
    objects are used in this house system for derivation of house positions.)

      All times are expressed in @{i}local mean time@{ui} (LMT) and are affected by a
    given @{i}time zone@{ui} value for the chart.

    - '@{b}NONE@{ub}' or '@{b}----@{ub}' indicate that there are @{i}@{b}no crossings@{ub}@{ui} of required type
      during the given time interval.
    - '@{b}____@{ub}' indicates that the requested information is @{i}@{b}not available@{ub}@{ui} because
      it is either @{i}@{b}impossible@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}undefined@{ub}@{ui}, or @{i}@{b}unimplemented@{ub}@{ui}.Specifically,
      - @{i}angles@{ui} cannot have angle crossings, and
      - @{i}arabic parts@{ui} have a dubious and disputed way of their calculation.
    - '@{b}????@{ub}' indicates a computational error of unspecified type.

  @{u}Extreme altitudes@{uu}: These are the altitudes of bodies during the times of
    their @{i}culmination/lowest altitude@{ui} (which is not the same as those when
    they cross the local meridian, because the bodies have their own proper
    movement as well).They are used by the @{b}Altitude HS@{ub} (a @{i}dynamic@{ui} flavour)
    for the computation of @{i}house positions@{ui}.(Refracted altitudes also take
    into account the @{i}refraction@{ui} of the Earth's atmosphere.)
      If there are no local extreme altitudes (i.e. during a required interval),
    a global one is returned.
@endnode
///
///   Format 3                                            //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-3 "ASense - Menus: Display Format 3"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-2
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-ASPECTS
@{b}@{u}Format 3@{uu}@{ub}: @{i}Constellations@{ui}, @{i}cartesian@{ui} coordinates, @{i}visibility data@{ui} and @{i}orb sizes@{ui}.

  '@{b}No Format 3@{ub}' - blocks the output of this table.

  @{b}Constellation@{ub}: There are 88 officially defined astronomical constellations
  on the sky (many ancient ones are obsolete and do not exist anymore).Their
  purpose is to allow more easier visual orientation for a sky gazer.12 of the
  constellations share their names with the 12 signs of zodiac, but apart from
  that, they mean entirely different things.@{i}@{b}Zodiac signs are equal 30° slices
  of the sky along the ecliptic, while the constellations are uneven patches
  of the heavens@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}Cartesian coordinates@{ub}: These are used internaly for the computations and
  are readily available if anyone needs them.It is a standard left-handed
  coordinate system, with the X-axis pointing to the Vernal point, and the
  Z-axis toward the north.One projection is fixed to the @{i}ecliptic@{ui}, and the
  other one to the @{i}equatorial@{ui} plane.

  IMPORTANT NOTE: @{b}@{i}Cartesian@{ui} speeds are only available if @{FG shine}helioc. astrometric
  positions with no precession nor nutation@{FG text} are wanted@{ub}.Otherwise, the speeds
  are meaningless and would therefore not be displayed.(@{i}If precessional speed
  is attributed to stars, the most distant ones would appear to move faster
  than light.Hence, precession, nutation and other @{b}local@{ub} physical effects
  have to be stripped first for the real stellar speeds to be obtained@{ui}.
  This is also true for the objects within the solar system, but on a much
  lesser scale (yet still *not* a negligible one).)

  @{u}Visibility data@{uu}:
  - @{b}Phase angle@{ub} - angle of an object's visible surface *@{b}not@{ub}* illuminated by
    the Sun (0..180°, not available for stars).

  - @{b}Phase percentage@{ub} - percentage of an object's visible surface @{i}illuminated@{ui}
    by the Sun (100..0%, not available for stars).

  - @{b}Elongation@{ub} - the real angular distance from the Sun.

  - @{b}Apparent diameter@{ub} - diameter of the object's disk from the observer's
    point of view, in arc minutes.(More than 30' for Sun and the Moon,
    less than 1' for all other objects.) Not available for stars.

  - @{b}Magnitude@{ub} - @{i}visual@{ui} magnitude of an object.
    A magnitude is a measure of object's brightness, as perceived by human
    eye.By definition, @{b}5 magnitudes == 100 times difference in luminosity@{ub}.
    @{i}@{b}5.5 magnitudes is about at the edge of visibility on a very dark sky@{ub}@{ui}.
    Available for stars under a separate menu (@{"Display/Stars 4" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-4}).

  @{b}Defined orb@{ub} - Curently defined orbs for objects.
    (Setable from the @{"Set/Orbs" link ASENSE-SET-ORBS} menu item.)
@endnode
///
///   Aspects                                             //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-ASPECTS "ASense - Menus: Display Aspects"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-3
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-CAT
@{b}@{u}Aspects@{uu}@{ub}: Table of aspects.
    An option exists for not to calculate aspects at all, and the other one
  to calculate them, but not to display the table of aspects.In the latter
  case the aspects will still be drawn in the chart.

  '@{b}No Aspects@{ub}' - blocks the output of this table.
  '@{b}No table, just draw@{ub}' - does the same, but allows drawing of aspects.

  @{b}Sorting@{ub} of the output table is possible, and several choices exist.

  @{u}The following fields are displayable@{uu}:
  1. @{b}Aspect@{ub} (@{i}bodies involved@{ui} and @{i}the aspect type@{ui}, all printed as glyphs).
     This field may not be turned off for reasons that should be obvious.

  2. @{b}Attributes@{ub} - @{"attributes" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS} of an aspect.
     '+' - @{i}applying@{ui} aspect (i.e. approaching),
     '-' - @{i}separating@{ui} aspect (i.e. going apart),
     'In' - @{i}ingoing@{ui} aspect (a.k.a. @{b}sinister@{ub}),
     'Out' - @{i}outgoing@{ui} aspect (a.k.a. @{b}dexter@{ub}).
     'EXACT' - any aspect which is @{b}more than 98.5% precise@{ub},
     'Exact' - a @{b}precision between 86.6% and 98.5%@{ub}.
     (Aspects with @{i}precision lower than 86.6%@{ui} are just ordinary ones,
       and are marked with either
     'App' (@{i}applying@{ui}) or
     'Sep' (@{i}separating@{ui}), depending on their @{"course" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COURSES}.)

  3. @{b}Delta to 100%@{ub} - the size of an arc which separates a body from extreme
     exactness of the coresponding aspect (i.e. from 100% value of exactness).
     @{i}Negative@{ui} values indicate applying aspects, and @{i}positive@{ui} a separating ones.

  4. @{b}Actual angle@{ub} - (True) angle between the aspecting bodies.
     The angles may be @{i}true@{ui} ones, or projections to some plane of reference.
     @{i}@{b}If they are true ones, it is possible (as an option) to calculate only the
     conjunctions from projections to the ecliptic.In that case, the projected
     angular difference will be preceeded with a '_' to indicate that it is not
     a true angle between bodies, but it's projection to the ecliptic instead@{ub}@{ui}.

  5. @{b}Precision@{ub} (in percentage) - precision of an aspect as defined in the
     @{"Aspects" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS} chapter of this manual.Note that it is NOT a linear value.
     Fainter aspects than the lower limit of precision will be rejected from
     the analysis.The lower limit for the precision may be changed from the
     @{"Set/Threshold of Aspects" link ASENSE-SET-THRESHOLD} menu item.

  6. @{b}Orb of aspects@{ub} is a constant value that depends only on the harmonics
     number.It is shown only to indicate the strength of various harmonics.
     The number is used to reduce the size of a @{i}planetary_orb@{ui} to a level
     which is acceptable for the aspect type's harmonic number (i.e. during
     the internal computations of the aspects).

  7. @{b}Total orb@{ub} is the result that is obtained after the multiplication of
     a @{i}planetary_orb@{ui} with the @{i}orb_of_aspect@{ui}.It is the maximal tolerable orb
     for this @{i}body - aspect type - body@{ui} combination.If the involving bodies
     are '@{i}total_orb@{ui}' apart, the precision of an aspect is equal to zero.

  8. @{b}Halfed orb@{ub} is an angular distance between the bodies when the precision
     of their aspect is equal to 50%.This is 2/3 of the @{i}total_orb@{ui} for the
     applying aspects, and 1/3 of the @{i}total_orb@{ui} for the separating ones.
     (@{b}This value should not be confused with the '@{i}Moiety@{ui}' term, which is a
     half of the @{i}planetary_orb@{ui}@{ub}.) More details about this can be found in the
     @{"Aspects" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS} chapter of this manual.
@endnode
///
///   Star Cat                                            //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-CAT "ASense - Menus: Display Star catalog Designations"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-ASPECTS
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-SYN
@{b}@{u}Star Cat.@{uu}@{ub}: Cross-catalog designations of stars.

  @{b}Proper Name@{ub} - Some of the stars on the sky have their own proper names.
    '@{i}@{b}Sirius@{ub}@{ui}' is an example of a proper name, but also a '@{i}Zubenelgenubi@{ui}' for
    example.@{b}The ASense includes *@{i}all@{ui}* stars with proper names, even the faint
    ones@{ub}, like @{i}@{b}Proxima@{ub}@{ui}.Most of the star names originate from arabic, but
    there is also a lot of stars with ancient greek, or latin names.Some
    were named by ancient egyptians, the others by medieval astronomers,
    and there are even a few, like '@{i}Navi@{ui}', with names of modern origin.

  @{b}@{u}Bayer@{uu}@{ub} - medieval atlas of visible stars (@{i}Uranometria@{ui}), published in 1603 by
    @{i}Johannes Bayer@{ui} in todays Germany.@{i}@{b}Stars within a constellation are marked
    with small greek letters in order of brightness@{ub}@{ui}.Alpha should then be the
    brightest one, beta the second, and so on.But, there were many exceptions
    to this rule, which is more often violated than it is not.Perhaps because
    the Germany is far to the north, and hence southern stars appeared fainter
    to the Bayer because they were close to the horizon.Or maybe Bayer has had
    something else in mind while ordering the stars.We will never know.
    @{i}@{b}When there were more stars than greek letters, the small latin letters were
    used, followed by the large latin letters@{ub}@{ui}.However, these are rarely used
    today and only few of the stars labeled with Latin letters remain in the
    use today.The examples are 'l Carinae' and 'G Scorpii'.
      @{b}Last large letter ever used by Bayer was 'Q'@{ub}.

  @{b}@{u}Flamsteed@{uu}@{ub} - medieval catalog of visible stars, created by @{i}John Flamsteed@{ui},
    english Royal astronomer.The Flamsteed catalog was published in 1712 as
    a successor of Bayer's catalog, and was referring to the equinox of 1725.
    @{i}@{b}This catalog improved the labeling by using the numbers to label the stars
    within a constellation instead of letters@{ub}@{ui}.Flamsteed numbers have not been
    assigned according to the brightness, but @{i}@{b}according to the position of the
    stars in right ascension, ordering from west to east@{ub}@{ui}.For example, '1 Lyrae'
    is the most western star in the constellation of Lyra.
    @{b}The catalog contained 2682 stars, and the largest number ever used by
    Flamsteed was 140 Tau@{ub}.

    Note: @{i}In 1930, when the borders of constellations were finally formalized,
    many Flamsteed stars got stranded@{ui} (30 Her in @{i}Hydra@{ui}, 49 Ser in @{i}Hercules@{ui}...).
    They are discretly forgotten, never to be used.

    @{i}Generally, first magnitude stars and few other prominent ones are commonly
  known by their proper names.Greek letters from the Bayer's catalog are then
  used until they run out, and then the Flamsteed numbers@{ui}.

  @{b}Harvard Revised@{ub} (a.k.a. @{b}Yale Bright Star Catalogue@{ub}) - In order to include yet
    more stars, @{i}@{b}ordering by constellation was finally dropped, retaining only
    the ordering by right ascension@{ub}@{ui}.Originally, this catalog was published by
    @{i}Harvard University@{ui} for the year 1900, but it is now revised for the year
    2000 and maintained by the @{i}Yale University@{ui}.It includes 9110 stars, all of
    the visible ones, and many below the threshold of visibility.For example,
    '@{i}Vega@{ui}' = '@{i}Alpha Lyrae@{ui}' = '3 @{i}Lyrae@{ui}' = 'HR 7001'.

  @{b}Variables@{ub} - Many of the stars in the sky are not stable, but vary in their
    light output for different reasons.Because of that, all of them receive
    a special designation in '@{b}General Catalog of Variable Stars@{ub}' (GCVS) if
    their variability has been confirmed, or in the '@{b}New and Suspected
    Variables@{ub}' (NSV) catalog if their variability has only been suspected.
    @{i}@{b}Labeling in the NSV is strictly by number in order of inclusion@{ub}@{ui}, but in
    the GCVS it is quite a bit more complicated...
    Remember that the last Capital Roman letter ever used by Bayer was 'Q'.
    Hence,@{i}@{b}the astronomers used 'R' for the first variable star within the
    constelation that didin't already have a name (given by Bayer).After
    they run out of Capital Roman letters, astronomers went back  to use
    double letters, beginning the sequence with 'RR', continuing with 'RS',
    'RT', ... 'RZ', then with 'SS', 'ST', ... 'SZ', 'TT', ... upto 'ZZ'.
    Finding more, they started again at the top of alphabet with 'AA',
    'AB', ... , 'AZ', then 'BB', 'BC', ... 'BZ', 'CC', ... and so on to
    'QQ', ... , 'QZ', with 'J' letter being left out to avoid confusion.
    After 334 letter combinations, the astronomers finally gave up, and
    labeled the next one they found as V335, followed by the constellation
    name and continued to use the numbers further on@{ub}@{ui}.For example, 'QZ Sgr'
    is followed by the 'V335 Sgr', 'V336 Sgr', ... and so on.

  @{b}Fundamental Katalog of Stars@{ub} (FKS) - Originally, 1435 bright stars were
    labeled as '@{i}fundamental@{ui}', because they were exceptionally typical for
    their classes, and were used as comparison exemplars for their spectra.
    Some of them were also included because their position was important
    (either because they were at constellation borders, or because they
    marked the ecliptic, or served as a pointers to some other important
    objects in the sky).Perhaps a few was also included for some other
    reasons, extreme brightness or popularity perhaps.This catalog was
    later extended to include more than 3000 fainter stars.

  @{b}Hipparchos@{ub} (HIP) - Hipparchos satellite was flown by ESA in 1990s in order
    to measure accurately distances to stars by measuring their parallaxes.
    Over 100,000 stars were listed.For example, Vega is HIP (or HIC) 91262.

  @{b}Henry Draper Memorial Catalogue@{ub} (HD) - This is one of the most commonly
    used catalogs of fainter stars.It was created to list the spectral
    classes of stars and it lists over 300,000 stars down to roughly 10th
    magnitude, ordered by their right ascension for the year 1900.
    This catalog was compiled by @{i}Annie J. Cannon et al.@{ui} at Harvard during the
    1911 - 1915 period, and published as a successor of a @{i}Durchmusterung@{ui} (DM)
    catalog under the name of "@{b}Henry Draper Catalogue of Stellar Spectra@{ub}".
    Originally, the catalog contained 225,300 stars, but more stars were
    added later in the "@{i}@{b}Extension of the Henry Draper Catalog@{ub}@{ui}" (HDE), which
    was published from 1918 to 1924.

    The stars in this catalog are guaranteed to have their spectrum measured.

  @{b}Durchmusterung@{ub} (DM) - This is the most famed catalog of fainter stars.
    @{u}It consists of 3 parts@{uu}: ('@{i}Durchmusterung@{ui}' == '@{i}Survey@{ui}' (German))
    1. @{i}@{b}Bonner Durchmusterung@{ub}@{ui} (BD) (@{i}Bonn@{ui}, Germany) - was compiled during
       the 1859 - 1862 period by @{i}F.W.A. Argelander@{ui}, a german astronomer.
       (F.W.A. Argelander was also the author of GCVS catalog of stars.)
       The catalog lists 324,188 stars to about 9.5 magnitude that are
       northern of the -22° declination.@{b}It divides the sky into 1 degree
       declination strips and then serially numbers the stars within the
       strip from west to east (by right ascension)@{ub}.For example, Vega has
       a 'BD+38° 3238' designation, which means that it is 3238 star in
       this catalog between the 38° and 39° of northern declination.
       The equinox for which it referred to, was the one from the 1855.
       @{b}Later southward extension@{ub} has included another 133,650 stars
       within the -2°...+23° of declination (BDE).
    2. @{i}@{b}Cordoba Durchmusterung@{ub}@{ui} (CD) (@{i}Cordoba@{ui}, Argentina) - covers the
       -23° ... -52° declination strips, which were left out from BD.
       It contains 613,953 southern stars, making the total count of
       the DM catalog to 1,071,800 stars.It was compiled by @{i}Thome@{ui} in
       1892 - 1932 period.The catalog is complete to 9.2 magnitude,
       and practically complete to 9.5 mag. in or near the Galaxy.
    3. @{i}@{b}Cape Photographic Durchmusterung@{ub}@{ui} (CP) (@{i}Cape Town@{ui}, South Africa) -
       this catalog was compiled by @{i}Gill & Kapteyn@{ui} in 1895 - 1900 period
       with the use of photographic plates (not visual).The catalog lists
       454,875 stars within the -18°...-90° declination bands.The catalog
       is complete to 9.2 magnitude, and practically complete to 9.5 mag.,
       in or near the Galaxy.

      @{i}Precession@{ui} has moved many of the stars in Durchmusterung catalog
    away from its original declination strips by now.(The catalog was
    compiled for the year 1900.)

      DM designations are often encountered, but the magnitudes from this
    catalog are unreliable (most of them are just quick visual estimates).

  @{b}Gliese & Jahre@{ub} (GJ) - These are catalogs of @{i}nearby@{ui} stars, that
    are closer than 25 pc.They list very faint, but close stars to us.Due to
    the faintnest of the objects which should be included, the list is quite
    incomplete, since most of the nearby red and brown dwarfs are still to
    be discovered.Catalogs made by @{i}@{b}Gliese@{ub}@{ui} (Gl), @{i}@{b}Gliese & Jahre@{ub}@{ui} (GJ) and by
    @{i}@{b}Worley@{ub}@{ui} (Wo) are merged into one, and referred by a single GJ designation.

  @{b}General Catalogue of 33,342 stars@{ub} (GC) - Another formerly popular catalog.
    Fairly large, but not as big as HD or BD, it has offered a compromise
    between the size and a number of included stars.

    This catalog was compiled by @{i}Benjamin Boss@{ui} in 1937 for the year B1950.

  @{b}Aitken's Double Stars Catalog@{ub} (ADS) - An old (published in 1932) catalog
    of double stars.This is the first catalog of stars known to be doubles.

  @{b}Messier objects@{ub} (M) - @{i}Messier@{ui} was a comet hunter who made a list of
    objects which were frequently mistaken for comets (@{i}an ignore list@{ui}).
    This is a two centuries old catalog, which originally contained 103
    bright objects, but the later additions have 107, 109 or 110 objects.
    Most of the objects on the list are @{i}clusters@{ui}, @{i}galaxies@{ui} or @{i}nebulae@{ui},
    easily visible by amateur astronomers, who usually get started their
    tour of the sky by observing the objects from this list first.

@{b}@{u}Some other special (or important) catalogs, not (yet) referenced by ASense@{uu}@{ub}:

  @{b}Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Star Catalog@{ub} (SAO) - Successor of
    the GC, published in 1966 on Harvard.It includes 258,997 stars down
    to 9th mag., divided into 10° bands of declination.

  @{b}Zodiacal Catalogue@{ub} (ZC) - Catalog of stars that can be occulted by the Moon.

  @{b}General Catalog of Nebulae@{ub} (GCN) - Compiled by @{i}John Herschel@{ui} in 1864.
  @{b}New General Catalogue of Nebulae and Clusters of Stars@{ub} (NGC) - Compiled
    by @{i}John L. E. Dreyer@{ui} in 1888, as a successor of GCN.It includes 7,840
    objects of many types, referring to the equinox of 1860.The objects
    were listed in order of their right ascensions.
  @{b}Index Catalogues@{ub} (IC) - @{b}Two supplements of NGC@{ub}, published by @{i}Dreyer@{ui} in
    1895 and 1908.NGC and IC should be considered as a single work, which
    lists a total of 13,226 objects of many types.

  @{b}Hubble Space Telescope Guide Star Catalog@{ub} (GSC) - 2 CDs, never printed.
    18,819,291 objects (15,169,873 stars), 9..13 or 14 mag..The remaining
    3,649,418 objects are galaxies and other deep sky objects.The catalog
    divides the sky into 9,537 small regions for easier reference.
    Most of the objects in this catalog have never been seen, but measured
    automatically from plates.
@endnode
///
///   Star Syn                                            //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-SYN "ASense - Menus: Display Star Synonyms & Translations"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-CAT
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-1
@{b}@{u}Star Synonyms@{uu}@{ub} - other names for the stars and their translations.

   @{i} Some stars have been assigned many different names by various cultures,
  especially the prominent ones.The same name has frequently been assigned
  to different stars, erroneously or not.Many names were corrupted during
  time into many similarly pronounced/written variations@{ui}.These are given
  here.

    @{b}Most of the stars have their proper names originating from Arabs@{ub}.@{i}Their
  names are frequently a corrupted shortcut of a longer Arabic phrase@{ui}.These
  are also given here, hopefully correctly transcribed into english.

    Origin of the names (if known) were also given (@{i}Latin, Greek, Chinese@{ui}).
  If nothing is mentioned, the @{i}@{b}Arabic@{ub}@{ui} is assumed as a most common origin of
  stellar names.

    The @{b}translations@{ub} are given in order of appearance of star synonyms with
  @{i}@{b}different@{ub}@{ui} meaning.It should be easy to match them.
@endnode
///
///   Stars 1+                                            //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-1 "ASense - Menus: Display Stars 1+"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-SYN
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-4
@{b}@{u}Stars 1+@{uu}@{ub}: Rotational speeds and distances (in light years or parsecs).
    This is only an addition to @{"Format 1" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1} table.

  @{b}Rotational speed@{ub} (km/s) - some stars have had their speed of rotation
    measured.The value given here, however, is not an accurate measurement.
    Instead, it is usually a minimal one, because the inclinations of the
    stars, which are required for accurate determination of rotational
    speeds, are rarely known.The measured values are therefore only a
    limit, and not an accurate value.They are also quite imprecise,
    because @{b}stars have a differential rotation@{ub} (i.e. they do not rotate
    as a solid body, but instead have larger rotational speeds in their
    equatorial regions than on their poles).
      Apart from these considerations, it should be noted that @{b}stars of
    O, B or A spectral class rotate much faster than the remaining ones.
    Stars without planets and single stars also tend to have larger speeds
    of rotation@{ub}.(Note that @{i}@{b}only about 1% of angular momentum of the solar
    system is located within the Sun@{ub}@{ui}, and the reemaining 99% is distributed
    among the planets and the asteroids.)
      @{i}Stars of advanced age slow down their rotation when they start to grow
    in size@{ui}.Some supergiants with diameters of several astronomy units (AU)
    may take years to turn around.
      @{i}Very close doubles slow down each other over time@{ui}, synchronising their
    rotational periods.

    @{b}Distance ± error@{ub} - expressed either in light years (ly) or parsecs (pc).
      @{i}@{b}Light year@{ub}@{ui} - a distance that light travels during one year, ~9.5 Pm;
      @{i}@{b}Parsec@{ub}@{ui} - about 3.26 ly, a distance when an arcsec on the sky is equal
        to 1 AU in length.
      @{i}@{b}Parallax@{ub}@{ui} - a measure of distance in arcsecs (1 / pc).
        Due to the Earth's rotation around the Sun, the positions of stars
        (of the closer ones, anyway) appear to shift back and forth over the
        course of year, describing an ellipse.Parallaxes are a measure of that
        motion.They are reversely proportional to distances of measured objects.
          First measures of stellar parallaxes were taken in 1838 by @{i}Bessel@{ui},
        who (serendipitously) measured the close-by star system of 61 Cygni.
      Distancies in Format 1 are not given for stars because an unsuitable
      measurement unit has been used there.Instead, they are given here,
      with a proper measurement units for such large distancies being used.
@endnode
///
///   Stars 4                                             //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-4 "ASense - Menus: Display Stars 4"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-1
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-5
@{b}@{u}Stars 4@{uu}@{ub}: Magnitudes and variability data.

    Some stars have variable light output.Reasons can be very different, and
  also the magnitude of changes of magnitudes and sometimes even of spectra.

  @{"Variability types" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-STARS-VARS"} - type(s) of star's variability, if any.

  @{b}Max. magnitude@{ub} - maximal recorded visual magnitude of this @{i}@{b}star system@{ub}@{ui}.
  @{b}min. magnitude@{ub} - minimal recorded visual magnitude of this @{i}@{b}star system@{ub}@{ui}.
  @{b}Abs. magnitude@{ub} - visual magnitude of this @{i}@{b}star system@{ub}@{ui} if located 10 pc away.

  @{u}These values are important parameters in determination of spectral types@{uu}:
  @{b}U-B magnitude@{ub} - difference in magnitudes between star's UV and blue light.
  @{b}B-V magnitude@{ub} - difference in magnitudes between star's blue and visual light.
  @{b}R-I magnitude@{ub} - difference in magnitudes between star's red and infrared light.

  @{b}Visual light@{ub}: @{b}350 nm@{ub} (violet) .. @{b}780 nm@{ub} (red).
  @{b}B - @{i}blue@{ui} band@{ub}, measured through a @{b}430 nm@{ub} filter.
  @{b}V - @{i}visual@{ui} band@{ub}, measured through a @{b}530 nm@{ub} filter,

  @{i}Note@{ui}: By definition, @{i}@{b}UBV Jonhson's photometry@{ub}@{ui} is to be measured at 7000 ft.

    Magnitudes describe the total amount of light that comes from an object.
  @{b}5 magnitudes == 100 times difference in the amount of light@{ub}, which means
  that 1 manitude == 5th root from 100 == 2.512 times difference in light.
   @{i}@{b}Threshold of visibility is about 5.5 magnitudes@{ub}@{ui} on a very dark sky.This
  is just about the visual magnitude of Uranus, which is sometimes barely
  visible if one knows exactly where to look (and the sky is pitch dark).
  @{i}Smaller values of magnitudes mean higher luminosity@{ui}. The Sun has about
  -26.8 visual magnitude, while the brightest star, Sirius, has only -1.46.
    Magnitudes were invented by @{i}Hipparchos@{ui} in 2nd century BC.

  @{b}Epoch@{ub} - Time of @{i}min@{ui}. light for E/ELL/RS/RV var. types,
           and0of @{i}max@{ui}. light for others.
  @{b}Percentage@{ub} - @{i}Rising time@{ui} (of light) or @{i}duration of eclipse@{ui} (if eclipsing).
    If a '@{b}*@{ub}' is present after this value, light constancy phase at minimum
    light is equal to zero.
  @{b}Period of variability@{ub} - always assumed const., except for @{i}@{b}bet Lyr@{ub}@{ui} (Sheliak),
    and @{i}@{b}bet Per@{ub}@{ui} (Algol). These 2 star systems are involved in mass transfer
    between some of their components, which causes gradual change of periods.
@endnode
///
///   Stars 5                                             //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-5 "ASense - Menus: Display Stars 5"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-4
@NEXT ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-6
@{b}@{u}Stars 5@{uu}@{ub}: Components, spectral types (very detailed), additional notes.

  @{u}Order of components@{uu}:
    @{b}Large letters@{ub} - stars.
    @{b}small letters@{ub} - planets and brown dwarfs.
    @{b}ABCDE @{ub}- main components.
    @{b}PQR@{ub} - close companions, discovered later.

    Order of components should match with the order of stars in the spectral
  types string.

  @{u}Special notification in ASense@{uu}:
    '@{b}­@{ub}' (ASCII 173) - @{i}spectral@{ui} range (G0Ib­G3Ib).
    '@{b}-@{ub}' (ASCII  45) - @{i}magnitude@{ui} range (1.25-1.39).
    '@{b}{}@{ub}' - @{i}pair@{ui} of stars (star system), used to indicate the name of a system.
    '@{b}()@{ub}' - values refering to a @{i}single@{ui} star, usually it's magnitude, sometimes
           with a variability range.'@{b}v@{ub}' in parenthesis indicates variability
           of a coresponding factor (q(v) means variable emission from a shell).
    '@{b}··@{ub}' - very distant companion (>1,000 AU away).
     '@{b}·@{ub}' - distant companion (100..1,000 AU away).
     '@{b}+@{ub}' - companion at 1..100 AU distance.
     '@{b}*@{ub}' - close companion (orbiting at 0.1..1 AU).
    '@{b}**@{ub}' - companion in a @{i}@{b}torch orbit@{ub}@{ui} (<0.1 AU away).
     '@{b}±@{ub}' - component described separately (separation > 1' of arc)
   '@{b}37č@{ub}' - brown dwarf with 37 masses of Jupiter.
    '@{b}3č@{ub}' - gas giant with 3 masses of Jupiter.
     '@{b}?@{ub}' - unresolved companion.
   '@{b}Fe+@{ub}' - iron enhanced by unspecified amount.
    '@{b}P*@{ub}' - phosphorus greatly enhanced by unspecified amount.
     '@{b}!@{ub}' - @{b}maser@{ub} ('@{i}@{b}microwave@{ub} amplification by stimulated emission of radiation@{ui}'),
           (longer wavelengths analogous of a @{i}laser@{ui} ('@{i}@{b}light@{ub} amplification@{ui}...')).
           This indicates presence of a warm material around the star, usually
           ejected by the star itself.
           @{b}SiO!@{ub} - warm silicon dust present around the star.
           @{b}H2O!@{ub} - warm water moleculs present around the star.

    Standard notification of @{"spectral types" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-STARS-SPECTRA" 0} and @{"luminosities" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_LUM" 0} were discussed in
  the chapter of this manual devoted to @{"stars" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-SELECT-STARS" 0}.

  @{b}Additional notes@{ub}: various assortment of remarks and otherwise unclassified
    or poorly available data, like @{i}metalicity@{ui}, @{i}age@{ui}, @{i}mass@{ui} and @{i}orbital data@{ui}.
    @{i}This option is not yet implemented@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Stars 6                                             //f
@node ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-6 "ASense - Menus: Display Stars 6"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@PREV ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-5
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY
@{b}@{u}Stars 6@{uu}@{ub}: Data derived from previous tables.

  @{b}Temperature@{ub} - estimated temperature of a star, @{i}@{b}derived from B-V magnitude
    difference@{ub}@{ui} by an empiric formula.Errors in this value are reflected on
    the result. (@{i}It would be more accurate to estimate the temperatures by
    directly analizing the spectra of the stars, but it would be much more
    complicated, and also not really necessary. Therefore, the approximate
    formula was implemented@{ui}.)

  @{b}Bolometric correction@{ub} - difference (@{b}in magnitudes@{ub}) between star's total
    luminosity (in all wavelengths), and it's visual luminosity.@{i}The Sun@{ui},
    for example, @{i}emits about 17% of its light in invisible UV and infrared
    parts of the spectrum@{ui}.
      This value is @{i}@{b}derived from a temperature, which is derived from B-V
    difference of magnitudes@{ub}@{ui}.Therefore, errors in B-V are reflecxted on
    the result, even more than on temperature.However, since this isn't
    an astrologicaly important parameter, the errors are tolerable.

  @{b}Visual luminosity (relative to solar)@{ub} - star's luminosity in @{i}visual@{ui} part of
    the spectrum, expressed in @{i}visual@{ui} solar luminosities.
      This value is @{i}@{b}derived from absolute magnitude of a star, which depends
    on star's magnitude and it's distance (1/plx pc)@{ub}@{ui}.Thereupon, errors in both
    visual magnitude and parallax reflect on the accuracy of this parameter.

  @{b}Total luminosity (relative to solar)@{ub} - star's @{i}total@{ui} luminosity, expressed in
    @{i}total@{ui} solar luminosities.
      This value @{i}@{b}depends on@{ub}@{ui} star's visual magnitude and it's parallax in the
    same way as the visual luminosity does. Additionaly, it depends on B-V
    magnitude difference in the same way as the bolometric correction does,
    since both @{i}@{b}visual absolute magnitude and bolometric correction@{ub}@{ui} were used
    in derivation of star's total luminosity. Errors in these values reflect
    (heavily) on errors in this parameter.

  @{b}Distance for Earth (in AU)@{ub} - @{i}@{b}distance from the star center which receives
    the same amount of radiation as the Earth does@{ub}@{ui} (although the distribution
    of energy between different wavelengths varies from star to star).
      @{b}This value is simply a square root of a star's total luminosity@{ub}. Errors
    in star's visual magnitude, parallax and B-V magnitude difference reflect
    even more heavily on the errors of this parameter than they do on the star's
    total luminosity.The specific environmental conditions on a possible planet
    (i.e. the thickness, density and composition of the atmosphere) would also
    influence heavily on the local weather system and temperature conditions.
      @{i}This value is therefore only a very approximate one@{ui}.

  @{b}Radius (relative to solar)@{ub} - stellar radius, expressed in solar radii.
      This value is @{i}@{b}derived from a star's total luminosity and it's temperature@{ub}@{ui}.
    Thereupon, it depends on star's visual magnitude, parallax and B-V magnitude
    difference.Errors in these parameters reflect even more on a derived value
    of radius, than they do on both star's total luminosity nad it's temperature.
      @{i}This value is therefore only a very approximate one@{ui}.

  @{b}Mass (relative to solar)@{ub} - mass of a star @{i}system@{ui}, expressed in solar masses.
      @{i}Derivation of stellar masses is not yet implemented@{ui}.
@endnode
///
@remark Pick
/// Pick                                                  //f
@node ASENSE-MENUPICK "ASense - Menus: Pick"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-PICK-AREXX
@{b}@{u}Pick@{uu}@{ub}: Auxiliary decisions, lupe.

  @{"ARexx Support" link ASENSE-PICK-AREXX} - Command Shell, sequences, macros, scripts.
  - @{"Command list" link ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS} - built-in ARexx commands.
  @{"Lupe" link ASENSE-PICK-LUPE} - a magnifying window (third party auxiliary tool).
  @{"Side" link ASENSE-PICK-SIDE} - left or right.
  @{"Step Type" link ASENSE-PICK-STEPS} - Steps of time/lon/lat or alt are possible.
  @{"Step Size" link ASENSE-PICK-STEPS} - Advance by n units of...
  @{"Star Sort" link ASENSE-PICK-STAR_SORT} - Sort prominent stars by this parameter (max first).
  @{"Hover Help" link ASENSE-PICK-HELPS} - Point on an object to receive help about it.
@endnode
///
///   ARexx                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PICK-AREXX "ASense - Menus: Pick ARexx Support"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPICK
@PREV ASENSE-MENUPICK
@NEXT ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@{b}@{u}ARexx Support@{uu}@{ub} - Interface to ARexx.  @{"Command list" link ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS} - built-in ARexx commands.

    Since version v4.0, the ASense has an ARexx interface, provided by the
  help of @{i}easyrexx.library@{ui} v3.0+, copyright 1994,1995 Ketil Hunn. The full
  archive of this library together with the src is available on the Aminet.

  @{b}Command Shell@{ub} - Open a shell to receive and execute arexx commands.
    This (simple) shell is provided by the easyrexx.library.Commands
    and their arguments are NOT case sensitive.
    IMPORTANT: @{b}Commands with @{i}arguments@{ui} @{b}MUST@{ub} be enclosed with qoutation
    (') or citation (") marks in order to work@{ub}. (The entered line is
    treated as a single string and parsed as such.)
      The shell can be closed by clicking the close gadget of it's window,
    pressing the @{i}CTRL-C@{ui}, or by typing the @{b}EXIT@{ub}.Commands @{b}HIDE@{ub} and @{b}QUIT@{ub} are
    also known to be able to close the shell window... :-)

  @{b}Sequences@{ub} - there is 1 slot to record and replay commands given to ASense.
    @{b}Record@{ub} - @{i}Start@{ui} or @{i}stop@{ui} remembering calls from @{i}menus@{ui}, @{i}gadgets@{ui} and @{i}arexx@{ui}.
      When recording, the mouse pointer will have a '@{b}REC@{ub}' attached to it.
    @{b}Load..@{ub} - Load an old sequence, saved as macro.
    @{b}Save..@{ub} - Save recorded sequence as macro for later use.The sequence
      remains in memory after saving, though, and can be @{i}played@{ui} again.
    @{b}Play@{ub} - Execute the recorded sequence @{b}ONCE@{ub}.
    @{b}Play..@{ub} - Execute the recorded sequence for (given) number of times.
      This feature may be used to create animations, for example.

  @{b}Run a script..@{ub} - The given script is executed @{b}ONCE@{ub}, @{i}without being loaded
    into slot reserved for recordings@{ui}.(The script is not treated as macro.)
    Any external ARexx script may be executed, no limits.
    NOTE: There is a template available in the rexx sub-directory of ASense
    distribution ('@{i}@{b}as_rexx.template@{ub}@{ui}') to allow easy making of ARexx scripts
    related to ASense.
@endnode
///
///     Command list                                      //f
@node ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS "ASense - ARexx: Command list"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPICK
@PREV ASENSE-PICK-AREXX
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-GET
@{b}@{u}Command list@{uu}@{ub} - the built-in ARexx commands.

  @{u}Internal command (supplied by the easyrexx.library)@{uu}: @{"GET" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-GET}

  @{"I/O commands" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-IO}: @{b}LOAD SAVE DATABASE FILTER FILTERS HISTORY DEBUG ASK QUERY@{ub}

  @{"GUI handling commands" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-GUI}: @{b}HIDE LOCK UNLOCK QUIT EXIT@{ub}

  Adjustments-making commands: @{"DECIDE" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-DECIDE} @{"CHOOSE SHOW" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-CHOOSE} @{"SELECT" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-SELECT} @{"DISPLAY ROUND" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-DISPLAY}
    @{"SIDE STEPS SORT HOVER_HELP" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-PICK} @{"STRSET THRESHOLD COLOR ORB CUSTOM DEFAULT RESET" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-SET}
    (Most of these commands also change the corresponding menu's flags.)

  @{"Chart-casting commands" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-CHARTS}: @{b}CHART STAR_CHART CYCLE MERGE SYNASTRY EPHE STATS@{ub}

    @{b}/A@{ub} - always, the argument is required for the command to work.
    @{b}/S@{ub} - switch, simple Y/N argument,nothing to follow (ARG)
    @{b}/K@{ub} - keyword, argument requires a string to follow (ARG="something else")
    @{b}/N@{ub} - number, argument requires a number  to follow (ARG=123533)
    @{b}/F@{ub} - final, no more argument parsing after this one is entered.

    Note: Arguments which accept [@{b}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ub}] as @{i}@{b}options@{ub}@{ui}, also accept
      the following aliases: @{b}TRUE/FALSE/CHANGE,1/0/2@{ub}, respectively.
@endnode
///
///       GET command                                     //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-GET "ASense - ARexx: GET command"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-IO

  @{b}GET@{ub} @{i}@{b}COMMANDLIST/S/F,AUTHOR/S/F,COPYRIGHT/S/F,VERSION/S/F,LASTERROR/S/F@{ub}@{ui}

      This command is a general one, supplied to all applications which
    use easyrexx.library to manage their ARexx interface. This command
    is intended to be used from ARexx scripts. It doesn't work from the
    supplied command shell because the shell doesn't print the returns.

    @{b}COMMANDLIST@{ub} - return the templates of all built-in ARexx commands.
    @{b}AUTHOR@{ub} - return the name of the application's author.
    @{b}COPYRIGHT@{ub} - return the application's copyright string.
    @{b}VERSION@{ub} - return the application's version number.
    @{b}LASTERROR@{ub} - return the last recorded error string.
@endnode
///
///       I/O commands                                    //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-IO "ASense - ARexx: I/O commands"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-GET
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-GUI

  @{b}LOAD@{ub} @{i}@{b}INIT_CONFIG/S/F,FROM/K,ASK/S,SESSION/S/F,CONFIG/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}INIT_CONFIG@{ub} - load config from the file pointed by the tooltypes.
    @{b}DATABASE@{ub} - load an old @{"database" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DATABASE} file from a given file (FROM, ASK).
      The current database will be appended if @{i}Project/Global Databases/Append@{ui}
      menu is checked ('@{i}@{b}DATABASE APPEND=ON@{ub}@{ui}' with ARexx.) Otherwise it will be
      replaced. If no filename is given, default is to attempt loading from
      the "@{b}ASense.db@{ub}" file in @{"DATA_DIR" link ASENSE-GENERAL-TOOLTYPES} if it exists.
    @{b}SESSION@{ub} - load an old @{"history" link ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY} file from a given file (FROM, ASK).
      The existing history will be appended if @{i}Project/Sessions/Append History@{ui}
      menu is checked. ('@{i}@{b}HISTORY APPEND=ON@{ub}@{ui}' with ARexx.) Otherwise it will be
      replaced. If no filename is given, default is to attempt loading from
      the "@{b}ASense.hist@{ub}" file in @{"DATA_DIR" link ASENSE-GENERAL-TOOLTYPES} if it exists.
    @{b}CONFIG@{ub} - load config from a given file (FROM, ASK) or from the last loaded
      one. This may or may not be the initial one.
    @{b}ASK@{ub} - popup the file requester to ask for a filename.
    @{b}FROM@{ub}=(@{i}filename@{ui}) - filename with path to load from.

  @{b}SAVE@{ub} @{i}@{b}INIT_CONFIG/S/F,AS/K,ASK/S,OVERWRITE/K,REPORT/K,HTML/K,
       CHART/S/F,DATABASE/S/F,SESSION/S/F,CONFIG/S@{ub}@{ui}
    Perform various types of saving.
    @{b}INIT_CONFIG@{ub} - save config into file pointed by the tooltypes (initial
      config). The file will be overwritten.
    @{b}DATABASE@{ub} - save the database buffer into given file (AS, ASK). The file
      will be @{i}@{b}appended@{ub}@{ui} if @{i}Project/Global Databases/Append@{ui} menu is checked.
      ('@{i}@{b}DATABASE APPEND=ON@{ub}@{ui}' with ARexx.) Otherwise it will be overwritten. If no
      filename is given, default is to save into "@{b}ASense.db@{ub}" in DATA_DIR.
    @{b}SESSION@{ub} - save the history buffer into given file (AS, ASK). The file
      will be @{i}@{b}appended@{ub}@{ui} if @{i}Project/Sessions/Append History@{ui} menu is checked.
      ('@{i}@{b}HISTORY APPEND=ON@{ub}@{ui}' with ARexx.) Otherwise it will be overwritten. If no
      filename is given, default is to save into "@{b}ASense.hist@{ub}" in DATA_DIR.
    @{b}CONFIG@{ub} - save config into given file (AS, ASK) or into last loaded one.
      This may or may not be the initial one. The file will be overwritten.
    @{b}CHART@{ub} - save the drawn chart as a picture (gif file).
      @{u}Chart saving related arguments@{uu} (change menu flags):
      - @{b}OVERWRITE@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - handle overwriting.
      - @{b}REPORT@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - save the tables too.
      - @{b}HTML@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - save the chart as html.
    @{b}ASK@{ub} - popup the file requester to ask for a filename.
    @{b}AS@{ub}=(@{i}filename@{ui}) - filename with path for saving into.

  @{b}DATABASE@{ub} @{i}@{b}APPEND/K,ADD/S,ADD_LINE/K,FLUSH/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}APPEND@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - modify the action performed by the
      '@{i}SAVE DATABSE@{ui}' and '@{i}LOAD DATABASE@{ui}' commands, as explained above.
    @{b}ADD@{ub} - put the value of the input string into datatbase (side dependent).
    @{b}ADD_LINE@{ub}=(@{i}string@{ui}) - put '@{i}string@{ui}' into database (must be a valid @{"input string" link ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING}).
    @{b}FLUSH@{ub} - flush the database buffer (together with all defined filters).

  @{b}FILTER@{ub} @{i}@{b}TYPE/K/A,EXCLUDE/S,FROM/K,TO/K,STR/K,SUBSTR/K,CASE/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}Days Mons Year Cycl  Cal Time TZ GLon GLat GAlt Temp
          Name Plac Grd1 Grd2 Comm Date JD@{ui}) - set the filter type.
      This argument selects which field of data string is to be filtered.
      '@{i}Name@{ui}', '@{i}Plac@{ui}' and '@{i}Comm@{ui}' options expect a @{i}string@{ui} (STR, SUBSTR). The
      others expect a @{i}numeric@{ui} value(s) (FROM, TO); @{i}one@{ui}, @{i}none@{ui}@{i}@{ui} or @{i}both@{ui} of them.
    @{b}EXCLUDE@{ub} - exclude the matching entries, keep the others.
      If this argument is not set, the matching entries will be kept.
    @{b}FROM@{ub}=(@{i}value@{ui}) - define the @{i}lower limit@{ui} for numeric values
    @{b}TO@{ub}=(@{i}value@{ui}) - define the @{i}upper limit@{ui} for numeric values
      NOTE: Values like 'FILTER TYPE=@{i}Days@{ui} FROM=@{b}25@{ub} TO=@{b}6@{ub}', and such are allowed.
      (This command would find all entries with days 25,26,...5,6.)
    @{b}STR@{ub}=(@{i}string@{ui}) - @{i}string@{ui} to search for in the chosen field.
    @{b}SUBSTR@{ub}=(@{i}string@{ui}) - @{i}substring@{ui} to search for in the chosen field.
    @{b}CASE@{ub} - case sensitive (sub)string search.

  @{b}FILTERS@{ub} @{i}@{b}ON/S/F,OFF/S/F,TOGGLE/S,REMOVE/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{u}Menu flag changing arguments@{uu}:
      @{b}ON@{ub} - turn ON filtering.
      @{b}OFF@{ub} - turn OFF filtering.
      @{b}TOGGLE@{ub} - toggle filtering.
    @{b}REMOVE@{ub} - flush the existing set of filters, but keep the database.

  @{b}HISTORY@{ub} @{i}@{b}APPEND/K,FLUSH/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}APPEND@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - modify the action performed by the
      '@{i}SAVE SESSION@{ui}' and '@{i}LOAD SESSION@{ui}' commands, as explained above.
    @{b}FLUSH@{ub} - flush the history buffer.

  @{b}DEBUG@{ub} @{i}@{b}NOTE/K/F,ASK/S/F,ON/S/F,OFF/S/F,TOGGLE/S/F@{ub}@{ui}
    @{u}Menu flag changing arguments@{uu}:
      @{b}ON@{ub} - turn ON debugging.
      @{b}OFF@{ub} - turn OFF debuging.
      @{b}TOGGLE@{ub} - toggle debugging.
    @{b}ASK@{ub} - popup the requester to ask for a debugging note.
    @{b}NOTE@{ub}=(@{i}note@{ui}) - debugging note.

  @{b}ASK@{ub} @{i}@{b}DB_FILTER/S,THRESHOLD_APP/S,THRESHOLD_SEP/S,PALETTE/S,ORBS/S,T0/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{u}All arguments popup the requester asking for@{uu}:
      @{b}DB_FILTER@{ub} - define another @{"filter" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_FILTERS} for the current database.
      @{b}THRESHOLD_APP@{ub} - threshold of applying aspects.
      @{b}THRESHOLD_SEP@{ub} - threshold of separating aspects.
      @{b}PALETTE@{ub} - palette (color) change.
      @{b}ORBS@{ub} - orbs of (main) objects.
      @{b}T0@{ub} - custom @{"sid(ereal)" link ASENSE-SIDEREAL-VS-SID} zodiac.

  @{b}QUERY@{ub} @{i}@{b}STRING/S/F,RET_STRING/S/F@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}STRING@{ub} - fetch the @{"data string" link ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING} from the current side as secondary result.
    @{b}RET_STRING@{ub} - fetch the @{"return string" link ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW} from the current side as secondary
      result.
@endnode
///
///       GUI commands                                    //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-GUI "ASense - ARexx: GUI handling commands"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-IO
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-DECIDE

  @{b}HIDE@{ub} @{i}@{b}ON_CLOSE/K,NO_MORE/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}HIDE@{ub} (no arguments) - hide the ASense.
    @{b}NO_MORE@{ub} - appear back from hiding.
    @{u}Menu flag changing arguments@{uu}:
      @{b}ON_CLOSE@{ub}@{b}@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - hide instead of closing.

  @{b}LOCK@{ub} (no arguments) - lock the GUI (set the busy pointer).
  @{b}UNLOCK@{ub} (no arguments) - unlock the GUI.

  @{b}EXIT@{ub} (no arguments) - close the @{i}ARexx command shell@{ui} ONLY.
  @{b}QUIT@{ub} (no arguments) - quit the program.
@endnode
///
///       DECIDE command                                  //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-DECIDE "ASense - ARexx: DECIDE command"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-GUI
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-CHOOSE
@{"Decide" link ASENSE-MENUDECIDE} menu managing. Enter @{b}ONE@{ub} of the options, @{i}@{b}case sensitive@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}DECIDE@{ub} @{i}@{b}ZOD/K,SIDZ/K,HS/K,EPHE/K,
         YRET/K,YEAR/K,MRET/K,MON/K,DRET/K,DAY/K,DIRARC/K,SID_TR/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}ZOD@{ub}=(@{i}Trop Drac DrSd Side@{ui}) - decide the type of @{"zodiac" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ZODIAC}.
    @{b}SIDZ@{ub}=(@{i}option@{ui}) - decide which zodiac to use if ZOD==(@{i}DrSd@{ui} or @{i}Side@{ui}).
      @{u}Known definitions@{uu}: ('@{i}User@{ui}' selects a @{"custom" link } defined sidereal zodiac)
        @{i}User 0Sag Sass 2000 1950 1900@{ui} - @{i}sidereal@{ui} zodiacs (@{i}ayanamsha@{ui} == 0.0)
        @{i}FagB Lahi DeLu Rama Usha Krsh DjKh Yukt@{ui} - @{i}sid@{ui} zodiacs (@{i}ayanamsha@{ui} != 0.0)
        @{i}JnBh Aldb BHub Bab3 Bab2 Bab1 EPsc Hipp@{ui} - @{i}sid@{ui} zodiacs (@{i}ayanamsha@{ui} != 0.0)
    @{b}HS@{ub}=(@{i}Z z T G P M R C B b O N K H X W V p A E@{ui}) - select the @{"house system" link ASENSE-DECIDE-HS}.
      For the meaning of individual letters, refer to @{i}Decide/House System@{ui} menu.
    @{b}EPHE@{ub}=(@{i}JPL SWIS BUIL@{ui}) - decide which @{"ephe" link ASENSE-DECIDE-EPHEMERIS} (if available) to use.
    @{u}@{"Arguments" link ASENSE-DECIDE-YMD} to define the meaning of words '@{i}year@{ui}', '@{i}month@{ui}' and '@{i}day@{ui}'@{uu}:
      @{b}YRET@{ub}=(@{i}TSol MSol@{ui}) - @{i}true@{ui} or @{i}mean@{ui} solar year, type options below.
      @{b}YEAR@{ub}=(@{i}Anom Side Trop Drac@{ui}) - types of solar years.
      @{b}MRET@{ub}=(@{i}TLun MLun@{ui}) - @{i}true@{ui} or @{i}mean@{ui} lunar month, type options below.
      @{b}MON@{ub}=(@{i}Syno Anom Side Trop Drac@{ui}) - types of lunar months.
      @{b}DRET@{ub}=(@{i}TDay MDay@{ui}) - @{i}true@{ui} or @{i}mean@{ui} MC return, type options below.
      @{b}DAY@{ub}=(@{i}Syno Side Trop@{ui}) - types of MC returns to define a '@{i}day@{ui}'.
    @{b}DIRARC@{ub}=(@{i}Sol Lun MC Asc@{ui}) - type of @{"arc" link ASENSE-DECIDE-ARCS} to use for directions.
    @{b}SID_TR@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - enable or disable calculation of @{"sidereal transits" link ASENSE-DECIDE-SID-TRANSITS}.
@endnode
///
///       CHOOSE & SHOW commands                          //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-CHOOSE "ASense - ARexx: CHOOSE aand SHOW commands"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-DECIDE
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-SELECT
@{"Choose" link ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE} menu managing. Enter @{b}ONE@{ub} of the options, @{i}@{b}case sensitive@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}CHOOSE@{ub} @{i}@{b}RETS/K,PROGR/K,DIRS/K,MIDP/K,COAL/K,MIDT_ECL/K,MIDPLACE/K,
         ANG_CROSS_TYPE/K,ANG_CROSS_INTV/K,ASP_PLANE/K,SID_MODE/K,
         ORIENTATION/K,PRESENTATION/K,COOR2/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}RETS@{ub}=(@{i}RSol RLun Enne@{ui}) - type of @{"return" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-RETURNS} charts.
    @{b}PROGR@{ub}=(@{i}PI PII PIII PMin@{ui}) - type of @{"progressions" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PROGRESSIONS}.
    @{b}DIRS@{ub}=(@{i}DI DII DIII@{ui}) - type of @{"directions" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-DIRECTIONS}.
    @{b}MIDP@{ub}=(@{i}Coor GC@{ui}) - select @{"method" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING 52} of chart merging.
    @{b}COAL@{ub}=(@{i}1D 2D GC@{ui}) - select @{"method" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING 147} of coalescing.
    @{b}MIDT_ECL@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - select whether to use the @{"midtime eccliptic" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING 31}.
    @{b}MIDPLACE@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - select whether to use relocation to @{"midplace" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING 45}.
    @{b}ANG_CROSS_TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}UpLi Cent LoLi@{ui}) - select the type of @{"angular crossing" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ANGLE-CROSSINGS}.
    @{b}ANG_CROSS_INTV@{ub}=(@{i}Date Prev Half Next@{ui}) - @{"interval" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ANGLE-CROSSINGS} of time to be searched for
      angular crossings.
    @{b}ASP_PLANE@{ub}=(@{i}2DEc 2DEq 2DHo True@{ui}) - select @{"plane" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC} of aspects, if any.
    @{b}SID_MODE@{ub}=(@{i}Trad Accu@{ui}) - how to compute the @{"sidereal" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES} charts.
    @{b}ORIENTATION@{ub}=(@{i}N S Comb@{ui}) - select the @{"view" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ORIENTATION}.
    @{b}PRESENTATION@{ub}=(@{i}None Ring Cone@{ui}) - select type of @{"presentation" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION}.
    @{b}COOR2@{ub}=(@{i}Pair Decl Lat Alt RAlt@{ui}) - select @{"2nd coordinate" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-2ND_COOR} to present.

  @{b}SHOW@{ub} @{i}@{b}RINGED/K,STARS/K,R_STARS/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}RINGED@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - draw chart in outer ring, around the main one.
    @{b}STARS@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - enable or disable drawing of stars.
    @{b}R_STARS@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - use special color (@{i}black@{ui} is default) to mark
      retrograde moving stars. (When precession & aberration are disabled,
      most stars on one side are retrograde, and on the other are direct.
      This roughly indicates the course of the motion of the solar system.)
@endnode
///
///       SELECT command                                  //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-SELECT "ASense - ARexx: SELECT command"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-CHOOSE
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-DISPLAY
@{"Select" link ASENSE-MENUSELECT} menu managing. @{i}@{b}MULTIPLE@{ub}@{ui} choices are allowed unless otherwise stated.
  Enter them as a single string, @{i}@{b}case sensitive@{ub}@{ui}, with or without blanks.
  @{b}SELECT@{ub} @{i}@{b}TOGGLE/S,OFF/S,CENTER/K,CORRECTIONS/K,ASP_TYPES/K,ASP_FLAGS/K,
         PLANETS/K,NODES/K,STARS/K,MB_AST/K,CENTAURS/K,KBOS/K,OORTS/K,
         COMETS/K,PARTS/K,ANGLES/S@{ub}@{ui}
    Default action is to turn ON the selected items.
    @{b}TOGGLE@{ub} - the given items are to be toggled.
    @{b}OFF@{ub} - the given items are to be turned OFF.
    @{b}CENTER@{ub}=(@{i}Topo Geoc Helc Bary@{ui}) - select @{"center" link ASENSE-PHYSICS-CTR} of observation (@{b}ONE@{ub} of them).
    @{b}CORRECTIONS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}LTC Defl Aber Prec Nut Refr All@{ub}@{ui}) - select @{"corrections" link ASENSE-SELECT-PHYSICS}.
    @{b}ASP_TYPES@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}con Ó opp Ň squ Ô tri Ö sex * 1quint Q1 2quint Q2 1oct Ů 3oct Ú
      1cun Ű 5cun Ü 1non N1 2non N2 4non N4 1sept S1 2sept S2 3sept S3
      1Dec X1 3Dec X3 1und µ1 2und µ2 3und µ3 4und µ4 5und µ5 pll || paran Ţ
      5ser 7ser 8ser 9ser 10ser 11ser 12ser Main Minor Valid All@{ub}@{ui}) - @{"aspects" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASPECTS}.
      '@{i}Main@{ui}' aspects: @{i}con, opp, squ, tri, sex@{ui}.
      '@{i}Minor@{ui}' aspects: @{i}1oct, 3oct, 1cun, 5cun@{ui}.
      '@{i}Valid@{ui}' aspects: @{i}All@{ui} but @{i}11ser@{ui}.
    @{b}ASP_FLAGS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}2D_Stars 2D_Conj Asp2Ang Asp2Stars TightOrbs All@{ub}@{ui}) - @{"flags" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-ASPECTS-CALC}, as
      defined in @{"Choose" link ASENSE-MENUCHOOSE} menu.
    @{b}PLANETS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Sun á Moo ŕ Mer â Ven ä Ear ű Mar é Jup č Sat ę
             Ura í Nep ě Plu î Xen X All@{ub}@{ui}) - selection of planets.
    @{b}NODES@{ub}=(@{i}True Mean None@{ui}) - (lunar) @{"nodes" link ASENSE-SELECT-NODES} to calculate (select @{b}ONE@{ub} option).
    @{b}STARS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}None Named Bright Nearby Close Zod Var 0_mag # 1_mag * 2_mag +
      3_mag ¶ 4_mag · 5_mag ş Mess § Filter & All@{ub}@{ui}) - selection of @{"stars" link ASENSE-SELECT-STARS}.
    @{u}Asteroids & other minor objects@{uu}: (still @{i}unsupported@{ui}, except for Pluto)
      @{b}MB_AST@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Cer ó Pal ň Jun ô Ves ö Hyg Eun Eur Dav All@{ub}@{ui}) - Main Belt asteroids.
      @{b}CENTAURS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Chi ë Pho Unk Nes Asb ă Cha ç Hyl ý Cyl Oky The All@{ub}@{ui}) - Centaurs.
      @{b}KBOS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Xen X Plu î FY9 Orcu Quao Ixio Varu Chao Rhad All@{ub}@{ui}) - Kuiper Belt.
      @{b}OORTS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Sedn All@{ub}@{ui}) - (Inner) Oort Cloud objects.
      @{b}COMETS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Chir ë Hall All@{ub}@{ui}) - (Short term) comets.
    @{u}Derived objects@{uu}:
      @{b}PARTS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Fort × All@{ub}@{ui}) - @{"Arabic parts" link ASENSE-SELECT-PARTS}.
      @{b}ANGLES@{ub} - Display data about the @{"angles" link ASENSE-SELECT-ANGLES} together with the other objects.

  IMPORTANT NOTE: @{b}ARexx allows upto @{i}15@{ui} arguments to be used simultaneously@{ub}.
    This command has more, so don't specify all of them in a @{i}single@{ui} call...
  NOTE: @{i}@{b}Xen X FY9 Hall@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}Mess@{ub}@{ui} attributes are still @{i}unsupported@{ui}.
  @{i}Example@{ui}: 'SELECT PLANETS="SunMoon Mars"' to turn them ON.

  @{b}@{u}Links to other part of the manual@{uu}@{ub}:
    @{"Planets" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS"} (planets and luminaries)
    @{"Minor Planets" link "ASense-astronomy.guide/ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS"} (asteroids and comets)
@endnode
///
///       DISPLAY & ROUND commands                        //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-DISPLAY "ASense - ARexx: DISPLAY and ROUND commands"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-SELECT
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-PICK
@{"Display" link ASENSE-MENUDISPLAY} menu managing. @{i}@{b}MULTIPLE@{ub}@{ui} choices are allowed unless otherwise stated.
  Enter them as a single string, @{i}@{b}case sensitive@{ub}@{ui}, with or without blanks.
  @{b}DISPLAY@{ub} @{i}@{b}TOGGLE/S,OFF/S,HEADER/K,OBJ/K,FORMAT1/K,FORMAT2/K,FORMAT3/K,
          ASPECTS/K,STCAT/K,STSYN/K,STARS1/K,STRAS4/K,STARS5/K,STARS6/K@{ub}@{ui}
    Default action is to turn ON the selected items.
    @{b}TOGGLE@{ub} - the given items are to be toggled.
    @{b}OFF@{ub} - the given items are to be turned OFF.
    @{b}HEADER@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block nohs name date time JD sidt deltat loc coors atpres attemp
      Trueeps Meaneps nutlon nuteps lunincl vertex equasc All@{ub}@{ui}) - @{"header" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-HEADER} options.
    @{b}OBJ@{ub}=(@{i}Name Glyp@{ui}) - naming of objects in caption column (select @{b}ONE@{ub} option).
    @{b}FORMAT1@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block zod long lonsp latit latsp rect RAsp decl decsp distan distsp
      hposit hpossw All@{ub}@{ui}) - selection of columns in @{"table 1" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-1}.
    @{b}FORMAT2@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block azim azsp altit altsp refalt raltsp rise culm zenith set
      bottom nadir maxralt maxalt minralt minalt All@{ub}@{ui}) - columns in @{"table 2" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-2}.
    @{b}FORMAT3@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block carteclip carteclsp cartequat cartequsp constell phang phperc
      elong appdiam mag deforb All@{ub}@{ui}) - selection of columns in @{"table 3" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-FORMAT-3}.
    @{b}ASPECTS@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}noasp block delta angle perc asporb totorb halforb All@{ub}@{ui}) - columns
      in @{"table of aspects" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-ASPECTS}.
    @{b}STCAT@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block Name Flams Bayer HR GCVS FKS HIP HD DM GJ ADS GenCat All@{ub}@{ui}) -
      selection of columns in the @{"cross-reference" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-CAT} of stars table.
    @{b}STSYN@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block names+ transl All@{ub}@{ui}) - columns in @{"proper star names table" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-SYN}.
    @{b}STARS1@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block rot parall plxerr lyrs lyerr parsec pcerr All@{ub}@{ui}) - selection
      of columns in @{"distance & rotation" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-1} related stellar parameters table.
    @{b}STRAS4@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block vartyp maxmag minmag absmag U_B B_V R_I epoch perc period
      All@{ub}@{ui}) - columns in the @{"variability" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-4} related stellar parameters table.
    @{b}STARS5@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block order sptype notes All@{ub}@{ui}) - columns in @{"spectral types table" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-5}.
    @{b}STARS6@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}block temp bolcorr vislum totlum distear radii masses All@{ub}@{ui}) -
      selection of columns in @{"luminosity" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-STARS-6} related stellar parameters table.

  @{b}ROUND@{ub} @{i}@{b}ARCS/K,AU/K,MAG/K,PERC/K,ABBREV/K@{ub}@{ui}
    The @{"precision" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-ROUND} of the output (select @{b}ONE@{ub} of options).
    @{b}ARCS@{ub}=(@{i}Mins Secs None@{ui}) - round arcs to...
    @{b}AU@{ub}=(@{i}1Dig 3Dig 9Dig@{ui}) - round distances to...
    @{b}MAG@{ub}=(@{i}1Dig 2Dig@{ui}) - round magnitudes to...
    @{b}PERC@{ub}=(@{i}Perc Prom None@{ui}) - round dimensionless numbers to..
    @{b}ABBREV@{ub}=(@{i}Abbr Ful@{ui}l) - round constellation names to...
@endnode
///
///       PICKing commands                                //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-PICK "ASense - ARexx: SIDE,STEPS,SORT and HOVER_HELP commands"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-DISPLAY
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-SET
@{"Pick" link ASENSE-MENUPICK} menu managing. Enter @{b}ONE@{ub} of the options, @{i}@{b}case sensitive@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}SIDE@{ub} @{i}@{b}LEFT/S/F,RIGHT/S/F@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}LEFT@{ub} - pick the left @{"side" link ASENSE-PICK-SIDE}.
    @{b}RIGHT@{ub} - pick the right @{"side" link ASENSE-PICK-SIDE}.

  @{b}STEPS@{ub} @{i}@{b}TYPE/K,TIME/K,CYCLE/K,GEOLON/K,GEOLAT/K,ALT/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}Time Cycl GLon GLat GAlt@{ui}) - select @{"type of steps" link ASENSE-PICK-STEPS} for offset charts.
    @{b}TIME@{ub}=(@{i}secs mins hour days mons year ctry mill@{ui}) - select size of time steps.
    @{b}CYCLE@{ub}=(@{i}SolR LunR SolE Tran Prog Dirs@{ui}) - if steps are cycles, which cycles.
    @{b}GEOLON@{ub}=(@{i}h m s deg amin asec@{ui}) - size of the step in gegraphical longitudes.
    @{b}GEOLAT@{ub}=(@{i}deg amin asec@{ui}) - select size of the step in gegraphical latitudes.
    @{b}ALT@{ub}=(@{i}m hm km@{ui}) - select size of the step in altitudes.
    @{b}BY_TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}1 2 3 4 5 6 8@{ub}@{ui}) - set step depending upon the selected @{i}TYPE@{ui}.
      Acceptable values correspond to shortcuts in @{i}Pick/Time Step@{ui} menu.
  @{i}Example@{ui}: 'STEPS TYPE=GAlt BY_TYPE=2' sets the steps to @{i}meters of altitude@{ui}.

  @{b}SORT@{ub} @{i}@{b}DB_IN_REVERSE/K,STARS_IN_REVERSE/K,DATABASE/K,ASPECTS/K,STARS/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}DB_IN_REVERSE@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - reverse @{"default" link ASENSE-PROJECT-DB_SORT} database sorting order.
    @{b}STARS_IN_REVERSE@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - reverse @{"default" link ASENSE-PICK-STAR_SORT} stellar sorting order.
    @{b}DATABASE@{ub}=(@{i}None Name Plac Time EW NS DtCl@{ui}) - select the primary sorting
      parameter for databases.
    @{b}ASPECTS@{ub}=(@{i}1Obj Type 2Obj Attr Perc@{ui}) - select the primary sorting parameter
      for aspects in tables.
    @{b}STARS@{ub}=(@{i}Name HR Cons Mag SpTy Long Lat RA Decl Vici Az Alt HPos@{ui}) - select
      the primary @{"sorting parameter for stars" link ASENSE-PICK-STAR_SORT} in tables.

  @{b}HOVER_HELP@{ub} @{i}@{b}OBJECTS/K,GADGETS/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OBJECTS@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - @{"hover help" link ASENSE-PICK-HELPS} for charted objects.
    @{b}GADGETS@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - hover help for gadgets.
@endnode
///
///       SETting commands                                //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-SET "ASense - ARexx: SET,THRESHOLD,COLOR,ORB,CUSTOM,DEFAULT and RESET commands"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-PICK
@NEXT ASENSE-COMMANDS-CHARTS
@{"Set" link ASENSE-MENUPICK} menu managing. Enter @{b}ONE@{ub} of the options, @{i}@{b}case sensitive@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}STRSET@{ub} @{i}@{b}RET/K,OVERWRITE/K,AS/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}RET@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - toggle between the @{"main" link ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING} and @{"return" link ASENSE-GADGETS-TOP-ROW} input string.
    @{b}OVERWRITE@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - enable/disable overwriting during typing.
    @{b}AS@{ub}=(@{i}Undo Offs Copy prev next@{ui} (@{i}data@{ui})) - alter the string's content.
      @{i}Undo@{ui} - perform 1 level undo, provided by Intuition.
      @{i}Offs@{ui} - reset the string to accumulated @{"offsets" link ASENSE-GADGETS-MIDDLE-ROW}.
      @{i}Copy@{ui} - copy data from the other side into this one.
      @{i}prev@{ui} - get previous record from the @{"history buffer" link ASENSE-PROJECT-HISTORY}.
      @{i}next@{ui} - get the next record from the history buffer.
     (@{i}data@{ui}) - user supplied string data, @{b}no sanity check@{ub}.
  Note: Don't forget to set the appropriate @{"side" link ASENSE-GADGETS-SIDES}, before setting strings.

  @{b}THRESHOLD@{ub} @{i}@{b}APPLYING/N,SEPARATING/N@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}APPLYING@{ub}=(@{i}promiles@{ui}) - threshold for applying aspects in promiles.
    @{b}SEPARATING@{ub}=(@{i}promiles@{ui}) - threshold for separating aspects in promiles.

  @{b}COLOR@{ub} @{i}@{b}NR/A/N,R/A/N,G/A/N,B/A/N@{ub}@{ui}
    Set the RGB values of a single color (only first 32 colors are used).
    @{b}NR@{ub}=(@{i}index@{ui}) - index of the color to be set (0..31).
    @{b}R@{ub}=(@{i}red@{ui}) - red value (0..255).
    @{b}G@{ub}=(@{i}green@{ui}) - green value (0..255).
    @{b}B@{ub}=(@{i}blue@{ui}) - blue value (0..255).
    NOTE: @{i}On AmigaOS V37/V38, RGB values are scaled down to 0..15 interval,
      and the color index is reduced to (0..15)@{ui} (except in low resolution).

  @{b}ORB@{ub} @{i}@{b}OBJECT/A/K,VALUE/A/N@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OBJECT@{ub}=(@{i}name@{ui}) - name of @{b}ONE@{ub} object for which the orb is to be set.
      @{u}Known names@{uu}: @{i}@{b}Sun á Moon ŕ Merc â Venu ä Eart ű Mars é Jupi č Satu ę
        Uran í Nept ě Plut î NNod Ć ú SNod ć ů Asc Desc MC IC Chir ë Phol
        Cere ó Pall ň Juno ô Vest ö@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}VALUE@{ub}=(@{i}arc_secs@{ui}) - value of the orb, in arc seconds.
    @{i}Example@{ui}: 'ORB OBJECT=Sun VALUE=60000' - sets the Sun's orb to 16°40'.

  @{b}CUSTOM@{ub} @{i}@{b}T0/K,AYANAMSHA/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}T0@{ub}=(@{i}julian day/time@{ui}) - set the start of custom @{"sid(ereal)" link ASENSE-SIDEREAL-VS-SID} zodiac.
    @{b}AYANAMSHA@{ub}=(@{i}degrees@{ui}) - set the ayanamsha (sid offset) at T0.
    @{i}Example@{ui} (@{u}random values@{uu}): 'CUSTOM T0=2433147.625482 AYANAMSHA=23.675'

  @{b}DEFAULT@{ub} @{i}@{b}THRESHOLDS/S,PALETTE/S,ORBS/S,CONFIG/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{u}Set default values for@{uu}:
      @{b}THRESHOLDS@{ub} - thresholds of aspects.
      @{b}PALETTE@{ub} - colors.
      @{b}ORBS@{ub} - orbs of (main) objects.
      @{b}CONFIG@{ub} - settings.

  @{b}RESET@{ub} @{i}@{b}OFFSETS/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OFFSETS@{ub} - reset all of the accumulated offsets (of time, coors and cycles).
@endnode
///
///       CHARTing commands                               //f
@node ASENSE-COMMANDS-CHARTS "ASense - ARexx: Chart casting commands"
@TOC ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@PREV ASENSE-COMMANDS-SET
@NEXT ASENSE-AREXX-COMMANDS
@{"Chart" link ASENSE-MENUCHARTS} menu managing. Enter @{b}ONE@{ub} of the options, @{i}@{b}case sensitive@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}CHART@{ub} @{i}@{b}OFFSETS/S,OFFSET/N@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OFFSETS@{ub} - use the accumulated @{"offsets" link ASENSE-PICK-STEPS} (plain chart otherwise).
    @{b}OFFSET@{ub}=(@{i}value@{ui}) - add an @{i}offset@{ui} of selected @{"type" link ASENSE-COMMANDS-PICK}.

  @{b}STAR_CHART@{ub} @{i}@{b}OFFSETS/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OFFSETS@{ub} - use the accumulated @{i}offsets@{ui} (plain chart otherwise).

  @{b}CYCLE@{ub} @{i}@{b}OFFSETS/S,TYPE/A/K,DUAL/S,DUAL_TIME_ONLY/S@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OFFSETS@{ub} - use the accumulated @{i}offsets@{ui} (plain chart otherwise).
    @{b}TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}SolR LunR SolE Ret Tran Prog Dirs@{ub}@{ui}) - type of the @{"cycle chart" link ASENSE-CHARTS-SINGLE} to cast.
    @{b}DUAL@{ub} - make it a @{"dual" link ASENSE-CHARTS-DUAL} chart.
    @{b}DUAL_TIME_ONLY@{ub} - make it a @{"dual-with-time-only" link ASENSE-CHARTS-DUAL} chart.

  @{b}MERGE@{ub} @{i}@{b}OFFSETS/S,TYPE/A/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OFFSETS@{ub} - use the accumulated @{i}offsets@{ui} (plain chart otherwise).
    @{b}TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Rela Comp Coal@{ub}@{ui}) - select type of @{"merging" link ASENSE-CHARTS-MERGING}.

  @{b}SYNASTRY@{ub} @{i}@{b}OFFSETS/S,TYPE/A/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OFFSETS@{ub} - use the accumulated @{i}offsets@{ui} (plain chart otherwise).
    @{b}TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}_L_R _LLR RL_R _LRL LR_R RLLR@{ub}@{ui}) - select type of @{"synastry" link ASENSE-CHARTS-SYNASTRY} charts.

  @{b}EPHE@{ub} @{i}@{b}OFFSETS/S,INTV/K,TWOMON/K,WEEKDAYS/K,SIDT/K,ECL_LON/K,COORS/K,RSMI/K,
       STATIONS/K,VOC/K,INGRESSES/K,PHASES/K,ECLIPSES/K,TYPE/K,SAVE/K,ACC/K,
       COMPACT/K@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}OFFSETS@{ub} - use the accumulated @{i}offsets@{ui} (plain chart otherwise).
    @{b}INTV@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}ChMn CuMn ChYr CuYr Dual@{ub}@{ui}) - select type of @{"ephemeris" link ASENSE-CHARTS-EPHEMERIS} to generate.
      '@{i}Dual@{ui}' means ephemeris for interval between left and right side charts.
    @{b}TWOMON@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - extend the monthly ephemeris with nearby month.
    @{b}WEEKDAYS@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE]@{ui} - include column of weekdays.
    @{b}SIDT@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - include column of sidereal times.
    @{b}ECL_LON@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - include @{i}ecliptic longitudes@{ui} of objects ONLY.
    @{b}COORS@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - include ALL selected coors from tables 1 and 2.
    @{b}RSMI@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - include ALL selected @{i}angle crossing times@{ui} (table 2).
    @{u}Events, calculated monthly@{uu}:
      @{b}STATIONS@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - times of @{i}retrograde@{ui} <-> @{i}prograde@{ui} changes.
      @{b}VOC@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - '@{i}Moon void of course@{ui}' times (unsupported).
      @{b}INGRESSES@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - @{i}new-zodiac-sign-entering@{ui} times.
      @{b}PHASES@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - times of @{i}lunar phases@{ui} (unsupported).
      @{b}ECLIPSES@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - details of @{i}eclipses@{ui} (unsupported).
    @{b}TYPE@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}Noon Midn Rand@{ub}@{ui}) - select starting point of the ephemeris, and time
      steps for which the values listed in the ephemeris are to be generated.
    @{b}SAVE@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - save the resulting ephemeris (ask for a filename).
    @{b}ACC@{ub}=(@{i}@{b}VHig High Norm Low VLow@{ub}@{ui}) - select the @{"precision" link ASENSE-DISPLAY-ROUND} of generated ephemeris.
    @{b}COMPACT@{ub}=[@{i}ON/OFF/TOGGLE@{ui}] - more compact output.
  IMPORTANT NOTE: @{b}ARexx allows upto @{i}15@{ui} arguments to be used simultaneously@{ub}.
    This command has more, so don't specify all of them in a @{i}single@{ui} call...

  @{b}STATS@{ub} @{i}@{b}PARTIAL/S/F,FULL/S/F@{ub}@{ui}
    @{b}PARTIAL@{ub} - show some of the usage @{"statistics" link ASENSE-PROJECT-STATS}.
    @{b}FULL@{ub} - show complete usage statistics.
@endnode
///
///   Lupe                                                //f
@node ASENSE-PICK-LUPE "ASense - Menus: Pick Lupe"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPICK
@PREV ASENSE-PICK-AREXX
@NEXT ASENSE-PICK-SIDE
@{b}@{u}Lupe@{uu}@{ub} - A magnifying glass.

    @{b}Lupe is a third party public domain utility@{ub}, included in the ASense to
  allow easier visual observation of fine details within complicated charts.
  To use it, place the executable wherever you like, and set a 'LUPE_FILE'
  tooltype string in the program's icon to point to it.After that, the Lupe
  will be accessible from the menu.

    To be able to further customize it, please read the @{"original docs" link "lupe.doc/Main" 0}.

    @{i}The Lupe archive@{ui} (with the source code) @{i}is available on the Aminet@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Side                                                //f
@node ASENSE-PICK-SIDE "ASense - Menus: Pick Side"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPICK
@PREV ASENSE-PICK-LUPE
@NEXT ASENSE-PICK-STEPS
@{b}@{u}Side@{uu}@{ub} - Left or right, should be self-explanatory.

    Changes the focus of the program's attention.The subsequent menu actions
  would refer to the selected side.@{i}Pressing any of the chart-casting GUI
  buttons would automatically change the focus to the nearest side@{ui}.

    @{b}Numeric keypad keys '4' and '6' would do the same@{ub}.
@endnode
///
///   Steps                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PICK-STEPS "ASense - Menus: Pick Steps"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPICK
@PREV ASENSE-PICK-SIDE
@NEXT ASENSE-PICK-STAR_SORT
@{b}@{u}Step Type@{uu}@{ub} - Steps of time, geo. lon/lat/alt and of cycles are possible.

    When advancing the chart by the GUI buttons (-20..+20 offsets) on the
  right side of the middle row, the steps are made upon the type selected
  here.It can be one of the following chart-data parameters: @{i}@{b}time, geolon.,
  geolat. or altitude@{ub}@{ui}.(The @{i}temperature@{ui} may only be changed directly in the
  string gadget if anyone ever needs to do that.)
    It is also possible to make offsets of @{i}@{b}cycles@{ub}@{ui}.

    @{b}The stepping allows a quick manual chart analysis@{ub} within the time/space
  continuum.which is specifically useful for @{i}@{b}rectifications@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}relocations@{ub}@{ui},
  @{i}@{b}elections@{ub}@{ui} and some other things (finding @{i}@{b}hits, planetary returns; phases,
  eclipses@{ub}@{ui},...).

@{b}@{u}Step Size@{uu}@{ub} - Advance by n units of...

    After selecting the Step Type, the accompanying measurement unit should
  be selected too.Only then the offsets may be applied (-20..+20 buttons).
@endnode
///
///   Star Sort                                           //f
@node ASENSE-PICK-STAR_SORT "ASense - Menus: Pick Star Sort"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPICK
@PREV ASENSE-PICK-STEPS
@NEXT ASENSE-PICK-HELPS
@{b}@{u}Star Sort@{uu}@{ub} - Sort prominent stars by this parameter (as indicated).

  @{u}The available parameters are@{uu}:
  - @{i}@{b}Name@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}proper name@{ui} (alphabetically)
  - @{i}@{b}HR Index@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by index in the @{i}Harvard Revised@{ui} catalog of stars
    (a.k.a @{i}Bright Stars Catalogue@{ui}).
  - @{i}@{b}Constellation@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by membership of a star in a constellation
    (by alphabetic names of constellations).
  - @{i}@{b}Magnitude@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}maximal visual magnitude@{ui} (brightest stars first).
  - @{i}@{b}Sp. Type@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}spectral type@{ui} (alphabetical string sort).
  - @{i}@{b}Ecl. Long.@{ub}@{ui}- Sort by @{i}ecliptical longitude@{ui} (Aries first).
  - @{i}@{b}Ecl. Lat.@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}ecliptical latitude@{ui} (N -> S).
  - @{i}@{b}R.A.@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}right ascension@{ui} (0h first).
  - @{i}@{b}Declinat.@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}declination@{ui} (N -> S).
  - @{i}@{b}Vicinity@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}distance@{ui} (closest stars first).
  - @{i}@{b}Azimuth@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}azimuth@{ui} (0° first).
  - @{i}@{b}Altitude@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}altitude@{ui} (N -> S).
  - @{i}@{b}House Pos.@{ub}@{ui} - Sort by @{i}house position@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Helps                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PICK-HELPS "ASense - Menus: Pick Helps"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUPICK
@PREV ASENSE-PICK-STAR_SORT
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUPICK
@{b}@{u}Hover Help@{uu}@{ub} - @{i}Point on a body@{ui} to receive help about it.

    By moving a mouse pointer on a body, you will receive a quick help.
  The name and the main drawn coordinate would be displayed in the lower
  left corner of a chart.

    @{i}@{b}This help is somewhat CPU intensive and hence it can be turned off@{ub}@{ui}.

@{b}@{u}Click Help@{uu}@{ub} - @{i}Click on a body@{ui} to receive help about it.

    Works identically as '@{i}Hover Help@{ui}', except that one has to click on a
  body to receive help about it.

    @{i}If several bodies overlap each other, clicking on them will reveal the
  first or second one from a pile (subsequently), but not the deeper ones@{ui}.

    @{b}If '@{i}Hover Help@{ui}' is turned off, clicking on a body will give help about
  it, but moving a pointer away from it won't erase it@{ub}!

@{b}@{u}Double Click Help@{uu}@{ub} - @{i}Double click on a body@{ui} to invoke a more detailed help
  from the manual if it is available.This may only work for several bodies.
@endnode
///
@remark Set
/// Set                                                   //f
@node ASENSE-MENUSET "ASense - Menus: Set"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT ASENSE-SET-THRESHOLD
@{b}@{u}Set@{uu}@{ub}: Configure ASense.

  @{"Threshold of Aspects" link ASENSE-SET-THRESHOLD} - reject the inaccurate ones.
  @{"Pallete" link ASENSE-SET-PALETTE} - customize the colors.
  @{"Orbs" link ASENSE-SET-ORBS} - customize the orbs.
  @{"Sid(ereal) t0" link ASENSE-SET-AYANAMSHA} - set a custom ayanamsha.
  @{"Screen Mode" link ASENSE-SET-SCREEN_MODE} - customize the screen mode.
  @{"Setings IO" link ASENSE-SET-SETTINGS} - load/save settings.
@endnode
///
///   Threshold of Aspects                                //f
@node ASENSE-SET-THRESHOLD "ASense - Menus: Set Threshold"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSET
@PREV ASENSE-MENUSET
@NEXT ASENSE-SET-PALETTE
@{b}@{u}Threshold of Aspects@{uu}@{ub} - Reject the inaccurate ones.

    @{b}Aspects that have a percentage of precision which is @{i}less@{ui} than this
  threshold are rejected as insignificant@{ub}.The threshold is entered in
  @{i}promiles@{ui} to allow extra precision.

    @{i}Default value is 500@{ui}, which means that aspects with less than 50.0%
  of precision percentage would be rejected.Nevertheless, @{b}@{i}values down to
  433@{ui} (half of the exact) @{i}were also found to show reliable results@{ui}@{ub}.

  NOTE: Higher values of this threshold are required to filter down the
  aspects from a dense @{i}synastry@{ui} chart or from some temporary one (like
  a @{i}horary@{ui} for example).For these cases, the user is advised to set a
  '@{i}Choose/Aspects Calc./Very Tight Orbs@{ui}' switch instead.This switch is
  also available as a GUI button in a center of a bottom row.By setting
  this switch, the orbs would be halfed, but the chart would still have
  a @{i}normal@{ui} distribution of aspects (i.e. all sorts of precisions).This
  would NOT be the case if a threshold of aspects is raised.
@endnode
///
///   Palette                                             //f
@node ASENSE-SET-PALETTE "ASense - Menus: Set Palette"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSET
@PREV ASENSE-SET-THRESHOLD
@NEXT ASENSE-SET-ORBS
@{b}@{u}Pallete@{uu}@{ub} - Customize the colors.

    The ASense screen has a depth of 5, which means that it uses 32 different
  colors.The user is allowed to customize these colors.Only one color register
  is still unused by the ASense at the time of this writing (number 8, purple).
  It can be used as a scratch register by the user.Or maybe not.
  UPDATE: The color 8 was changed to @{i}window_blue@{ui} and used to draw auxiliary
  rings when 2 coordinates @{"presentation modes" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-PRESENTATION} were selected.There are NO free
  colors anymore...

    One may notice that some colors have duplicates.One copy is usually used
  for @{i}aspects@{ui}, and the other for something else (usually @{i}stellar glyphs@{ui}).This
  approach allows easier customization, because single color registers have a
  dedicated purpose.Registers at the end of array are for the @{i}stellar glyphs@{ui}.
  The only exceptions are colors @{b}4@{ub} (@{i}@{b}purple@{ub}@{ui}, used for both @{i}sextiles@{ui} and
  @{i}retrograde@{ui} objects), and @{b}11@{ub} (@{i}@{b}red@{ub}@{ui}, used for both @{i}trines@{ui} and @{i}arabic parts@{ui}).

    When customizing the colors, user is advised to utilize a '@{b}Show RGB@{ub}'
  switch in a @{"Lupe" link ASENSE-PICK-LUPE} (a magnifying glass third part utility, available from a
  '@{i}Pick/Lupe@{ui}' menu item).This allows an easy recognition of colors from the
  screen.

  NOTE: @{"Colors of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COLOR} are carefully chosen to fit the purpose.Think @{i}twice@{ui}
  before introducing significant changes.(@{b}If the colors get standardized, the
  cross-examination of charts would be much easier, and one should not have
  to read a legend every time to understand the chart@{ub}.) Please respect that.
    The stars were colored according to their natural spectral classification.
    Last two colors (31 and 30) are colors of a @{i}cursor@{ui} in a string gadget and
  its @{i}background@{ui} (respectively).
@endnode
///
///   Orbs                                                //f
@node ASENSE-SET-ORBS "ASense - Menus: Set Orbs"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSET
@PREV ASENSE-SET-PALETTE
@NEXT ASENSE-SET-AYANAMSHA
@{b}@{u}Orbs@{uu}@{ub} - Customize the orbs.

    The sizes of orbs are not accurately empirically measured by anyone yet.
  Thus, the user is left with an option to change the default values to its
  own accord.

    To change an orb, enter the size of it in SECONDS of arc, and then click
  on a glyph of a body to which you wish this orb to be assigned to, to satisfy
  the requester.
    Repeat as many times as you like.

  NOTE: The chapter about the @{"computation of aspects" link ASENSE-ASPECTS-COMPUTATION} explains the hadling of
  the orbs.There is an upper limit for the size of the 2 largest orbs that
  should be respected if one wishes to avoid the @{i}overlapping@{ui} of aspects
  (i.e. 2 bodies being in 2 different aspects *simultaneously*).
@endnode
///
///   Ayanamsha                                           //f
@node ASENSE-SET-AYANAMSHA "ASense - Menus: Set Ayanamsha"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSET
@PREV ASENSE-SET-ORBS
@NEXT ASENSE-SET-SCREEN_MODE
@{b}@{u}Sid(ereal) t0@{uu}@{ub} - Set a custom ayanamsha.

    Enter a date and time of ayanamsha, then answer the requester.If you
  answer with '@{b}Sidereal@{ub}', it would be assumed that at the given time moment
  the @{b}sidereal shift@{ub} (ayanamsha) @{b}was zero@{ub}.This case will allow the usage
  of @{i}@{b}accurate@{ub}@{ui} algorithm of transformation to your custom sidereal zodiac.

    Otherwise, if you click on '@{b}Sid(ereal)@{ub}', you will also be prompted to
  enter a (@{b}nonzero@{ub}) @{b}sidereal shift@{ub} for the previously entered time.In this
  case, only the @{i}@{b}traditional@{ub}@{ui} algorithm of sidereal tranformation can be
  applied to your @{i}custom@{ui} sidereal zodiac.

    You may abort as well.

    More details about the used transformations from tropical to sidereal
  zodiac can be found in description of a '@{"Choose/Sid. Mode" link ASENSE-CHOOSE-SID-MODES}' menu.
@endnode
///
///   Screen Mode                                         //f
@node ASENSE-SET-SCREEN_MODE "ASense - Menus: Set Settings"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSET
@PREV ASENSE-SET-AYANAMSHA
@NEXT ASENSE-SET-SETTINGS
@{b}@{u}Screen Mode@{uu}@{ub} - customize the screen mode.

  - @{b}Select & Use@{ub} - if the selected screen mode differs from default, the
    ASense will store it's id in the environment variable 'AS_SCREEN_MODE'.
    When you select this menu item, the value in ENV: will be updated.
    The ASense will also try to adapt it's GUI to the new resolution.
    (@{i}Note that you may still use 3rd party mode promoters in combination
     with this option, for example to open a high resolution screen in a
     low resolution@{ui}.Several utilities of this type may be found on Aminet.)

  - @{b}Save Changes@{ub} - if the selected screen mode differs from default, the
    ASense will store it's id in the environment variable 'AS_SCREEN_MODE'.
    When you select this menu item, the value in ENVARC: will be updated.
@endnode
///
///   Settings                                            //f
@node ASENSE-SET-SETTINGS "ASense - Menus: Set Settings"
@TOC ASENSE-MENUSET
@PREV ASENSE-SET-SCREEN_MODE
@NEXT ASENSE-MENUSET
@{b}@{u}Setings@{uu}@{ub} - load/save settings.

    The choices should be self-explanatory.Anyway, it should be noted that
  @{b}by saving the settings you save the current state of all menu items and
  gadgets, the colors of the screen, as well as the internal variables@{ub},
  set from the '@{i}Set@{ui}' menu (@{i}threshold of aspects, orbs, ayanamsha@{ui}).

    Initial path/name of a settings file is @{b}ASense.config@{ub} in the same directory
  where the program resides.This can be changed to wherever/whatever you like
  by changing the 'CONFIG_FILE' tooltype string in the program's icon.This is
  usefull for example if you wish to keep the executables in a write protected
  area, and their scratch files (like a settings file) somewhere else.
    If you load/save from some other config file (option '..'), then next time
  you attempt a simple load/save (i.e. without the '..' requester), the config
  will be restored/saved to the last one that you selected with requester or
  to the root one (i.e. initial one) if this is empty.

    '@{i}@{b}Default@{ub}@{ui}' settings are an internal initial default.
    '@{i}@{b}Root@{ub}@{ui}' file is the user default config file, as pointed by the CONFIG_FILE.
@endnode
///
@remark Help
/// Help                                                  //f
@node ASENSE-MENUHELP "ASense - Menus: Help"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT MAIN
@{b}@{u}Help@{uu}@{ub}: Links to this and other guides.

  @{u}Examples@{uu}:
  - @{"Nikola Tesla" link ASENSE-EXAMPLES-TESLA}, inventor (biography) - @{"input string" link ASENSE-GADGETS-INPUT-STRING} filling example.
@endnode
///
///   Examples - Tesla                                    //f
@node ASENSE-EXAMPLES-TESLA "ASense - Examples: Nikola Tesla"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXT MAIN
@{b}@{u}Nikola Tesla, inventor@{uu}@{ub}:

  @{u}The most important discovery@{uu}: @{b}the (invisible) 'wheel'@{ub} of magnetic force.
  (??-Feb-1882 (Greg. cal.), sunset, Budapest, Hungary, data rating XX 0)

  He discovered the @{i}@{b}rotating magnetic field@{ub}@{ui}, which is the essence of the
  @{b}electric motor@{ub}, another one of his discoveries. He also discovered the
  @{b}alternating currency@{ub}, the @{b}radio@{ub}, and produced the @{b}first robot@{ub} in 1898.
  During 1903 he patented the basic principles of a @{b}logical circuit@{ub}.
  His other inventions are @{i}generators@{ui}, @{i}transformers@{ui}, @{i}motors@{ui}, @{i}turbines@{ui},...
  Tesla also left the legacy of unpublished ideas that he has claimed to
  have solved, the ideas that still puzzle the scientists today.The main
  ones are @{i}@{b}wireless transmission of power@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}free energy@{ub}@{ui} for everyone.

  @{u}Extraordinary abilities@{uu}:
  - @{b}ability to visualize the ideas in his mind so strongly, that he had
    never needed additional testing of equipment for experimental purposes@{ub}.
    Whatever he produced almost always worked flawlessly on the first run.
    (He could have make the error in choosing the correct material perhaps,
    but not in design, in principles upon which his machinery has relied.)
    Things simply kept assembling themselves in his head while he was doing
    some ordinary things like eating, talking, walking around or feeding the
    pigeons.When they were finished, he took some of them out and presented
    them to the world...
  - @{b}ability to sleep only 2 hours per day@{ub}.

  As an honour, @{b}unit for a @{i}density of magnetic flow@{ui}@{ub} (the @{i}@{b}magnetic induction@{ub}@{ui})
  @{b}bears his name@{ub} (@{i}tesla@{ui}): @{b}T = J / A = Wb / m˛@{ub}. This is a very large unit.
@endnode
